We are reliant on solid fuel as there is no has or oil. An air source heat pump would be ideal.

recently attended passivehaus training so really interested in being part of the sustainable movement and seeing the benefits on my energy consumption in practice

Sustainability_exp: I am very interested in the green angle. I am on my 3rd PHEV (awaiting funds for a full EV Tesla!) but am aware that my home is probably less green, but harder to upgrade.
Future_exp: Yes. I missed out on the FiTs scheme mainly due to house moves at the start of the scheme. PV used to be a negative selling point but this has now changed. Gas it not being installed in new properties from 2025 and we have a climate crisis that needs addressing.
Upgrade_exp: I am aware that the traditional h/w tank and gas boiler combo with a single room thermostat is very inefficient at heating the house as required. I also dont like my large gas bill.
Financial_exp: Although this sort of installation looks like having a good ROI, I would need to borrow to do it, and I have school fees to pay. I would hope this trial will prove the financial case for others.
Technology_exp: I am a bit of a techy and would love to have such technology in my house.
Research_exp: I have just joined OVO and would like to take this opportunity to do my part in supporting Plan Zero. I would like to show my 3 year old son I am doing my bit for his future.
Planned_exp: As stated above, I have thought about it, but until proven it would normally be too much of a  financial risk for me at this stage.
Replacement_exp: The boiler is 8 years old, and the rest is over 20 years old. I am having issues with valves and always feel as though I dont control it!

Sustainability_exp: Where I live the only option is oil but Im keen to explore other more sustainable alternatives to oil which is also quite smelly in the garden by the tank
Upgrade_exp: My current oil fired boiler is about 23rd years old and wont last forever. Id be very interested in learning more about heat pumps rather than replacing like for like as long as heat pumps can cope with our cold winters.
Building_exp: I am currently refurbishing the house and looking to replace flooring and carpets soon.
Financial_exp: Well who wouldnt be but Id also still be interested in learning more about carbon neutral options even if I wasnt successful.
Technology_exp: Im intrigued by the technology but dont really want to turn my house into a "smart" home. Carbon reduction appeals, automation doesnt.
Planned_exp: Ive got quotes for changing to a heat pump but aside from the costs the advice has been conflicting so until this trial I had decided to just defer the decision until my current boiler fails.

Sustainability_exp: As a graduate of environmental sciences and a champion of climate and environmental issues holding a senior position within Ovo I am absolutely committed to helping deliver zero Carbon living and leading by example and helping this critical cause
Future_exp: I am constantly looking at ways to improve efficiency at home to help reduce my carbon footprint. This opportunity represents the next step in my drive to having a zero carbon footprint.
Upgrade_exp: My current heating system is circa 20-30 years old and needs a complete overhaul. I was planning on doing this earlier in the year but covid and this amazing opportunity made me pause.
Building_exp: As above. My heating system is already ear marked to be replaced and this represents an amazing solution to improve my environmental impact
Financial_exp: I would not be able to afford this technology and would have to go for a more traditional improvement that would support my drive to reduce carbon but not at the level of the heat pump
Technology_exp: Anything like this That moves humanity forward interests me. What an opportunity to make a difference and help research going forward
Research_exp: Having an academic background in environmental sciences any research and development that I can at take in is a great opportunity to contribute to one of the most important issues facing mankind
Planned_exp: As above having looked into the solution I would have to opt for a cheaper more traditional upgrade which would be really disappointing
Replacement_exp: As above, my system was due to be upgraded prior to this opportunity and covid came along

Sustainability_exp: I work for a zero carbon company and would like to play my part in reducing my own personal carbon footprint by embracing new greener initiatives as they become available.
Future_exp: Installing this system would be beneficial; even if I were to sell my property the next occupants would benefit from the new system which would probably be a unique selling point. My family are keen to upgrade our appliances to energy efficient products when they need replacing and the same ethos applies to the way we view our home.
Upgrade_exp: My current system is nearly 10 years old now and works perfectly fine but a new heat pump will allow me to take full advantage of a more efficient system whilst becoming more environmentally friendly.
Building_exp: If successful then I would change part of my property around and install a walk in shower where the current airing cupboard is located.
Financial_exp: Being free of charge is brilliant as allows me a system that I could not afford otherwise whilst also improving the energy efficiency of my home.
Technology_exp: I always want to improve the technology in my property as newer technology normally means more savings and better energy efficiency. I believe technology is the way forward.
Research_exp: I am keen to take part as the role I work in involves the installation of smart meters. This would give me an insight into the effectiveness of new energy technologies which could help me give advice to the customers I visit during my normal day.
Planned_exp: Will be eventually but due to the prohibitive costs; until my current boiler stops working I will keep it.
Replacement_exp: Our current system is still working ok.it is just not as efficient as modern technology and will eventually need replacing with whatever is affordable.

Sustainability_exp: I have been trying to reduce my familys impact on the environment for many years without any major lifestyle changes. We dont do air travel, we cycle often, and recycling lots of things beyond the usual.
Future_exp: I am aware that gas heating needs and will be phased out.  I am keen to do this as soon as we can.   We have lived here 16 years and expect to live here for the rest of our lives (40 yrs+), so we do look at home improvements as long term investments.
Financial_exp: Replacement of the heating system not something we could usual afford.  I would like any upgrade of heating system to cost less or little more than our Gas, so having free installation would go a long way to achieve this.
Technology_exp: From what I understand about Heat pumps I think the house would suit it and that we would be able to alter the way we heat and use hot water to suit it.
Research_exp: I am very happy to support any research project  that can help guild how the technology can be best used, and households can most easily adapt to use it.
Planned_exp: "Planning"? As soon as the current gas boiler needs replacing or it is economical  to yes.

Sustainability_exp: I cycle rather than drive whenever possible. I�m re-wilding my garden, and guerrilla planting on the adjacent railway embankment. I compost everything I possibly can. I recycle everything I possibly can. I source my food locally wherever possible. But, I need help with making the house greener.
Future_exp: What I really want is to be energy self sufficient, which is obviously easier said than done. I work at home, so it�s really important that I do my bit because working at home is far less energy efficient than being in the office. I�ve started, by putting in good windows for example, but I�ve got a long way to go.
Upgrade_exp: I have a combi boiler, it works great but I have to burn gas. I also have a fireplace, which I love and hate in equal measure because of the environmental impact. I have a big garden which seems perfectly suited to a heat pump.
Building_exp: It�s an old house, so it�s an ongoing project.
Financial_exp: Of course, but it�s not my primary reason for being interested, this is something I�ve been looking at for a while.
Technology_exp: Totally. I love smart home tech and how it helps me reduce my carbon footprint.
Research_exp: Tell me what you want from me in return! I�ll support whatever I can if it helps the wider adoption of this type of technology.
Planned_exp: It�s in my thoughts but I don�t have an active plan.

Sustainability_exp: I love new technology and linking that with reducing our family carbon footprint is something that really excites me. A few year back I attended a talk on air source heat pumps and it opened my eyes to other possibilities for heating my house. Since then I have been assessing how our family can reduce our impact and save money.
Future_exp: Our gas boiler is 20 years old and I assume will need replacing in the next 10 years. Rather than look at another gas boiler I would love to move this to a greener alternative. I am also looking at solar panels and battery storage so moving to an green electric system would massively reduce our family environmental impact.
Upgrade_exp: My gas boiler is 20 years old and so moving to another gas boiler would feel wrong given the alternatives. A heat pump would solve two problems, replace the older boiler and remove the need for us to use gas.
Financial_exp: I still have children living at home so disposable income is not easy to come by. To replace the existing boiler would require a large loan so if I it can be replaced while providing valuable data for other households then it would benefit me financially, the government with valuable data and the environment.
Technology_exp: I work in the IT industry and have always loved new technology. Where the technology is not too expensive I am keen to introduce it my house. This includes smart thermostat, smart meters. The technology behind heat pumps is fascinating, I have one friend who already has a air source heat pump. It is only cost that has prevented me from pursuing this.
Research_exp: I think my house would provide valuable data. It is relatively modern and I have sufficient space to accommodate a heat pump. I believe it would prove how amazing heat pumps are and that a reasonably sized house can still achieve huge savings.
Planned_exp: I am not in a position to purchase one but if my current boiler were to break (20 years old) I think it would be the only sensible choice. I do not have the spare money to do this without borrowing the money so it would only be on a need basis.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is 20 years and burns a lot of gas. I would love to replace it with a greener alternative and save money.

Sustainability_exp: I am eager to embrace renewable technologies and reduce my impact on the environment. I am planning to have the house refurbished and this would be an ideal opportunity to experiment!
Future_exp: "Future proofing" the investment would be a bonus. A successful low carbon heating system, that would influence others to do the same, would be the main aim.
Upgrade_exp: Having looked at various alternatives, a heat pump seems the obvious choice.
Building_exp: As mentioned before, I am having the house refurbished and would see this as an ideal time to make changes.
Technology_exp: I have read about the technologies available and am keen to try them out.
Research_exp: I am more than happy to take your advice and run with it. I would give you any feedback needed and I see this as an opportunity to test new technology that could make a difference.
Planned_exp: It is a consideration but the cost is restrictive.

Upgrade_exp: just recently upgraded boiler but radiators are old and inefficient
Technology_exp: no personal expertise but every problem needs a technological answer
Other_exp: Encourage family to be part of scheme

Sustainability_exp: Keen to help environment and interested
A move away from Natural Gas for heating is critical for a more sustainable future and energy system

My wife and I do not intend on moving again so this house will need to be for for the next 50 years. That means carbon neutral which means an air source heat pump(not enough land for ground) under floor heating and a green energy provider. I am also very interested in the subject and would love to be a part of the project that could turn our ageing  housing stock in to a world leader.
Future_exp: This is vital for all of us. The west has lead the world into this climate crisis and it is our moral duty to do everything  we can to lead it out again.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pumps are the only way. Storage heaters are too inefficient and so called blue hydrogen impractical as the gas system will leak loads if you put the smaller hydrogen molecule into the pipes.
Building_exp: The insulation  has to be top notch so we are investigating replacing our existing loft conversion in the bungalow
Financial_exp: As stated  above I consider these measures something  that must be done. If it can be done early at less cost and be an inspiration to others that is a massive win.
Technology_exp: I consider it my duty to decarbonise my live and home. We changed to an induction job from gas. Next big thing is going to be the gas boiler and then car.
Research_exp: This is the future. For us all for our nation  otherwise... the alternative is too bleak to type but it is an existential  issue. We need to stop as many tipping points being triggered as fast as possible.
Planned_exp: Heat pump tech is the only viable  option to domestic  heat unless you happen to have handy geothermal. If this project allows  me to decarbonise my life and inspire others to do so it would be amazing
Replacement_exp: I have an old gas boiler that needs to be replaced, if I can move away from gas early it would be amazing

Sustainability_exp: As a parent of two young children, Im ever more conscious of what the world will look like when they reach adulthood and the type of natural challenges they might inherit. Whilst we try as a family to manage our own environmental footprint (fewer car trips, buying fewer products with plastic packaging etc.) it is not always easy to be sure that are efforts are actually having a meaningful impact. I believe this scheme will certainly go a long way in helping contribute in a significant, particularly given the age of our property.
Future_exp: Given the age of the house (over 100 years), this is a great opportunity to upgrade the overall heating system to ensure it can handle future changes in broader technology and regulatory requirements for energy efficiency
Financial_exp: This is a significant investment and given the current economic climate I would not be able to make this transition without the government support
Technology_exp: As mentioned, as a family we are always considering ways we can adjust our lifestyle and adopt new methods to minimise our carbon footprint. I do not know anyone with this technology installed, so it would be great to have this installed to see how it works and understand the benefits it could provide others.
Research_exp: Id be happy to provide additional support to the programme as required in the coming years

Future_exp: I am currently going through the process of a house extension and energy efficiency improvements (or wishing to!) but have been frustrated by the lack of easy information and ability to achieve the next level set of improvements to our existing very inefficient and older home to bring it up to modern and environmentally friendly, low-energy standards.
Upgrade_exp: I have already investigated ground source heat pumps as a great fit for planned underfloor heating needs however did not manage to make sufficient information or progress to confidently proceed.
Building_exp: I have planning permission and builder engaged for an extension and set of improvements to our property and would live to maximise this opportunity to improve the energy efficiency of our home.
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt be?! I would be a keen and engaging participant for the trial but ultimately this is something I have always planned to do and if I can help prove some of the technologies and processes involved to make this more wide-spread that would be great.
Technology_exp: As mentioned, I have already explore GSHP, insulation and numerous other technologies to see what options are available for improving a residential property.  I think the home heating battery is an amazing idea to get around heat storage and energy availability concerns people have.
Research_exp: Other than personal passion and interest for my home and energy efficiency, I have already been an early adopter for Smart Meter SMETS1 & SMETS2 trials run in my area, to help me understand my usage better.  Being able to prove efficiency savings based on specific changes made would provide great insight that could help engage and persuade others to make similar changes.
Planned_exp: As mentioned, I have investigated this already for our extension but have been put off by the industry contacts I was able to engage with (with difficulty) who recommended against GSHP due to the relatively small scale involved.

Replacement_exp: In the next few years - there are no parts available for our boiler, if it breaks we need to replace the whole thing.

Sustainability_exp: We originally switched to OVO many years ago because of its green credentials, and see the zero carbon heating trial as an excellent opportunity for our family to reduce our carbon emissions still further. Our gas heating system is over 20 years old, so Im convinced it would make a huge improvement. Ive pestered my wife for the last few years about how Id like to change to an air source heat pump, electric car, solar panels the list goes on, but having the spare funds to actually be able to do these things has been the sticking point. The Zero Carbon Heating Trial would be a huge help and I could finally stop nagging my wife!
Future_exp: We all know fossil fuels wont be available forever. With primary age children, we will potentially be in this house for the next 15+ years and would like to be running the most efficient system possible during those years. This will do the right thing for the environment and inspire the next generation (our children) to continue using low carbon technologies into the future.
Upgrade_exp: My existing heating system (gas boiler) is approximately 20 years old so is in dire need of upgrading. It is probably only about 60% efficient, whereas a heat pump could be 300-400% efficient depending on the time of year.
Financial_exp: Were a family of four, with two school-aged children (8 and 6), so were used to budgeting and saving a little away each month. A free heat pump system would certainly be appreciated, and could free up some savings to maybe replace our 10 year old petrol car with a second-hand electric car much sooner, reducing our carbon footprint still further.
Technology_exp: I have probably spent far too many hours watching YouTube videos about renewable energy and heat pumps, and the speed of development in this field is impressive. With modern refrigerants being less harmful to the environment, it seems like a good time to adopt heat pump technology. I would be interested to see what the engineers would specify for our house (e.g. whether a monoblock or split system would be most appropriate).
Research_exp: We need to get the whole country to decarbonise, and I think being able to share real-world experience of zero carbon solutions is going to play a critical part in the wider public acceptance and adoption instead of existing fossil fuels. Robust research into how best to deploy and use heat pumps across the wide variety of UK housing stock is going to be crucial.
Planned_exp: I believe our gas boiler is the original installed when the house was built in the late 1990s, so its now over 20 years old. Its got to be pretty inefficient and we really dont want to replace it with another gas boiler. Having an Air Source Heat Pump would be a massive improvement, and we could demonstrate to skeptical friends, family and neighbours that low or zero carbon heating really is possible or effective as a retrofit option, not just for new build homes.
Replacement_exp: Like all families with children we use a lot of hot water, and this demand on heat will only increase once they become teenagers. As well as replacing our 20+ year old gas boiler, Id really like to upgrade our old 140 litre hot water cylinder for one of the amazing space saving Sunamp Uniq Heat Batteries. Since I first saw them being demonstrated on an episode of Fully Charged Ive been convinced this is a brilliant solution for greater overall heat capacity in a smaller package. Plus, we could finally get rid of the noisy water pump for our showers, as the Sunamp works with mains water pressure. Brilliant.

Sustainability_exp: Climate change is on of our biggest challenges to solve through global agreement and local and individual action. As a recent father, I want a world where my daughter can experience the natural world whilst understanding humans limits through sustainable development.
Future_exp: Household carbon and emissions are one of the large and significant gaps to stopping Britain meeting its SDGs and Climate accord commitments.
Upgrade_exp: Its a sustainable low carbon solution.
Building_exp: Our house is a 1939s detached house, typical of our area. It hasnt beenodernised for several years and could be a great example to sustainable living to the average householder.
Financial_exp: As a charity worker with limited resources and a stay at home partner we are unable to spend vast amounts modernising our house.in the foreseeable future.
Technology_exp: New technology and innovation is.one of humanities greatest gifts and our only solution to solving climate change.
Research_exp: Although not academic by background, Ive seen first hand the benefits of evidence base to male change happen.
Replacement_exp: Albeit my heating does seem insufficient.

Measures_Recommend: Loft Insulation; Wall insulation; Window replacement; Door replacement; Draft Proofing

At the moment I have two gas fires that stay on all winter to heat the house. With a new heating system this will reduce my heating bill and save on my carbon footprint.

Upgrade_exp: I�m not a fan of burning fossil fuel and would like an alternative.
Financial_exp: Not only is this a great opportunity but would hopefully contribute to further funding and essential feedback.
Technology_exp: I always try to keep up to date in the latest technology for the benefit of reducing my carbon footprint and helping to contribute to helping the planet from global warming.
Planned_exp: Hadn�t heard of this technology before now so am keen to be part of the trial.
Replacement_exp: As I said before gas fires burn a lot of energy and this would be my opportunity to rectify this and help with the project at the same time.

Sustainability_exp: I do what I can to reduce waste, recycle where possible and would like to extend this to my heating system.
Upgrade_exp: I have been told my boiler may need replacing in the near future and feel it would be a good time switch to a more renewable heating system
Building_exp: I had my timber suspended floors downstairs insulated a couple of years ago and am looking to replace my front door which opens straight into the living room and possibly enclose the porch in order to preserve heat.
Financial_exp: I am on a low income as a self-employed artist and I have been using life savings to carry out energy saving works such as insulating under floorboards.

Sustainability_exp: Home heating systems are a major source of carbon, so Id like to move to a low-carbon system. If we can power this from certified 100% renewable energy in future, perhaps boosted by a solar panel, then that would be ideal.
Future_exp: Yes, that would be nice, but thats not my main motive. The technology installed now will be superseded, or quickly improved, anyway. For example, Ecodan heat pumps could become a lot smaller or quieter. So I dont think this is mainly about future proofing. This is a trial after all, and we dont know the results.
Upgrade_exp: The heating system we have -- a 7-year old Worcester-Bosch condenser combi boiler combined with a Hive thermostat -- is actually very efficient. It controls the temperature in the house quite accurately, and were careful about scheduling temperatures according to need. The system still has plenty of life in it. So were not looking for a way to upgrade as such. But we are interested in reducing carbon and encouraging everyone in the country to do so.
Building_exp: Maybe the opposite is true. We didnt have any plans for refurbishment, but we might make some changes if were accepted for the trial, depending on what the installation involves.
Financial_exp: Im not sure how anyone can honestly answer "no" to this question. How can the offer of a new heating system free of charge be unattractive, even if there are caveats?
Technology_exp:
Definitely. Three points of interest here:
1. How well can low-carbon heat pumps work to heat an ordinary 3-bed house like ours.
2. What will the heating controls be like: Im interested in precise controls as a way people can save energy and make a big impact in reducing carbon.
3. Most interesting: how will my home system (and maybe electric car, when I can afford one!) talk to the evolving smart grid through the Kaluza system.
Research_exp: For all the reasons mentioned above.
Planned_exp: Weve thought about changing to a heat pump but theyre still prohibitively expensive, so this is a great opportunity. So weve thought about it, but no, not planning.
Replacement_exp: No, we werent planning to replace our heating system right now. As mentioned above, our heating system (Worcester-Bosch combi boiler + Hive thermostat) is very efficient and still has plenty of life in it -- 7 years old.

Sustainability_exp: Since OVO has taken over SSE i have been getting more and more interested in Plan Zero and my impact on the planet. I have started making changes to the things i do, and reduce my impact. This is just another big step towards that.

Upgrade_exp: As previously mentioned, i need to replace my boiler (have needed to since we moved in) but would like to reduce my carbon footprint whilst doing it.
Building_exp: I have recently been having work completed on the house and there is still things left to do, so disruption wouldnt be an issue... You dont fix leaking roofs as well do you? lol
Financial_exp: I am not going to lie this is also a factor in applying, but even if i had to contribute i would be happy to do so.
Technology_exp: "I love and technology and  new advances in the way we do things. \nEspecially if they help to reduce our impact on the planet, seems like a win-win to me :)"

Replacement_exp: Had no idea this question was coming!\nMy current combi boiler has needed replaced for the last 3 years (since we moved in) but we have been doing other things to the house. This came up and i saw it as a great opportunity to get it replaced for something far more efficient.

A keen recycling family, we have invested in an electric vehicle to reduce our carbon footprint.  We are extremely interested in achieving a zero-carbon status as soon as possible.
Future_exp: Friends in Germany have installed heat pump technology and we have seen how efficient it can be.  Although our house is only 12 years old its time to consider upgrading our gas heating system and the obvious replacement technology is heat pump based.
Upgrade_exp: The technology, although in use to a much greater extent on the continent, needs a boost here in the UK.  By offering our house as an exemplar, we achieve both goals:  a carbon saving heating system and an example to others in our neighbourhood.
Building_exp: although we are happy with the structure and decoration of our house, an upgraded heating system would enhance our personal view of it.

Technology_exp: We have seen more modern carbon-free / Neutral domestic systems in friend houses in Germany.  As a result, we have no fear of technology. Research_exp: For all of the reasons above - and the intrigue of participating in something which moves the UK forward to the advantage of us all.
Planned_exp: Im afraid the expense is too much at our stage of life.

We already use 100% renewable electricity, and would like to move to completely "green" energy as part of our contribution to reducing environmental impact.

Reliance on fossil fuels also decrease by adapting this heating method so everyone wins! I am a positive person and would seek to shout about the benefits the system would bring along with learning more about the other changes I could make to support a better world.

Im sure this is possible but requires a bespoke design.
Upgrade_exp: I always enjoy Grand Designs" type programmes as they identify modern alternatives to sustainable living such as ground & air heat pumps utilising heat exchange as well home power generation, improved insulation and low power consumption devices such as LEDs that we have throughout the house. oUr smart meter is an objective measure of power utilisation and helps identify sensible management strategies. Our boiler was an efficient solution (Valliant EcoPro) in 2010, but technology moves on.
Building_exp: I have been working through the house and enjoy planned DIY and have the whole building recorded in my CAD system. The next project is insulation within the integral double garage including new insulated tight fitting garage door. I havent given up on a Photo Cell solution as we have  a considerable south facing aspect with the potential to a full width logia supporting such cells without shade.
Financial_exp: Due to COVID 19 both our children (25 & 27) having acquired degrees and started in work, no longer have full employment and poor prospects for the near future, so we are still supporting them totally as they do not wish to take from the state. So home developments. no matter how sensible in the long term are currently on the back burner, this would enable me to move forward sooner and acquire knowledge for our church project at St Johns Hartley Wintney having already project managed a restoration there including energy saving technology, they now wish to capitalise on current grants to lower their carbon foot print and allocate more funding to charitable causes rather than running costs for the Victorian church and Church centre that serves the whole community not just Christians.
Technology_exp: I managed an Imaging Department within the NHS, then worked 30 years for Siemens Healthcare in London and nationally always looking for efficient solutions that brought the most good to patients and the operating staff. This industry needed to transform and reduce radiation contamination required for both treatment and diagnosis as well as reduced running costs (greater efficiency through well designed technology). So I have always been interested and passionate about well designed solutions ideal for their purpose and looking at the bigger picture. Ethical, efficient and desirable.
Research_exp: It is by taking part one can gain knowledge, consider fully the benefits and help others save our planet for our children and their children. Credibility is key in influencing others based on experience, knowledge and empathy. Understanding a the solution and how it best fits into each scenario as I presume you are looking to do with this survey.

This funded opportunity brings that possibility from 5 years to imminent.

We did the same with our last house, and I hope to do the same with this Victorian house, this time going a lot further (with OVOs help). I also really love a warm house and am very conscious of the impact that has on our bills and the environment.
Upgrade_exp: The boiler is definitely the part of the house that sees the most action in our house. We have four floors which requite a lot of heating, the prospect of using a device that can heat our home from ambient temperatures from outside is really exciting.
Building_exp: We bought this house in January and knew it needed a bit of work. But I dont think we were prepared for the lack of insulation, the holes in the walls, the holes in the roof (weve just had it fixed). We recently replaced the double glazing, but the house needs to be fully draft proofed. We have had some people come in to quote for the green homes grant who recommended boxing in our room in the roof with insulation and plastering, Celotex insulation in both lofts, underfloor insulation in the lounge-diner and replacing the patio doors and bathroom windows with double glazing.
Financial_exp: Weve already spent quite a lot of money on the house this year (new windows, ceilings, roof repairs, doing the kitchen up), so anything OVO can do to help would be really appreciated. But for me its less about the money and more about the fact that I trust OVO and I trust that they will use a respected company to install the systems. This sort of tech is quite new and not very many companies are doing it.

You only need to look at our Kitchen (which weve nearly finished doing up) to see this aesthetic (I can send pics).

Sustainability_exp: I am a committed environmentalist. My career is in the field of domestic energy efficiency so I am familiar with the scale of challenges in the domestic sector as we pursue net-zero emissions. I want to be able to walk-the-walk in terms of the impacts of my activities. I recognise that fossil fuel heating must be phased out to achieve our aims and am keen to contribute to research that facilitates this.
Future_exp: I recognise that heating homes in the future must not use fossil fuels and heat pumps are part of the mix of solutions. Im aware that they operate best in well insulated homes with low temperature emitters and so my intention would be to install underfloor heating as part of this project, insulating my ground floor as part of the process.
Upgrade_exp: My gas boiler is fully operational however it is over 25 years old and I would like to upgrade to a more efficient system within the next few years. Without the opportunity presented by this project I would likely wait until the current boiler breaks and would likely replace it with a condensing gas boiler which would lock in the use of fossil fuels for at least another 15 years. This presents an opportunity for me to make the transition to low carbon heat earlier than would otherwise be possible.
Building_exp: I am not planning building or refurbishment works although I would be keen to switch the distribution system to low flow temperature underfloor heating as part of this project and would insulate the floor as part of this. The project therefore presents an opportunity to upgrade the fabric efficiency of the property in a way that would not otherwise be done.
Financial_exp: I am of course attracted to the fact that the system will be provided free of charge however I am aware that there no guarantee of lower running costs, although with the other improvements I have mentioned to the fabric insulation I expect that this would be achieved.
Technology_exp: I am very familiar with heat pump technology through my work as a domestic energy efficiency researcher. I understand what a heat pump is, how it operates most effectively and what might be required in terms of behaviour change, for example to heating patterns. Im keen to adopt new technology and also to contribute to understanding how effective it can be in transitioning to low-carbon heat.
Research_exp: I have worked on similar research and monitoring projects through my job at BRE. I understand the commitment level needed, the requirements of the research contractors and what makes a good research subject. Im also keen to do my bit to help the Government plan for a low carbon future.  As someone that works in domestic energy efficiency research I am particularly interested in this trial. I am knowledgeable about heat pumps, energy efficient behaviours and research studies such as this and I believe that I can provide good evidence about what is achievable with the technology.
Planned_exp: My current mains gas boiler is over 25 years old therefore I expect to have to change it within the next few years however without the opportunity presented by this project I would likely replace it with a modern gas boiler, locking in the use of fossil fuels for at least another 15 years.
Replacement_exp: My current mains gas boiler is over 25 years old therefore I expect to have to change it within the next few years. I would also take the opportunity to upgrade the distribution system to future-proof it for a low flow temperature system so that heat pumps can operate most efficiently.
