Upgrade_exp: Our existing oil boiler is old and inefficient, we are considering ways to upgrade the system and ideally reduce our carbon output. We have looked at many options from condensing oil boilers, to biomass and heat pumps. Heat pumps seem a great way to meet our aims and we have space for either ground or air source systems.
Building_exp: We are planning some building works next year, we have granted planning permission and are currently getting structural calculations for building control. The work would include moving, or ideally replacing the boiler with a new heat source.
Financial_exp: We need a new boiler at present and whilst heat pumps are attractive, they are currently cost prohibitive, so the fact this would provide a greener alternative is very attractive
Technology_exp: We are always keen to adopt new technology, once proven, and cost efficient. Heat pumps have been in use for many years now and their price is dropping so we are keen to see a system in action at our property
Research_exp: With the aim of reducing reliance on fossil fuels, highly efficient electric heating systems using energy from renewable sources seems the obvious solution. We would be proud to be taking part in a project to help make them more widely available
Planned_exp: Whilst we have looked ta pumps, the purchase and installation cost is prohibitive, so being selected as part of this research would be fantastic as we could change to the technology we would choose, were we to have the funds
Replacement_exp: Our oil boiler is 40+ years old so is not efficient by todays standards. With the volatile price of heating oil another energy source would be preferable, but our property is not on the gas grid, LPG is very expensive, as is all electric heating. A heat pump would be an ideal solution, although is cost prohibitive at full price

Sustainability_exp: I�m looking to eliminate the use of gas from my home and move to all electric.  Thereby allowing me to move to generating my own electricity and becoming carbon free and hopefully carbon negative by producing more than I consume
Future_exp: Moving to an electric boiler and self generating electricity
Upgrade_exp: It�s an option I�ve considered and I�m open to the idea
Building_exp: Been in the new house and extensive refurbishment is underway, the heating system is still up for debate and sourcing
Financial_exp: Even if it wasn�t, it�s probably still a direction I would travel just not maybe so quickly
Technology_exp: I�m an early adopter of most new tech
Research_exp: I like the way OVO take these things forward and would like to work with a reputable company like them
Replacement_exp: All working fine at the moment but keen to remove the gas supply to enable a move to carbon zero

Sustainability_exp: I�m an environmentalist and work in the sustainability sector. I live a low carbon lifestyle as far as possible. I�m aware of the challenges of rolling out low carbon heat across existing housing stock and would like to be part of the trial to help make that happen at scale!
Future_exp: As above & my house is efficient as it can be within our means
Building_exp: We�re renovating our kitchen which is the most likely place to be home to the heat pump and related kit. If the boiler is going that would change the nature of our renovations.
Financial_exp: Our budget is limited so this would allow us to do more than we thought possible
Technology_exp: As before - I�m aware we need to massively change our energy systems and heat is a big challenge.
Planned_exp: We don�t have the means to do so

Sustainability_exp: I am a keen practitioner of recycling and saving energy. I feel that there is too much energy being wasted all over the world in both home and workplaces and more could easily be done to curb that usage.
Future_exp: Absolutely, I like being at the forefront of technology. I have a keen interest in automation and saving costs within my house.
Upgrade_exp: I feel a heat pump would be a great way to showcase the easy steps that can be taken in order to save not only costs but also energy as well.
Building_exp: No building refurbishment is planned in the near future.
Financial_exp: Of course, but I am heavily interested in the technology regardless.
Technology_exp: I work as an IT Infrastructure Engineer and love all things technical. I also heavily automated my home as a hobby as well. I feel that given both these things I would be ideal to trial this system as I could provide feedback from a technical/objective viewpoint and could easily communicate both the positive and negative aspects of using the system.
Research_exp: I would love the support and take part in the trial of new technology and be seen as an early adopter to try to bring more people around into expanding their home heating systems.
Planned_exp: I am not planning this in the immediate future but it could plan medium/long term.
Replacement_exp: My heating systems do not need replacement although it has been in this house for a number of years and thus will be due to be replaced in the medium future.

Upgrade_exp: I do not know enough about heat pumps to know that they are the way forward, although open to them as have heard of the positives

Sustainability_exp: I work for OVO and fully committed to wanting a zero carbon footprint and the biggest starting point for me to make that happen is the fossil fuels I use to heat my home.
Future_exp: I want to be part of a world which doesnt require relying on gas and external electricity supply.
Financial_exp: I think this would give me the confidence to share how good the technology is to others and I would struggle to afford it otherwise.
Technology_exp: I love smart technology. I have a fully Google integrated system
Replacement_exp: My system is old and makes sense to change is properly

Sustainability_exp: Im a keen supporter of green initiatives, backed by science, that help with cleaning the environment for mine and the future of the next generation. we need to act now to slow emissions
Future_exp: i would like to make the future       something achievable now at least in having a low carbon heating system fit for the next few decades
Upgrade_exp: Heating systems as far as Im aware are one of the most carbon intensive home appliances so it is an obvious system to be low emissions
Financial_exp: I could not afford this system if it not for the trial.
Technology_exp: Im keen to go the extra mile to embrace tech that is green
Research_exp: very happy to help with anything to do with green technology. It is a chance to do more for the environment.
Planned_exp: We have been researching heat pumps last year and luckily found out about the trial.
Replacement_exp: Our heating system is not working so we are using the wood burner for now.

Sustainability_exp: we have always been interested in reducing our environmental impact.  In our previous home we tried to do as much as possible fSC wood on our double glazing, cavity wall insulation and solar hot water.  Since OH has retired we have downsized and are looking at ways to "green" our new home which only has wall insulation.
Future_exp: Our current heating system is oil-fired, and we would like to move away from carbon fuel. We feel that this is the way forward for everyone if we are to do our bit for climate change.  If it has the added bonus of stabilising our energy costs that is a an advantage for us personally too.
Upgrade_exp: As part of our research for "greening" our energy usage we have have been considering heat pumps, particularly airsource heatpumps due to the installation costs and complexity of a groundsource system
Building_exp: The property was built in 1930s and is single glazed. It requires rewiring and all facilities need upgrading.  It  makes sense to make any change to the heating system while we are doing this work. Due to Covid we have been unable to progress this beyond our planning stage but hope to be able to get this moving fairly soon.
Financial_exp: We have investigated the cost of ASHP and we are aware that it will cost us in the region of �12k, which is a sizeable costs compared to replacing the current boiler.
Technology_exp: AS I said above we have used energy efficient tech in the past, d.g/ solar panels/cavity wall and sheep wool insulation in the loft.  We use Hive to control our current heating system and are comfortable with domestic tech/IT and are interested in it both in itself and for the benefits it can bring to us as as we get older.
Research_exp: We tend to keep records of the effect of changes to systems on our energy usage and costs.  This would be an interesting exercise
Planned_exp: If we are unsuccessful we may well chose to go down this route if we can fund it

Sustainability_exp: I am making as many changes in my life to reduce the carbon footprint of my household. This includes cutting out as much plastic packaging as possible and switching to a hybrid car.
Future_exp: I would like to be as low carbon as possible moving forward
Financial_exp: I would otherwise have to put off this type of work for a few years
Technology_exp: I am always interested in science and technology improving the way we live
Research_exp: I am keen to be involved in anything that furthers a more environmentally conscious approach to the way we live

Sustainability_exp: I have 2 electric vehicles and am on a green energy tariff but want to go off grid if possible. I am confused about how to invest my green pound for best effect, I have researched Solar PV, BATTERY, ASHP, GSHP, SAHP but haven�t invested in any of these technologies. Meanwhile I have tried to reduce carbon footprint as much as I can via LEDs , insulation,  low energy devices etc
Future_exp: See above I want to go off grid as far as I can affird
Upgrade_exp: We have underfloor heating powered by an 8 year old gas boiler and a well insulated house.
Financial_exp: Justifying investment in ASHP on a ROI basis has been difficult. As I am just approaching retirement I need to make the investment to get payback when I am on a lower income
Technology_exp: I am an early adopter of new technologies for example I been driving Teslas for 5 years
Research_exp: I want to be an exemplar of how a fairly standard modern house can be adapted to go off grid
Planned_exp: Am in discussion with a GHI approved installer to get a quote for ASHP and Solar PV
Replacement_exp: The boiler is 8 years old and the controls are a bit archaic but the underfloor system is efficient

Sustainability_exp: The technology is there to make our housing more efficient, less wasteful, smarter & work better for us so why don�t we use it!
Future_exp: The only way to reduce our carbon impact is to make changes, one of these changes is making our houses more efficient
Upgrade_exp: I endeavour to make my house as efficient as possible but there is only so much that can be done whilst keeping the original central heating system.
Building_exp: I have been trying to make my home smarter through technology by using things such as WiFi controlled lights and heating as well as improving the living spaces of the house. The house is a shared environment for me and my family and if I can make it better I will

Sustainability_exp: Work for a sustainability charity so very driven to make my home as sustainable as possible.
Future_exp: Main thing I would like to do is get off gas.
Building_exp: Have recently bought a house with poor insulation and old heating system. Now looking to improve these.
Financial_exp: This is a huge advantage as means I can do more to make the property more sustainable, e.g. solar panels, which would otherwise not be possible with the budget I have.
Technology_exp: I belive that technology is huge step towards making our wor more sustainable.
Research_exp: I want to do my bit towards making a more sustainable future for us all.
Planned_exp: I am planning to, but further in the future as not 100% on what technology I need so need to do more research.
Replacement_exp: Boiler is 10 years old and have old ineffiecient radiators.

Sustainability_exp: We live in a 1930s semi and know it could be heated more efficiently the  a gas boiler but dont know what the best option is to retrofit the property
Future_exp: I work for a sustainability charity and know i should be doing more at home but I am not an energy expert.
Upgrade_exp: I think this might be the right solution for our property but need expert advice and support as it is a relatively new technology for retrofit.
Building_exp: We are slowly trying to improve the property and have been saving up to do some work to improve the property but want to also make sure we make it more energy efficient when we do this.
Financial_exp: We both work for charities but live in am expensive area so any help we can get to future proof the property would be really help especially if our house can be used as an example of how to retrofit an energy system in a 1930s semi.
Planned_exp: Without more advice we dont know if this is the right option.
Replacement_exp: We have an old boiler and some radiators need updating so making it all more efficient would be a really good approach.

Sustainability_exp: I work in sustainability and have done quite a bit already to improve my home and we are also car free. A heat pump would help us to do more to reduce our impacts
Future_exp: It is a positive step to be less reliant on fossil fuels and will help to reduce our energy bill.
Upgrade_exp: Although our boiler is four years old I am keen to move away from a fossil fuel heating system
Building_exp: We renovated our house a few years ago so are not currently renovating but understand there would be some disruption caused by having a heat pump installed
Financial_exp: We could not afford to upgrade our heating system without this grant. We have a young family and a single income so this would be massively helpful
Technology_exp: Absolutely, I work for a sustainability charity and love the idea of being able to speak first hand about more experience of having a low carbon homes
Research_exp: Research projects are so important to help us understand how best to retrofit the wide variety of housing types. We also need to understand how to support/persuade large numbers of households to adopt low carbon heating systems. We will be happy to be used as a case study, take part in any ongoing monitoring etc
Planned_exp: We have no current plans to upgrade our heating system due to the costs involved
Replacement_exp: Our heating system works well - it is about four years ild

Sustainability_exp: We are on a fully renewable electricity tariff and are keen to reduce our gas use as much as possible to combat climate change.
Future_exp: Everyone needs to do what they can so the whole country can become carbon neutral far sooner than the Governments 2050 target.
Upgrade_exp: We are having problems with our boiler and definitely dont want to replace it with last century technology!
Financial_exp: From the research we have done, it is unlikely we would be able to afford a heat pump without grant funding.
Technology_exp: We have seen pumps work well in a few different buildings and are keen to investigate if it would work for our home.
Research_exp: We would be delighted if this project not only helped reduce our own carbon footprint and bills but also helped others move to low carbon technology.
Replacement_exp: Heating system doesnt need replacing but we do have to fix it regularly!

Future_exp: I think this is the way we need to move forward to protect the planet
Upgrade_exp: This is a good opportunity to upgrade to a new more sustainable system
Building_exp: We have no plans as of yet to develop the property
Financial_exp: This is something we would not be able to afford to do ourselves, and its a way of us being able to become more sustainable, save energy therefore lower bills.
Technology_exp: I work for a sustainable charity and I am very interested in ways which I can adopt a one planet living plan
Research_exp: I am happy to provide stats so the systems can be monitor and maybe improved on
Planned_exp: As previously stated this is not something we could afford to do ourselves
Replacement_exp: We had a new boiler put in three years ago, but I like the idea of having newer greener more sustainable system

Upgrade_exp: I applied for the trial because \nI needed to replace my boiler. I had to go ahead as other options seemed too difficult to investigate; information that was reliable seemed hard to find. Being involved with a trial like this would help me feel I was getting the expert input I needed.
Financial_exp: I�m not asking for free system. I would like to take active steps to reduce my CO2
Planned_exp: I looked into this. Information that I felt was detailed enough, while reliable and impartial was hard to come by

Sustainability_exp: Ive worked in Demand Side Response for over 10 years providing Frequency Response. I have consulted for domestic DSR service providers. I have a Masters in environmental policy, in particular in Carbon Markets.
Future_exp: I want to be able to shift my heating to electricity. I am professionally developing Time of Use access to wholesale markets, targeting both low price arbitrage and low carbon periods. Id like this ability at home too!
Upgrade_exp: For the above reasons, I want more flexibility in my heating system, and to move to a lower carbon alternative.
Technology_exp: I am professionally aware of the benefits of a flexible heating system operated from the electricity network. I want to be able to optimise against TOU tariffs and the carbon intensity of the grid.
Research_exp: For the above reasons, I am very keen to take part in this project.
Planned_exp: A heat pump is on my list of priorities for home improvements.
Replacement_exp: My current gas boiler is in good working order.

Sustainability_exp: We try to do everything we can to reduce our environmental impact, from small things like buying recycled toilet roll with no plastic packaging and eco-bricking all the way up to the bigger things. We have recently switched to a fully electric car and already have a fully renewable electricity tariff. We would love to stop using gas so that we are completely fossil fuel free.
Future_exp: We had already started to research the options for installing a heat pump and as a result of this came across the details of the trial. In order to halt the climate crisis it is going to be necessary for us all to move to a new source of energy and someone needs to lead the way. It would be really exciting to be part of that process and contribute to the change.
Upgrade_exp: Our house still uses the original gas boiler and a hot water tank. If we do not install a heat pump then we will need to upgrade to a new boiler because it is inefficient and no longer supported by the manufacturer. Instead of replacing it with another gas boiler it seems to be the right time to upgrade to a greener technology.
Financial_exp: Our main motivation is to help reduce our environmental impact, the money saving is simply a bonus.
Technology_exp: I am not someone who is particularly keen on technology itself, but I am interested in innovations which relate directly to the environment and have no qualms about moving to a new system.
Research_exp: I believe that in order to make positive changes to help combat the climate crisis it is important for some people to take a risk and be early adopters of new technology. these early adopters can then help to spread the word and provide real-life examples of how we can do things differently.
Planned_exp: We have made initial enquiries about switching to a heat pump with several local companies. Registering interest in the trial came about as part of that research.
Replacement_exp: Our current gas boiler is no longer supported so will need to be replaced (see previous answer)

Sustainability_exp: Feel very strongly we as a species need to move faster on this - we have an electric car on order, would like to make our house greener, would like to help this area of the economy get to a green future faster - if by experiencing some disruption ourselves and living with consequences, we can help make the experience of greening better for others we feel like we would be doing our bit!!
Financial_exp: Not really - nervous about having our currently functioning system messed about with - but other principles override this!
Technology_exp: I understand that heat pumps produce 3kWh for every 1kWh used - this seems amazing.

Sustainability_exp: The potential impact of global warming on humankind could be disaterous. What is more worrying is that the environment seems to be changing in line with the worst case scenario as modelled by scientists. Urgent actions is required. But the good news is that the technology to address many of the problems already exist. It is a matter of will and investment.
Future_exp: We can sometimes feel helpless against this force of nature, yet we can improve the C02 footprint of our own property. This generational problem can only be solved one step at a time.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pump combined with renewable power is the way ahead.
Financial_exp: It is good that the government has taken the initiative to drive the adoption of heat pumps. We need more early adopters to act as ambassadors for this technology.
Technology_exp: As an engineer, I am always intrigued by new ideas or applications of concepts.
Research_exp: Heat pumps work, but I expect there is scope to optimise their operation in a range of building types. Especially when they are combined with other measures.
Planned_exp: My gas boiler had started to become unreliable a few years ago. I was considering replacing it with a heat pump then, however my wife was diagnosed with cancer, so I went for the easy option and got a new high efficiency boiler fitted. BTW - she is fine now.
Replacement_exp: Having solved my original problem (see above), and having invested in a new gas boiler, I was less inclined to explore the options. However this scheme creates a new incentive to look again.

Sustainability_exp: I am a long term environmentalist but live in a house in the country with oil fired central heating and no viable area to locate any other source of renewable energy e.g. photovoltaic panels.  Run a Hybrid car and considering electric car for next vehicle.
Future_exp: With oil prices so volatile and committed to a carbon neutral future I want to do all I can to establish the medium term future of the property in a lower carbon way.  I believe that this form of heating is the next best thing I can do to achieve a better carbon footprint especially at a time I an my wife are spending more time due to Covid at home.
Upgrade_exp: My current heating system is oil fired, inefficient and not very environmentally sound.  I am concerned it may fail at some point in the not too distance future as it does regularly suffer intermittent failures.
Financial_exp: The cost of a this sort of system is out of my budget at the moment and the cost of heating our house is increasing.  The only way I will be able to adopt this type of system in the near future is if it was provided for free.  Otherwise I would have to carry on with the current system for the next 5+ years.
Technology_exp: I work in technology so am very keen to always adopt new technology particularly where it has a better environmental impact.
Research_exp: I have worked with OVO Energy as a supplier in the past and know that you are a real innovator in the market and that was what attracted me to apply to be part of this research project.
Planned_exp: I would like to change to heat pump but I cant afford it at the moment so this is the ideal opportunity.

Sustainability_exp: OVO have just purchased the company I work for, I am truly inspired by Plan Zero and want to go Zero and try it out
Future_exp: As my background is creative and electrical engineering, I have always been keen to try out new technologies especially those that can be of extreme benefit
Upgrade_exp: People have always burnt things to keep warm , to become zero carbon we need stop doing this and use natural resources to capture heat or generate heat through renewable energy
Building_exp: We are due to start building an attached garage with an annex above it. We are keen to make this as insulated and low carbon as possible . Using electric heating powered by renewables or heat pump
Financial_exp: I am keen to take part in trials and bring alive new technologies and comfortable with this trial being subsidised
Technology_exp: I am a creative and ideas person with a technical background, I have always been keen to try the latest things and be an early adopter and share it with others and make suggestions as to how things could be improved
Research_exp: Whilst people have tried these technologies before I feel that the OVO project is delivering at the right time and people are ready to make a difference and change the world - I want to be part of that
Planned_exp: We are considering it as part of the building works
Replacement_exp: The heating system is inadequate for the house, poorly designed with one thermostat and onefficient

Sustainability_exp: One of the main reasons for moving ovo was the green and sustainable options on offer. Signing up to better options when available
Future_exp: I am keen to do my part to help reduce my carbon foot print as soon as I can and for my familys future
Building_exp: We are updating aspects of the interior to the house (kitchen) and believe this is an opportunity to upgrade other aspects of it too.
Financial_exp: Its an opportunity to get a excellent carbon neutral system that we couldnt afford at this time.
Technology_exp: Always interested new and exciting technologies
Research_exp: If this project can give useful information moving forward, all the better
Planned_exp: We have been looking into the possabilty of a heat pump as a possible option when upgrading

Sustainability_exp: I currently spend �210 per month on electricity and �160 per month from October through to end of April on solid fuel. As I am 61 and my partner is 66 in November we are nearing an age when managing a solid fuel system is hard work and additionally I consider that I am in a fuel poverty situation as well as it being inefficient.
Upgrade_exp: I have 3.5 acres of land behind my house. I envisage it being ideal for ground source heat pump.
Financial_exp: I am not in a position to pay for this outright due to being in fuel poverty.
Research_exp: This is my dream to future proof my home.
Planned_exp: I would do this and explored it before but just could not afford it.
Replacement_exp: I have a Parkray that is well maintained but very old and inefficient.

Sustainability_exp: I am interested in all forms of Heating as the ViIllage i live in has no gas Electric heating seems the only sensible option moving forward.
Future_exp: Electric is the only really carbon free energy source, once the country is fully re-neweable.
Upgrade_exp: At the moment we use storage heaters, we have a well insulated house, but they are still hit and miss for comfort and energy use.
Financial_exp: Never look a gift horse in the mouth.
Technology_exp: As a manager at a school, i would like to see how this technology works, and if it is good i would roll it out across the portfolio.
Research_exp: It would feel good to be on a trial for new tech.
Planned_exp: The cost is prohibative to upgrading without the incentive.

Sustainability_exp: I am very keen to reduce my environmental impact through any cost effective means

The house does not have full central heating and I have been looking to make the house warmer and in a green manner, but am unsure how to go about this. I am coming up to full retirement and want to make the house more cosy
Future_exp: I have always been interested in the environment and want to be part of the solution to combat climate change
Upgrade_exp: I have been looking at Air Source heat pumps and for me, it seems a good solution to heat a small terraced house at a relatively low
Building_exp: Before I fully retire I want to renew the house and put in a new kitchen and bathroom
Financial_exp: I am interested in changing my form of heating, which at present is minimal. From next year I will be reliant on a pension. Obviously, no cost is attractive.
Technology_exp: I want to make my house energy efficient and understand the urgent need to change the ways houses are heated.
Research_exp: I would be interested to see what an integrated heating system would achieve in my house
Planned_exp: I have been looking at alternative heating systems and want to be low carbon, so have been looking at all heating options
Replacement_exp: My heating system is a mixture of electric and gas and I would like to make it remotely controllable and do away with gas. I want to make the heating efficient and reduce running costs

Sustainability_exp: I am concerned over climate change and try to do all I can to reduce my carbon footprint in all of my activities in life.
Future_exp: I am aware that eventually dirty energy will be taxed heavily with gas being phased out for new properties. But I like my house and don�t want to move so would be keen to retrofit a low carbon heating and hot water system
Upgrade_exp: My current system is not that old however it is gas fired and not as clean as electric
Financial_exp: Somewhat a silly question, but in any event I have been looking at heat pump technology over the past year
Technology_exp: As above I can see the merit in this technology for low carbon heating and hot water
Research_exp: I think the public are sceptical about heat pumps and would like to champion the technology if I can.
Planned_exp: I have been looking at the technology and have researched a number of providers and potential cost, payback and grants
Replacement_exp: Reasonably new (5 years ago replaced gas boiler)

Sustainability_exp: We hope to reduce our environmental impact generally, motoring too
Future_exp: It would bring this 250 year old house up to date
Upgrade_exp: We have heard that this is a good and efficient alternative to what we currently have
Building_exp: Only decorative refurbishment recently, other improvements made made some years ago
Technology_exp: ...but just dont know how appropriate it is for this kind of house
Research_exp: We are happy to help your research if we can
Planned_exp: Only if you believe a heat pump system would work here
Replacement_exp: All heating, cooking, and hot water is currently provided by a gas-powered Rayburn - expensive on gas and not good environmentally

Future_exp: Things will be changing in the next 2-3 years. I dont want to install an out dated system.
Upgrade_exp: I would like a heat pump but I dont know if it is a practical option.
Financial_exp: I have to budget my money as I am now a pensioner (since December 2020).
Technology_exp: I feel in the UK we are slow to adopt new technology. I wish to speed this up and make heat pumps mainstream.
Research_exp: I am critical of government of not putting enough support into changing to low carbon heating. I think this project will give more information into the practicalities of retro fitting to properties of all shapes and sizes hopefully assisting more heating engineers to become trained and confident to install heat pumps.
Planned_exp: I would like a heat pump but I dont know how to find a reliable contractor to see if it is possible in my small house.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is the original 2001 from new build. Im sure I could replace with a more efficient system. I dont want to replace with gas if possible as gas systems are being phased out. But I may have a boiler breakdown meaning I will have the quickest option, probably gas.

Sustainability_exp: We already have an electric car and will be getting solar PV panels - we are keen to reduce our environmental impact and happy to make these lifestyle changes.
Future_exp: Although we have managed to find ways of reducing our need for electricity from the grid, we realise that our current gas boiler/heating set-up does not match what we have achieved with electric use.
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump seems to be a great solution to our desire to reduce our carbon footprint. It seems to suit our house style and we have plenty of outdoor space.
Building_exp: No major building work is being done at the moment, although we expect our PV panels and battery will have been installed by the end of the year.
Financial_exp: We have already made significant investments into our lifestyle to reduce our carbon footprint - buying an electric car 4.5 years ago and installing solar panels. A low/no-cost solution for heating is obviously very attractive.
Technology_exp: We enjoy upgrading the technology in our home when available and were early purchasers of a Tesla Model S in the UK. We have installed Nest into our last two houses to control our heating and hot water, and have had a smart meter installed in our current house.
Research_exp: We have previously taken part in research projects for in-home Wi-Fi systems and electric car chargers, so we are familiar with the demands of a trial such as this. It is exciting to be part of a new technology rollout.
Planned_exp: We had considered a heat pump when moving into our house 2 years ago, but had not yet progressed these enquiries into a building project.
Replacement_exp: Our combi boiler is approximately 10 years old and does not need to be replaced immediately, but we would like a more energy efficient/low carbon method of heating our home.

Sustainability_exp: I take an active interest in all ways I, and my family, can reduce our environmental impact. Weve reduced our gas use to the minimum and are on a renewable electricity tariff. Im improving the houses insulation and have been looking at smart boiler controls to better manage how we heat the house, which we will be fitting along with a more efficient boiler if we arent accepted for this trial.  I have also considered fitting solar panels although have not yet taken this idea forward due to the design of our roof requiring a more complex installation.
Future_exp: An important part of bring the countrys CO2 emissions down is to move to low carbon domestic heating as quickly as possible so these technologies need to be the future. Im keen to play a part in moving to that future.
Upgrade_exp: My heating system works fine. If I wasnt concerned about CO2 emissions I would continue as we are, although possibly with a new gas boiler to replace the aging one we currently have. I dont see a heat pump as an upgrade. I see it as an alternative, hopefully an alternative that will start to become viable for all homes.
Financial_exp: One of the things that has held me back from buying a heat pump is the cost. I know they work well in new builds where radiators and underfloor heating are designed for the lower water temperatures. But I dont know how well it will work in my 1990s house with standard radiators. It would be a lot of money to spend to find that it doesnt heat the house effectively. If the system is being provided for free Im happier to take the risk.
Technology_exp: Although I make use of technology I am not normally an early adopter. I use technology where I see it can make a positive difference. For example, if Im not accepted for this trial I will probably install a smart heating system with individual room control so each room can be managed separately.
Research_exp: For heat pumps to become readily acceptable in domestic settings people need to see that they work. I am very keen to be part of that process. I see it as not just making a difference to our CO2 emissions but also for every person who, in future, feels confident to buy a heat pump because of the results of this trial.
Planned_exp: I have considered a heat pump but the cost is too high when compared against the uncertainty of how it will perform in our 1990s, which was designed to be heated by a gas boiler.
Replacement_exp: Not the entire system, but the boiler. It is old and not very efficient. I have plans to replace it with a new boiler and smart control system.

Sustainability_exp: gas fired central heating uses such an impactful power source that I feel guilty every time I use it.
Financial_exp: I am a single parent with only my own income.  The heating system is old and I cant afford to replace it (even though it works perfectly fine) on my own.
Planned_exp: if I did have the ability to finance a new heating system, I would definitely move to a more sustainable product

Sustainability_exp: Have already installed solar PV and batteries
Future_exp: Would now love to replace my gas boiler with a more sustainable heating source
Building_exp: May be having some internal work done to house in 2021
Financial_exp: I am attracted to the fact that I will need to replace my existing gas boiler in time, so your offer came along at the right time
Technology_exp: Being an ex engineer I like to keep up with new technologies, especially when it can cut my carbon footprint
Research_exp: As above have always been keen on new technology
Planned_exp: When I need to replace my existing gas boiler I would look at a heat pump source for this
Replacement_exp: Current heating system is probably around itshalf life stage, but of course will polute the atomoshere the longer I keep it

Sustainability_exp: I am very interested in moving to green technologies; Im aiming to replace our car with an electric one and I want to invest in solar panels for our house. In the meantime I am on a green energy tariff but while it is possible to select renewable energy for electricity the same isnt really the case for gas. Id therefore like to move away from needing a gas supply, and weve already removed our gas hob.
Future_exp: I note that gas boilers will not be fitted to new houses in future. Plus I imagine that gas prices will only increase.
Upgrade_exp: Again I would like to move away from a gas boiler
Building_exp: Not currently but we do plan a first floor extension in the next couple of years and I am aiming to include solar panels in this
Financial_exp: I like free stuff. But also if I dont have to pay for a green heating system I can put that money towards my electric car dream
Technology_exp: I have adopted in some smart tech, such as a smart thermostat. I am also interested in green technology more generally
Research_exp: As above, I am interested in green technology and also in doing my bit
Planned_exp: This would be an aim in the more longer term but it would be great to bring this forward
Replacement_exp: The boiler is currently working so my main aim is to be greener

Sustainability_exp: The scale of challenges facing our planet are formidable.  Every step we take to reduce our ecological footprint helps the environment.  I have already started making our kitchen eco-friendly and have a blog on our catering website detailing this journey.  To have a zero carbon heating system installed would be the icing on the cake!
Future_exp: "We do not inherit the earth from our ancestors, we borrow it from our children "(Native American proverb).  Adopting a low carbon technology heating system can only benefit the next generation.
Upgrade_exp: Our current heating/hot water system is inefficient.  We spend ages running the taps to obtain hot water, thereby wasting a natural resource.  As well as reducing our carbon footprint, a heat pump has so many other advantages (e.g. lower running costs, less maintenance, safer & has a long life span).
Financial_exp: Unfortunately I am not in a position to afford the installation.  To be given the system for free would just be amazing.
Technology_exp: Using technology to improve our control over energy usage can only be a positive step.
Research_exp: Out of all the energy suppliers we have used over the years, OVO   surpasses them all in terms of customer support and efficiency.  To be able to assist them with the project would be our way of saying "thank you".  It would also, undeniably, be of great benefit to us.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler is 13 years old and our central heating system has been here since we moved here (1992).  It is not the most efficient of systems!  Although the boiler is serviced annually, we often have to call out the engineer in between services.
Other_exp: If the system works well, I would love to encourage others to reduce their carbon footprint and replace their heating system with a zero carbon one.

Future_exp: Know that the government wants to move from gas central heating and water to more climate friendly solution
Upgrade_exp: Keen to be able to improve on what we have, which is effective. Hope to be able to lower cost of heating as well
Financial_exp: Concerned that one day we will be obliged to move away from Gas and not be able to afford to put in new system
Technology_exp: I like being an early adopter of technology
Research_exp: This would be something new and potentially beneficial to society as a whole. Be good to be part of this experiment
Replacement_exp: The heating system has years of life left, less than 10 years old.

Sustainability_exp: I have been planning to install a heat store and solar PV. I had ruled out heat pumps because I thought they were too expensive.
Future_exp: I think its going to become more desirable for a house to have low carbon energy use and also prices are likely to keep rising on fossil fuels.
Upgrade_exp: We have the space so it seems very logical to use a heat pump and save energy.
Building_exp: We are planning to build a rear extension and rearrange some rooms. The boiler and cylinder will have to be moved anyway so its a sensible time to install something better.
Financial_exp: I thought heat pumps were very expensive so this definitely got my attention.
Technology_exp: I am an engineer at heart and always keen to find the better solution. We have moved to EV cars and I am very keen to get PV panels and a home battery.
Research_exp: I would be happy to provide feedback and statistics as needed. I am happy for changes to my house too. Im also the kind of person who will talk about my heating system at great length to friends and family :o)
Planned_exp: I thought they were too expensive so was thinking to use PV to heat water instead but had certainly investigated heat pumps previously as an efficient solution.
Replacement_exp: The boiler and cylinder are not very efficient and also we want to move them so this would fit well.

Sustainability_exp: Very keen to be more environmentally positive. I have solar panels and drive a hybrid car.
Future_exp: I think its important that we are able to lower the environmental footprint where we can
Upgrade_exp: I feel its important to make the right decisions for the future ecology, a hear pump is more efficient than gas.
Building_exp: I have already extended my property
Financial_exp: Absolutely, I have invested in solar panels and cant afford to invest further.
Technology_exp: Love new tech, like to be an early adopter and champion for new tech.
Research_exp: Anything I can do to promote green initiatives while improving my footprint is a bonus.
Planned_exp: Would love to but dont have the budget

Sustainability_exp: I recently bought an electric car. Im interested in different technologies for powering our lives.
Future_exp: An alternative low carbon technology would be a hydrogen boiler, but that seems to be a long way off yet.
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump is a more efficient way of heating than conventional electric heaters.
Financial_exp: Taking the opportunity for a free system provided it is suitable is obvious.
Technology_exp: I am interested in the technology and what it involves.
Replacement_exp: Our gas boiler is still fairly new, and working well so scrapping this is a negative factor to getting a new heating system.

Sustainability_exp: I have previously had exterior insulation fitted so want to continue to use less fuel. My boiler has been reliable but is elderly and I would prefer a ground source heat pump before the inevitable happens and I have to make a choice quickly.
Financial_exp: This is obviously the case but, not the only reason by any means - see above.
Research_exp: I have supported the push for ground source heat pumps to be placed in parks for the good of the local communities, so it�s rather good to think there�s a chance to have one of my own.
Planned_exp: I�d certainly be interested to know if one would be feasible for my home and I have considered where I would put the battery, but have not got as far as planning it.
Replacement_exp: Only if the boiler packs up.

Sustainability_exp: I would like to reduce use of gas as a heating fuel, and eventually generate as much of my own power and heat for domestic electrical supply, heating and hot water as possible
Future_exp: Eventually I would like to have solar PV to help provide the electrical requirements for home heating and hot water generation.
Upgrade_exp: Have previously considered this type of system, either standalone or as part of solar PV and solar heating.
Financial_exp: Obviously having a system installed and paid for  makes it even more attractive to get this type of heating.
Research_exp: Happy to be part of the trial as long as my family, property or finances are not adversely affected by it.
Planned_exp: Have previously considered this type of system, either standalone or as part of solar PV and solar heating.

Sustainability_exp: My boilers is old and I have been considering how to replace it with the most environmentally friendly option. However my research so far into the possibilities have been well beyond my budget, so this opportunity would be very welcome.
Technology_exp: My sister has a heat pump which works well and I am very interested in developments of this technology.
Research_exp: I have a keen interest in contributing to research ( I work in health research management)
Planned_exp: As in my previous answer - I would like to but would need some financial assistance which this research would provide.

Sustainability_exp: I am a keen supporter of green solutions and take simple everyday actions to reduce my energy use, however I am not able to invest in new technology with a high initial cost. This trial would be an ideal opportunity for me to make a difference
Future_exp: I currently have a gas powered central heating system which is nearing the end of its life. I am aware that the use of gas for heating is being phased out and I would welcome the opportunity to adopt a new low carbon technology sooner rather than later to make the house more energy efficient long term
Upgrade_exp: I dont really understand how a heat pump works but I know that it takes heat from outside the house to heat the inside - if this can be done in an energy efficient way it seems like a no-brainer. I am prepared for this to involve building work
Building_exp: I am unable to afford any large scale changes to my property although I know that my almost 50-year-old heating system is likely to be consigned to the scrap heap at any point so I would really welcome the chance to update it now
Financial_exp: As a pensioner this is the only way I can afford to adopt new low carbon technology
Technology_exp: I have a practical approach to technological innovation in that I will happily adopt new tech that improves my life, but I need to be sure it will be efficient and cost effective
Research_exp: This would be an exciting and very worthwhile project to be involved in, which would make huge improvements to my property and feed back information to the research team on the viability of doing this large scale
Planned_exp: As a pensioner I am unable to afford any large scale changes to my property
Replacement_exp: The original Johnson & Starley warm air system was installed in the 1970s - it is now obsolete and when it stops working I dont know what I could replace it with

Sustainability_exp: I help others be more energy efficient and sustainable through my work. Id like to lead by example.
Future_exp: The carbon footprint of grid electricity is now lower than that of gas. By moving to a heat pump we could dramatically reduce our carbon footprint, especially if we can reduce improve the fabric efficiency of the property (weve already started).
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump would be a great way to upgrade the system to a more energy efficient and sustainable system. Depending on the system it could also provide good cost savings.
Building_exp: We are already planning insulation and central heating changes, this would be the perfect opportunity to change the system e.g. larger radiators.
Financial_exp: Heat pumps are great, but dont give the best return on investment  for houses that already have a gas connection. Id love to have a heat pump, but cant justify (or afford) the cost
Technology_exp: I want to be able to tell others the realities of living with a heat pump and what the retrofit process is like.
Research_exp: Millions of houses will need deep retrofits to be more energy efficient and generate heat more sustainably. The better we know how best to retrofit properties the easier the transition will be.
Planned_exp: Long term I was planning on doing so, I simply cant afford to do so without subsidy
Replacement_exp: The system is 7 years old so it should still have a few years left, but it will probably need replacing in 3-6 years.

Sustainability_exp: We have a very old, inefficient gas boiler that is definitely not doing our carbon footprint any good at all. Moving to a technology that has none of the same emissions is a very attractive idea and one I have been examining recently.
Future_exp: Im not sure that gas boilers are the future of heating, they are definitely the past and I keep hearing talk that they will not be installed after a date in the near future. Adopting a new low carbon technology now will remove any worries about having to upgrade in a few years time, or worry that the bills will keep going up and up as gas gets more expensive.
Upgrade_exp: Our gas boiler is very old and inefficient and on its last legs. We have been saving for a new one but I have also been looking into alternative options. Heat pumps have been something that has come up over and over again. Also, a relative has had one fitted in the past couple of years and they are very happy with it. They were coming from a house without central heating though so I think anything would be an improvement from storage heaters!
Financial_exp: To be honest, who wouldnt be! After looking at installation costs of a new system vs a new gas boiler, Im not sure we could afford it. We only have one salary coming in which is plenty for us to live on and save some every month but it would take us quite a while to be able to afford a new heat pump system. This is only from some initial investigations online, we havent had any official quotes.
Technology_exp: I love a bit of technology and am still intruiged by the way heat pumps work and the fact that they can generate heat from cold air.
Research_exp: I think things that take us away from the established norm with regard to fossil fuel use can only be a good thing. Electric cars, solar panels, heat pumps etc are all the future of energy and they need to be proven to work as well as, if not better than the fossil fuel alternatives. I would be more than happy to help and provide whatever feedback is required.
Planned_exp: I wasnt planning to, but it is an option that I have been looking into and considering.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler is so old the company that made it went out of business 8 years ago! But it has kept plugging away each winter, gradually getting more noisy, requiring resetting more often and now its starting to make some strange noises occasionally, so it has to go. We have saved just enough for a new gas boiler but the opportunity to have a new low carbon system was too good not to at least enquire about.

Sustainability_exp: Ive been thinking for some time about low carbon heating in order to reduce environmental impact and hopefully save money, but cant afford to take the measures necessary to have a meaningful impact. We should all do what we can to reduce our impact, but unfortunately in my case finances get in the way
Future_exp: This will improve the environmental impact of my house, hopefully for many years to come, and it would be interesting to see what technology can do, especially when retro-fitted to an existing property
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump is environmentally friendly compared to other more conventional systems. I have space at the back and sides of my house which should be more than enough to install a pump, and a field on one side which should reduce any impact on neighbours and infrastructure
Financial_exp: Anyone would be attracted to it because its free, but in my case as already mentioned this is technology that I otherwise wouldnt be able to afford for a number of years
Technology_exp: Im always interested in new technology anyway and when I can be, Im an early adopter. Such an overhaul of the heating system would be very interesting to see, as would the impact on the environment and our gas bills
Research_exp: I would support the project in any way possible. I assume that Ovo would conduct checks on the system and on bills etc in the future to assess the success of this project, and would be more than happy for inspectors to come to my address, call me etc
Planned_exp: I have already looked into a heat pump but would otherwise be unable to afford to switch to one
Replacement_exp: The heating system works ok, but is a conventional boiler system in a fairly large house so I suspect it isnt as efficient as it could be

Sustainability_exp: Have a 15 year old gas boiler, would like to replace with something greener
Upgrade_exp: If it can be done within our small garden
Financial_exp: I doubt we could afford the capital outlay
Technology_exp: Have seen new build eco-houses but this house is exactly where we want to be and would like to bring it up to future standards
Replacement_exp: Gas boiler still works with care, but isnt very efficient and will soon need replacement, especially if we add more radiators

Sustainability_exp: I have been trying to find a way to move my heating and hot water to an electric system with some form of energy storage. With a view to installing solar panels in the future and using an agile energy tariff to shift energy use off peak.

My wife and I are doing our best to reduce our impact on the environment and are doing what we can to live as green a lifestyle as possible, that I cluded seeking to find eco-friendly, sustainable and fair trade clothing, beginning to grow our own fruit and veg, and we are keen to have a much greener heating system.  We would like to go as carbonneutral as possible, switching away from the oil heating in place when we purchased our house.  We recognise the issues of climate change and want to set a great example for our 3 year old, both in respecting our planet but also in ensuring he has a beautiful world left to grow up in.
Future_exp: We would ideally like a system that moves us away from our oil tanks and oil fired boiler into greener low carbon technology.  Air or ground source hearing technology is great, both sustainable and clean. Likewise we intend to have solar installed in the future, to further lower our carbon footprint.  We want to embrace green technology and the changes that can bring and to help demonstrate to others that it is not only feasible but better than the fossil fuel dependent systems people have had to rely on historically.
Upgrade_exp: We have an oil tank and boiler and ideally I would much rather have a heat source pump in combination with an electric boiler, this would not only produce cleaner, more efficient heating, but would also help us to provide a great example to our 3 year old boy, chiming with other changes we have made to our lifestyle as a way of going greener.
Building_exp: We arent currently undertaking building works but are in the process of looking at how to upgrade our homes heating system and have a view to extending and refurbishing our home in the next 5 years.  This would be an ideal way to ensure an up to date system was in place that would either match the needs of our current property and any future refurbishment / extension and enable our old/ aging and inefficient system to be made green.
Financial_exp: We spent a lot moving into our current house.  We are an armed forces family, and decided to settle to provide stability for my wife and son, as well as enabling us to invest into living a greener lifestyle.  We bought our house just over a year ago and spent significant sums undertaking crucial works, such as replacing the roof.  This unfortunately ate into our budget for redoing other aspects of the property, such as the heating system and has delayed our ability to install solar power too.  That the system would be provided free of charge is fantastic, as it will enable us to make significant green improvements much sooner than we could otherwise.
Technology_exp: As above, we would like to adopt greener, more efficient technology, setting a great example for our son and doing our bit to help fight climate change.   We see this as an ideal way to also learn and pass on good practice and knowledge to friends as they come to updating their heating systems.  We have friends dotted throughout the country who are likely to look to upgrade their heating systems with modern technology in the next 5years or so.  This scheme would allow us to help point them to trusted sources for such upgrades too.
Research_exp: This research project sounds brilliant, helping to set up a system to update older houses with up to date, modern heating solutions.  If it can produce an affordable and effective road map to enabling householders throughout the UK to update their homes in a green way, wed love to be part of that change.
Planned_exp: In the long run, I intend to install a heat pump, be it ground or air source, they appear to work wonderfully well alongside other green systems, such as electric boilers and solar power, so this is the perfect opportunity for us.  It provides a route to affording the changes we wish to make without taking us a long time to do so.
Replacement_exp: We have an old heating system that is inefficient.  We have an older, single skinned oil tank, along with an aging oil boiler.  Additionally, our radiators are primarily single panel, single convector radiators with poor heat output for the property.  In short, o suspect well have to replace our heating system in the fairly near future and I fear that we may not be able to afford to make those changes in the way we would like to if that proves to be the case, as if the heating system goes in the next few years, we wont have saved sufficient to afford a green replacement, e.g. air/ground source heating with efficient radiators and an electric boiler.

Sustainability_exp: Living in an area outside of the main gas network, were surrounded by homes that heat using bottled gas or oil. Sometimes you can smell the oil and there are weekly gas bottle and oil deliveries that come through the single road through the village. I have been keen to take steps to increase the energy efficiency of my home and replacing my ageing oiler boiler with something with as low an impact as possible is high on my list of priorities. I hope that installing an air-source heat pump might make it a viable alternative for my neighbours when considering replacing their current heating systems.
Future_exp: I feel that low carbon technologies intergrate well with the future that many of us want to see compared to fossil-fuel heavy approaches. In my situation, Im currently reliant on oil deliveries for my boiler. I try to use it as little as possible due to the smell. An electricity-based heat pump would be beneficial for reliable heating and would also integrate well with future additions such as PV solar panels.
Upgrade_exp: As mentioned, my oil boiler might be more than 20 years old so is currently highly inefficient, relatively. Rather than invest in a new oil boiler or considering transitioning to bottled gas, I am very keen to learn more about heat pumps as an alternative that could be used to heat the home. Perhaps taking advantage of the low temperature system to keep the solid walls warmer and reducing the rise and fall in temperatures we often experience here.
Building_exp: On the run up to winter, I have taken steps to improving the energy efficiency of my home such as draught-proofing as much as possible, blocking fireplaces and I increased the loft insulation to 270mm. I feel that a low carbon heating system like a heat pump could benefit the house and that involvement in research could be helpful for future policy and advice... With the added benefit of reducing emissions!
Financial_exp: The system being free of charge is an clear benefit, however, my motivations are more closely aligned to wanting to have the chance to be involved with cutting-edge research and that the installation might be a valuable case study for others in the area.
Technology_exp: I enjoy trying new technologies and have interest in smarthome systems and the potential for home automation. The more I learn about heat pumps, the more Im fascinated by the technology and would be eager to try one out.
Research_exp: I feel that a better understanding of how heat pumps can integrate in the grid, especially for homes outside of the gas network, is very valuable. It would be a pleasure to be part of that cohort.
Planned_exp: I have been investigating the potential of installing an air source heat pump to replace the oil boiler, especially given the release of the green homes grant details. However, if an installation can also be beneficial for the research, this feels like a good outcome.
Replacement_exp: As mentioned, Im looking to replace my ageing oil boiler over the next year or so. Involvement in the research would be an opportunity to go green sooner as Im keen to avoid another oil boiler or bottled gas.

Sustainability_exp: House built 110 yrs ago and therefore difficult to draught-proof.
I would like to move away from fossil fuels and be more energy efficient
Future_exp: We want to invest now to save money and help preserve the environment
Upgrade_exp: We are open to considering all the option - heat pump and other options.  We dont know which is the best
Financial_exp: This is mainly because it feels high risk to invest in still experimental environment technology.
Technology_exp: We would like to be more environmentally friendly and want to understand how we can do this
Research_exp: Because it not only helps us make more envrionmental sustainable but furthers the research to help other people do the same.
Planned_exp: We would probably wait until our current boiler breaks (it is 30+ years old) and then investigate our options.  Probably we would play it safe financially and install more or less the same again.
Replacement_exp: It currently seems to be working well but we know it is very old so will need replacing at some point soon

Sustainability_exp: We are very keen to reduce our carbon footprint and explore greener home heating systems. It is the future and the general population need to break out of their comfort zone and embrace new technologies.
Future_exp: We have a gas boiler and although it keeps us warm, there are greener alternatives. Our house is using outdated technology and needs to modernise. We are keen to be the first ones in our family/ social circle to embrace greener technology so we can spread the word and encourage others to move away from old polluting technologies.
Upgrade_exp: We looked at heat pumps when we were doing building work on our house last year but unfortunately our budget didn�t stretch to it. Our existing gas boiler was still functional so we are still using it. We are keen to change it to a heat pump, but we can�t afford to at the moment.
Financial_exp: We have a young family with two children under 5. I am a part time NHS midwife And my husband works in telecoms so no furlough for us! We are fortunate that we both have our jobs but neither of us a high earners.
Technology_exp: We like to stay up to date with technology and try new things especially when they are beneficial to the environment.
Research_exp: I regularly participate in research, improving the collective knowledge is how the human race learns new things and evolves.
Planned_exp: We had been put off a heat pump by the high upfront cost.
Replacement_exp: Our current boiler is still working fine but when it needs replacing I think we unfortunately we would have to take the cheapest option rather than installing a heat pump.

Sustainability_exp: I like the idea of making savings on my bills and using energy which is better for the environment
Future_exp: I like the idea of having systems in place which will give lower bills and require less maintenance as we get older. I also believe that there will be a drive to reduce and ultimately eliminate fossil fuels
Upgrade_exp: I believe in the technology and that it will reduce maintenance and running costs
Financial_exp: I could not afford to put this technology in to my home
Technology_exp: I like the idea of a system that moves away fossil fuels
Research_exp: I would like to take part in this trial and show that there are better alternatives to fossil fuels
Planned_exp: I would love to get a heat pump but could not afford the technology
Replacement_exp: My current boiler has been in the home for approximately 8 years and so it�s life is limited, this would be a great way to get a new better alternative to the traditional gas combi boiler

Sustainability_exp: I am keen to reduce my environmental impact in whatever way I can.
Upgrade_exp: I hadnt thought about until prompted by this promotion programme
Financial_exp: I am always interested in a bargain!
Technology_exp: so long as it is for a good reason, not just technology for technologys sake
Research_exp: I am interested to learn what options are effective, particularly for a 50+ year old house

Upgrade_exp: Id like to explore the possibilities of using a heat pump in a small property
Replacement_exp: Replacement of my system is not needed immediately but will be within the next few years.

Sustainability_exp: We have an old gas boiler, and I realise the our carbon footprint is much higher than it could be.
Future_exp: I feel that gas heating is likely going to be discouraged by government regulation, so would be looking to move away from this as a heat source.
Upgrade_exp: We have good access to an internal garage where the boiled currently is. An air source heat pump attached to the garage external wall seems like a straight forward upgrade.
Building_exp: The garage is soon to be decorated, so any improvement works would be good to do before this starts.
Financial_exp: I am interested in this technology and improving my carbon footprint, but I think it would take a long time for the installation costs to be offset by savings.
Technology_exp: Heat pump technology gas always been particularly interesting to me, especially  as we move towards renewable energy generation. We dont own the roof for solar panels, so this seems like the best choice.
Research_exp: There seems like there is huge interest in renewable heating technology at the moment, and it would be good to be involved in improving this technology for wide use. It would also be a good local demonstration for my neighbours.
Planned_exp: Our boiler needs replacing soon, but would probably replace with a new gas combi boiler due to much lower costs.
Replacement_exp: As I said before, the gas boiler is old and inefficient. Would be looking to replace this soon anyway. This would be a great opportunity to replace it responsibly.

Sustainability_exp: I have an old back boiler, it�s inefficient. I�m not replacing it with gas so this is an ideal opportunity to make a difference. We have to do lots of small things to work towards a more sustainable existence
Future_exp: Definitely, renewable energy has to be the way forward. It�s outrageous that we don�t have more of it.
Upgrade_exp: My heating and plumbing system is 40 years old. It needs upgrading so a heat pump is the way forward.
Building_exp: There are all sorts of elements that need updating. I�m planning for an extension and refurb so this is all part of that.
Financial_exp: I have much to achieve on a small budget so anything I can do to maximise that will enable me to upgrade windows for example.
Technology_exp: I�m fairly tech savvy so thy is element is interesting
Research_exp: Anything I can do to help this cause is good. It would be interesting to be involved.
Planned_exp: I have been trying to work out the best approach but think now I have decided on a heat pump
Replacement_exp: I have a very old system so yes this is a good opportunity

Sustainability_exp: I have already insulated my house as much as practical and installed solar thermal and solar PV systems, but still heat with mains gas and so would like to reduce my environmental impact further.
Future_exp: I know that replacing my gas boiler will not be possible after 2025 so would like to move to a lower carbon system now.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pumps are one of the future systems for home heating. I was one of the researchers in the Energy Saving Trusts heat pump trial and so know something about the technology
Financial_exp: I would not move to a heat pump at this stage if a free installation was not available
Technology_exp: As noted I am a keen adopter of new technology having installed solar thermal and solar PV and finding the sytems very satisfactory
Research_exp: I have been involved in research on renewable energy systems for many years
Planned_exp: Not without this trial, but this is an opportunity to do so
Replacement_exp: My condensing gas boiler system is about 10 years old but still functioning well as it is hardly used for 5 months of the year given our solar thermal system.

Sustainability_exp: As gas is from a none renewable source but currently very cheap to use. it always good to start looking into alternative fuels.
Future_exp: Gas supplies are depleting and the prospects of homes having to change heating source in the future it is better to get in early and trail new solutions to see what works best.
Financial_exp: The ground source heat pump or air source are still very new tech and people need to test this new tech and then promote its benefits to other s.
Technology_exp: I currently have solar panels on my roof which i wish to expand to try and make my home more energy efficient and one day have a battery to try and remain of the grid as much as possible.

Sustainability_exp: Whilst keen to reduce my household environmental impact, my primary concern is with improving local air quality. As our home is heated either with Gas or from a small Wood Burner, anything we can do to reduce our emissions at the same time as reducing our bills is worth investigating.
Future_exp: Electrical heating with heat pumps is clearly going to be the future of domestic heating. Currently though, its a big investment to replace Gas Central heating with a HP system. Projects like this one, as well as other means of government support, are important to get this industry off the ground and into the mainstream.
Upgrade_exp: Whilst there is nothing currently faulty with our home heating, a HP system would reduce our contribution to local air pollution and hopefully show other local residents that such options exist.
Financial_exp: Clearly this is a factor. It would not be financially viable for us to consider changing our current Gas boiler. A free heating system upgrade would also help us to afford the investment into Solar PV, something we would love to be able to add.
Technology_exp: Now feels like exactly the right time to be an early adopter of this technology.
Research_exp: Without support, projects like these would not get the traction that they need to take the industry into the mainstream and reduce domestic heating GHG emissions across the whole country.

Sustainability_exp: I am very worried about the impact of climate change and would like to be an exmaple to others for how this transition can not only benefit the environment but is a better solution overall

Upgrade_exp: Having researched the technology i am comfortable that the technology is superior and works.

Research_exp: Absolutely i think this is a really important showcase that can lead to a mass rollout if successful
Planned_exp: Thinking yes but not sure how to proceed which is why i would like to take this path ideally
Replacement_exp: Its about 9 years old and still running fine

Upgrade_exp: Frankly it beggars belief that this "new" is so high carbon and thermally inefficient and it makes sense to us to correct this through upgrading the heat source.

Technology_exp: I am an engineer and a gas boiler is really only a couple of steps up from an open fire in cave so if I can help you prove that these systems work then I am willing to help.
Research_exp: Very keen to help provide the data on these new systems (although technically its a Carnot cycle system and thats nearly 200 years old already).

Replacement_exp: Alas not and this was the blocker to us undertaking the work ourselves.

Sustainability_exp: Before the COVID-19 outbreak, my wife and I have decided that we would like to reduce our impact on the world we live in. We installed Solar, but in recent months have also traded in our old gas guzzler car to get an EV.

Upgrade_exp: We are absolutely considering all available options when upgrading our central heating system.
Building_exp: We are not planning any refurbishment at this time, due to the outlay on solar and an EV.
Financial_exp: Of course! Who wouldnt be? However, I enjoy giving feedback on things and would be happy to participate in any way I can.
Technology_exp: I am very excited by new technology and would love to be able to adopt something like this project.
Research_exp: I am very keen to help with feedback, site access & testing. I also like to know how things work and why, so might ask different questions. Having been in an IT role for a number of years, I am also computer literate and happy to press buttons etc as required!
Planned_exp: As stated previously, the cost of a heat pump would likely be too high to install.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler is nearly 10 years old. Last year the engineer told us that wed be lucky to get another year out of it as the heat exchanger is looking like its not got long left.

Sustainability_exp: This is the main motivation - our heating is our biggest carbon emission and this would significantly reduce it.
Would like to reduce our carbon footprint and have a more efficient house. I currently work in the renewable sector and one a system fitted at my house.

Im always looking for ways to reduce the household environmental impact and this would be an excellent way of adding to this.
Future_exp: Current heating system us gas. Whilst gas is likely to be available for many years to come, its ultimately a finite resource. As we move to the availability of more sustainable electricity, a heating system that uses small amounts of electricity is much more future proofed.

Technology_exp: Ive always been an early adopter of technology and this intrigues me.
Research_exp: Im happy to provide follow-up information regarding the outcome of the trial.

Sustainability_exp: I have an electric car but oil heating.  I wish to reduce my carbon footprint by making my home as efficient as possible.
Future_exp: My long term home is oil heated at present.  By switching to a renewable heating source we should be able to lower our bis and our carbon footprint.  Our home is already insulated and double glazed.
Upgrade_exp: I have investigated heat pumps previously but due to initial outlay costs I have not been able to implement their potential.
Financial_exp: With help of the initial investment I may be able to add heat pumps and with the savings made I may be able to add solar PV in the near future.
