Research_exp: I enjoy testing and developing automation systems and the data they collect.
Planned_exp: The initial cost of a heat pump is the prohibitive factor at the moment
Replacement_exp: An aging oil fired boiler is quite inefficient, expensive and smelly part of my home.

Sustainability_exp: I try to be as green as possible, Ive had solar panels for 7 years, have replaced my double glazing for more energy efficient does and windows, replaced all bulbs with led, had wall and loft insulation, so I just need to tackle the heating now
Future_exp: I believe fossil fuels are not the way to hear your home anymore, but electric heating systems would be far too expensive to run
Upgrade_exp: I would love to move to a great pump, but cant justify the expense vs savings
Financial_exp: It would allow me to achieve my goal of installing an environmentally friendly system without the worry of trying to find the funds
Technology_exp: I have installed a lot of technology for home automation, and embrace the use to make the running of a house easier and more efficient
Research_exp: I would be very grateful to be given the opportunity to take part in this project and happy to provide any feedback required
Planned_exp: I would love to but cant justify the costs
Replacement_exp: My heating system is only approx 6 years old, having had the old has boiler replaced when the old one developed issues after 18 years

Sustainability_exp: We have investigated solar panels in the past but it appears that the agle of our roof pitches makes this sub-optimal. Our electricuty supply is always from suppliers guaranteeing that it is generated from 100% renewable sources. We are currently considering replacing our gas boiler and did investigate installing a heat pump as an alternative but the cost was prohibitive compared to installing a more efficient gas boiler. We would, however, welcome the opportunity to install a more environmentally efficient system if we can. At some point we intend to build our own house and would then aim to install a sustainable energy system.
Future_exp: We are aware that the Government is committed to phasing out the reliance of domestic users on burning fossil fuels and the importance of this in meeting our responsibilities to reduce carbon emissions. We support this initiative but as we live in an old house, the realistic options available to us are somewhat limited. That said, we do believe that having a low carbon heating system will be increasingly important to future house buyers and we are consious that replacing our existing gas boiler with another one (albeit much more efficient) is not the way we should be going.
Upgrade_exp: As already stated, we have looked into the possibility of installing a heat pump but were not convinced that the technology available at the time would reliably satisfy the needs of this property at an affordable cost. We didnt, however, have a survey done at the time to confirm this and would be very happy to engage in a process that could demonsrate that a heat pump is a viable option for a property of this age and size.
Building_exp: As already stated, our current boiler is very old and inefficient. It is also proving unreliable in terms of the control system, valves and old hot water tank. The old vertically vented asbestos flue will, we understand, mean that the next service of the boiler is likely to result in it being condemned. As a result, we are activily looking at replacing the boiler over the next few months - hence our investigations into solar, heat pumps and gas boiler options.
Financial_exp: We do have the option of getting a replacement boiler under the Government /Supplier ECO scheme as my daughter lives with us and is currently unemployed. However, if there was an opportunity to install a vaiable and more envirnmentally friendly alternative then we would be very happy to be involved in this trial. We understand that the current asbestos flue may be a complication but we have investigated the options for removing this and are happy to cover the cost of removing the parts that need to be removed and making the rest safe.
Technology_exp: We believe that the Government needs to take a more proactive role in helping people in older properties to upgrade their homes, as well as ensuring that new homes meet very high standards. The current incentives seem somewhat misguided in that we can currently get substantial help to replace a gas system like for like but cant get enough help to make installing a greener alternative a viable option. We truly believe that heat pumps, highly insulated homes and heat recovery systems are the future and the sooner we get there the better. But the majority of the housing stock in the UK is older, draughty houses with highly inefficient and environmentally damaging heating systems. I am sure that the technology is there at the moment to address these problems but the public needs to be educated about the alternatives and it needs to be demonstrated that these are within financial reach of a far larger proportion of the population. We would be delighted to be part of a trial that could demonstrate that investment in greener energy systems for an older property is both financially viable and is capable of delivering the performance needed to effectively replace conventional heating systems.
Research_exp: For the reasons already stated. Unless it can be demonstrated that the new technologies are relevant for the majority of the population who live in older houses then it is hard to see how this country is going to make the changes in carbon emissions that it needs to. It is not enough for the Government and manufacturers of these technologies to demonstrate how effective they are in a new, highly specified house. That is widely accepted now but that isnt where the majority of energy wasteage occurs. If this trial is to make a difference then it needs to engage home owners like us who are highly committed to reducing our carbon footprint but restricted from doing so by the costs involved in upgrading the property we live in.
Planned_exp: For the reasons stated already but we would like to.
Replacement_exp: As already stated, we need to replace our current gas boiler and are close to committing to a replacement gas boiler under the ECO scheme.

Sustainability_exp: It is now a priority to reduce our environmental impact in any way we can and I would love to run our home with renewable energy
Future_exp: We have worked hard to reduce the carbon footprint of our home and this would be a welcome addition to our efforts
Financial_exp: Of course this would be amazing, but to think we would have green energy at the end of it would be incredible, especially as this will be our family home for many years to come
Technology_exp: We have always embraced new technology where we can  and this would be a natural next step. I would love to find out more about how it works
Research_exp: We would be honoured to take part in the research that would hopefully benefit a greener future for our children

Financial_exp: I cant afford a new boiler, or to undertake this work myself.
Research_exp: If it means that more homes will move to a sustainable source of heating, this reducing carbon output, I think this is worthwhile.
Replacement_exp: It doesnt need to be replaced, but our boiler is quite old.

Sustainability_exp: My dream would be to live in an eco house.  Being able to stay in our current home and achieve this would be even better.
Future_exp: We are retired now and a low maintenance house would be such a relief.  We want to stay in our home, but reduce our outgoings.  We would also like to do our bit for future generations.
Upgrade_exp: We need a new boiler and upgrading to a heat pump would be even better.  We have viewed houses with heat pumps and they are so warm and cosy and often without unsightly radiators.
Building_exp: We would love underfloor heating and even solar panels (subject to cost).
Financial_exp: We are on a fixed income now and we have to be very mindful of all our current and future expenses.
Technology_exp: I love modern homes and technology.  My passion is modern art, architecture and design. Anything I could do to modernise my home excites me and this allows me to do my bit to save the planet too!
Research_exp: This is an exciting project that could revolutionise heating in Britain and it would be wonderful to be a part of it.  I would be very proud to be able to say we were one of the first homes to take part in this study.
Planned_exp: We would love a heat pump, but our budget doesnt stretch that far!
Replacement_exp: We certainly need a new boiler as ours is well over 20 years old and is inefficient and costly.  It is not good for the environment or our finances.  We burn a lot of gas, but are always cold.

Building_exp: We have recently purchased our home, it is only electrically heated at the moment, we are looking for central heating options and we would prefer to install a green system over a gas, but the costs of a green system seem too high when compared to gas.
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt!  But in fact I was first drawn to this when researching a green installation option for our new home.
Replacement_exp: As mentioned above our new home has no central heating system so this would be a perfect opportunity to have a new green installation rather than gas.

My daughter dreads summer as gets too hot and I am worried already about winter as I can�t breathe!!

Sustainability_exp: I am really interested in decreasing the carbon footprint of the house and being part of the future of this.

Sustainability_exp: I want to make my house as green as possible to reduce my bills on a long term basis as ill not be moving for a long time and want to invest in my home
Future_exp: I have an interest in heat pumps and low carbon tech.
Upgrade_exp: Been considering changing to a heat pump as boiler is on its last legs, but in honesty i cannot afford the heat pump technology.  Been holding off replacing the boiler as hoped i could get a grant or find a way of installing a heat pump

Sustainability_exp: We have been working to implement ways we can reduce our impact on the environment. Small daily changes such as reducing plastic usage, recycling where we can etc. We chose not to install gas for this reason when we moved into the property and try to optimise our usage of electricity using economy 10 options. We feel that moving to an alternative heat source would significantly reduce the amount of the electricity we use - which is for heating. This will then improve our impact on the environment. The other thing we have looked at is solar panels but financially these are unviable at this time.
Future_exp: This naturally ties in with the above. As we move forwards greener sources for things that consume large amounts of energy such as heating will be key. I think heat pumps are a good alternative and have the added advantage of being low carbon.
Upgrade_exp: We are on economy 10 electricity only. an alternative source of energy is likely to only improve our current bills
Financial_exp: From investigation of these types of systems current prices would be prohibitive to us being able to install ourselves.
Technology_exp: As a scientist, I have generally keep up to date with how technology is evolving and how we can use it to minimise our impact on the world. To me the most exciting part is the mention of heat batteries earlier in the survey. Energy storage has been a limiting factor and it is great that improvements are being made that means changing to this type of technology is more sustainable in the long term.
Research_exp: Id be really excited to take part and support the research in this area. My scientific background means I am used to gathering data so would be interested in supporting anyway that I can.

Sustainability_exp: looking to get solar system as well so makes sence with heat pump

Financial_exp: yes and no, will just make it a bit quicker and have been planning this since we purchased property 2 years ago
Technology_exp: ashp are the way to go in the UK as winters dont go below 0 degrees  tbh, also thought and researched gshp but cost is much higher and would been a bore hole too, but with solar system air source heat pump is great
Research_exp: yes of course, very keep to help
Planned_exp: like I said before this opportunity will help speed things up and get everything running
Replacement_exp: not really but want to get carbon neutral and disconnect mains gas

Sustainability_exp: We are already making steps to move to a greener way of living from using as little plastic as possible (glass milk bottle deliveries), recycling and composting and hope to move to an electric car within a year or two.
Building_exp: We are planning a major building refurbishment in September and hope to install air-conditioning and solar panels. We will be adding a loft extension and moving the existing boilers so to swap out our gas boiler for something greener would fit in well to our plans.
Technology_exp: We use nest products in the house including a nest thermostat.
Research_exp: I work for an software company and head a team managing the IT infrastructure for R&D so I am well versed in the potential downsides of new technology and the require testing processes.

Sustainability_exp: I have fitted Solar PV, cavity wall insulation. additional loft insulation, smart heating since moving in. I want to reduce my overall carbon footprint as much as possible.
Future_exp: I have investigated the Sunamp system when visiting the Fully Charged Show event last year. However, our gas boiler continues to function well and scrapping it is a false economy at present.
Upgrade_exp: I have investigated this but my central heating uses microbore piping and I have been told that it may not be possible to get the required volume of water through since it comes from the heat pump at a lower temperature than a gas boiler.
Financial_exp: I have participated in trials such as using the Solar PV to heat my hot water and use it as a heat store. Im happy to share data and have some disruption in order to gain more insights into moving to a lower carbon model.
Technology_exp: My home battery and car charger are both smart to allow better, optimised use. I was an early adopter of the Hive heating control system from Centrica.
Research_exp: Keen to share data and get insights
Planned_exp: See comment above but happy to get a second opinion.

Sustainability_exp: We have gone to individually programmable TRVs on our radiators. We run a fairly cool home through the winter. I have tried to address all air leaks into the house. We have recently had triple glazing installed (for both noise and heat loss).
Future_exp: This is essential for the future for the future of the environment. Renewable heating along with insulation to a higher standard than what is currently legislated are the most important parameters for housing.
Upgrade_exp: A newer boiler only has an incremental impact and is not worth the investment if the lifespan is limited. The only other option open to us is external insulation but this is one of the most expensive solutions and payback time is very long.
Financial_exp: We have looked in the past but cost was prohibitive Vs payback time for the air source heat pump system
Technology_exp: We always look to the latest solutions when choosing upgrades to our home.
Research_exp: I am an automotive design engineer and love using the latest technology and trying to improve the status quo. The more people who use new technologies the more barriers are reduced for new entrants.
Replacement_exp: Or current boiler is 20 years old and has suffered several failures.

Future_exp: We are currently improving our home to make it as energy efficient as possible.
Building_exp: We are about to start kitchen renovations and will need to replace our existing boiler as part of this.
Financial_exp: At the moment the cost of these systems are prohibitively expensive for our family.
Research_exp: We are happy to be part of research if it benefits the future of heating systems installed in homes.
Planned_exp: We have been exploring alternatives to gas boilers and heated pump seems the best way forward.

Sustainability_exp: I believe we all generate too much carbon through burning fossil fuels and this is unsustainable for the world at large, putting future generations in severe danger if we do not take action.
Future_exp: I believe all new build properties should be fitted with a carbon neutral solution to heat for the reasons above and I believe that eventually we will be forced to not be powered by fossil fuels.
Financial_exp: It would be a great investment in the property for a small ask as being part of the trial.
Technology_exp: I would class myself as an early adopter and feel that anything like this is important to future development of our sustainability as a world.
Research_exp: If we do not carry out trials to see what is successful and measure the impact this has then we cannot make informed decisions as a world to what the best solution may be to climate change.

Sustainability_exp: While Im happy with the boiler I have - I can see that well be moving away from this technology - so look at technologies like heat pumps is very interesting to me.
Future_exp: Without this trial - Im unlikely to touch this boiler for 10-15 years. That might leave me having to adapt when the natural gas lines are changed or be left with old tech while everyone else moves on.
Upgrade_exp: My heating system works well - but I love new technology and would love to be able to move to a heat pump style system.
Technology_exp: Im very keen on new tech and low carbon tech. All lighting in the house is LED and Ive installed smart home monitors so that I can keep an eye on temperature control.
Research_exp: This is the way forward - and I dont mind being at the cutting edge of tech as we go forward.
Planned_exp: As above - boiler is relatively new. So wont change without this until it starts failing.

Sustainability_exp: It doesnt feel right to still be using gas CH when weve made the switch to full electric for cars and considering the ever decreasing grid carbon, however, the upfront investment cost is a big block, so weve put off making any changes in the hope of the costs reducing in future.
Future_exp: The heating is our remaining major ongoing contribution to CO2 and while we can choose electrify supplier etc to (hopefully) to drive renewable usage down, theres nothing we can do while we still use gas. I also love the idea of being more independent and self-sustainable in generating/using our energy (solar panels with storage being the next thing to tackle)
Upgrade_exp: Yes, the way of extracting something for (almost) nothing in energy terms makes total sense rather than ongoing fossil fuel use.
Building_exp: Were at a stage where we need to change carpets, where the garden could do with some re-turfing etc, so if floors need to be disturbed for cabling, or piping, or garden dug up for GS heat pump, its not the end of the world
Financial_exp: As mentioned above, the desire to move to a low/zero carbon is there, but the funds to invest in such a system arent!
Research_exp: Anything I can do to help. I am keen to support the low carbon future. My job as an engineer relies on gathering feedback and results, so I appreciate the need for detailed data and feedback to support system and service improvement.
Replacement_exp: Technically our heating still functions, though its a less efficient back boiler. Weve looked into the options for replacing it, but although a new gas CH system would be the cheapest method, I do not want to invest any money into something that feels so backwards. At the same time we cant afford a heat pump system, so have decided to wait and see, considering (hoping) there would be upcoming incentives to decarbonise heating.

Sustainability_exp: I had originally looked into CHP and heat pumps when first replacing the boiler but CHP seemed to have disappeared (presumably it didnt work) and heat pumps were not affordable to me. We know gas isnt sustainable as a form of heating, werent electricity from renewables (and therefore heat pumps) are together with increased levels of insultation.
Future_exp: Gas prices are only going to go up!
Upgrade_exp: Our heating system works fine as is - and Im aware that a heat pump may not be as effective until all radiators have been increased in size.
Financial_exp: I could not afford to change my heating system to a low carbon one myself.
Technology_exp: I am a keen follower of new tech - have do have a Wiser heating programmer (individual control of raditors that Ive replaced so far) and bits of home automation.
Research_exp: We are aware of the importance of reducing carbon emissions  and are more than willing to have some disruption in order to take part - Id also be very interested in monitoring the COP of the heat pump to see how well its doing.

Future_exp: Looking at the type of boiler and its location, we have never been inspired by the choices on offer to replace/relocate for little gain to product that does not seem as durable. The new technology seems to be a radical step into a different direction
Upgrade_exp: I know at some point my model will be deemed as unrepairable under my British Gas maintenance despite never breaking down. Having the chance to take part in something that may change the way heating systems are view in general is exciting
Financial_exp: Sure not completely free as sure there will be some expenditure related to the install of any  different system but the trail is very attractive as will provide a different option to what we would consider as a Normal replacement system.
Technology_exp: Work in IT so love all things that adopt new technology
Research_exp: It seems exciting for normal people to be engaged in this way, having a sample of mixed properties taking part provides a better overview than a special show house which will just end up looking like any other home heating advert
Planned_exp: Had not considered a heating pump, when we considered what to do when the boiler needed to be replaced it has never been suggested - saying that i guess no incentive for a gas company to mention it
Replacement_exp: Still works well,so wasnt top of my list

Building_exp: Although have recently moved in and are open to works being undertaken/refurbishment.
Planned_exp: Im fascinated by heat pumps and would love to explore whether this technology could help improve the efficiency of my home.

I think, too often, people presume that older properties cant take advantage of new, more efficient technology to help reduce a homes carbon footprint and bills. I think it would be interesting to explore what adaptations could be made to an older property.

Although our income may seem high (�50k+) living in the South of England is expensive and we do not have the spare funds to carry out the improvements we would like.....which is very frustrating.
Future_exp: It would be wonderful to be able to future proof our home and feel we are making every effort we can to bring change and slow down climate change and help the soaring temperatures in the Arctic
Upgrade_exp: I know that air source Heat Pumps are a realistic and practical way to heat your home whilst reducing your energy consumption.  It would be very exciting to think that we could do this at home.
Financial_exp: This is something that we would have undertaken as a priority if we had the necessary money available and it is frustrating that this has not been the case.
Technology_exp: We are always interested in new technology and it would be wonderful to be able to replace our old boiler with something so up to date.
Research_exp: I fully support and admire the work that this project is doing.  As more homes are improved to reduce energy usage, the greater the impact will be to reduce climate change....and as more people come across Heat Pumps in their everyday lives, at friends houses etc, the wider the impact can be, as more people adopt the system.

Sustainability_exp: We�ve taken steps to make an older, but well constructed property more efficient. We replaced the old boiler, changed all the windows, added increased loft insulation. I believe we should all be using less gas in domestic settings as it has a huge environmental impact. We�ve made our property more efficient but there is still work to do. Our gas use has dropped significantly since we made these investments but is still higher than I would like.
Future_exp: The shift to cleaner domestic heating is inevitable. Shifting to a more electric energy system which is supplied by an increase in renewable sources is also inevitable. I�m keen to prove that houses like mine which represent a great deal of properties in the U.K. can reduce their footprint - that�s critical to turning the tide in this country.
Upgrade_exp: I hear that heat pumps can turn 1KW of electricity into 4KW if heat energy. In future I would like to add PV to my house to generate the energy required to drive the pump, reducing my impact on the grid and eliminating fossil fuel usage.
Building_exp: In the next year we plan to extend our house which is likely to require reconfiguration of the roof. As such, a great time to do work up there. We also plan to replace our hot water tank during the works.
Financial_exp: There is plenty of conflicting opinion around the efficacy of such systems. I�m keen to prove the doubters wrong but it�s a big amount to risk to investing in.
Technology_exp: For example the Evohome smart radiator valve system we installed works great for us. We only hear the rooms we use as we use them. Technology has a key role to play in making us all more efficient. It comes with its quirks but we are more than happy to work with them for the efficiency it provides.
Research_exp: As said, I want to be able to prove that tradional U.K. housing stock can make use of these types of solutions. Retrofitting existing housing stock is crucial to making all domestic situations more efficiency. Let�s stop the inefficient burning of gas in our homes and prove that there is a better way!
Planned_exp: I had been considering PV, Thermal Store and heat pump system to make the most of the natural resources we have available. I had been waiting to see clearer examples of where this had been achieved in properties like mine. This is a great opportunity to test whether it is effective. If so, let�s shout it from the roof tops.
Replacement_exp: We had to replace our boiler as the one in the house when we bought it was 35 years old. Our gas used dropped significantly just by doing that!
Other_exp: Someone needs to take the first steps and generate the efficacy data to prove to everyone else that it�s the right thing to do. Let�s do it!!

Sustainability_exp: I already try and reduce my carbon footprint by following the guide lines turning off lighting or TV when not in room, having the hot water on a timer, not leave hot water tap running etc
Future_exp: I think there has to be a way forward to use less energy
Upgrade_exp: I think heat pumps are the way forward
Financial_exp: I would like to install a a greener alternative but at the moment the heat pumps are out of my price range
Technology_exp: I am really interested in heat pumps I work with special educational needs young people in a construction college and part of the course is learning about how the construction industry can help the environment and heat pumps were discussed in the plumbing course. As I support the students in the lessons I was fortunate to be able to learn about there value for the future of the environment.
Research_exp: I would really like to take part in this project as I would like to be able to share my experience with the students I support at the college as part of their learning experience
Planned_exp: I wanted to change to a heat pump but I dont believe I would be able to afford it
Replacement_exp: The heating system was installed in the house when it was built in 2000 and will need replacing I wanted to replace it with a heat source pump but realized due to cost I would not be able to achieve my aim
Other_exp: Please note my house is a town house so the room in the roof is how it was originally built

Sustainability_exp: Our house has poor heating (only one storage heater in the living room for the whole house) we would like to improve this and as we have the opportunity to improve our environmental impact it was something we were investigating before we came across this trial.
Future_exp: We see low carbon technology as the way forward and would like to make our contribution
Upgrade_exp: As previously mentioned our storage heater is archaic and we only have one. When purchasing the house we wanted to upgrade to a central heating system and feel we have an opportunity to do this being environmentally conscious
Building_exp: We are doing minor renovations as the house is dated and in need of some TLC
Financial_exp: If we are honest, as we are first time home-buyers we wouldnt be able to afford to install central heating for a few years as we would need to save the funds ourselves to do this
Technology_exp: During our research heat pumps have consistently come up as a attractive technology that we are interested in pursuing
Research_exp: We are very keen to get involved with something that is looking at low carbon technologies as we are passionate about doing our part to keep our reduce our impact on the environment
Planned_exp: Our research into heating systems showed us that heat pumps are a very efficient form of heating and we were investigating potentially installing one in the future. This opportunity would allow us to do so sooner.
Replacement_exp: Our one storage heater is old and inefficient. We are desperate to replace it as it is also expensive to run.

Sustainability_exp: I thought about installing a ground source heat pump when we did building work 7 years ago, but it could not be managed within our budget at the time.
Future_exp: We all have to do this to help reduce the impact of climate change
Upgrade_exp: Gas will have to be phased out in the coming decades, so the move makes sense.
Financial_exp: I wanted to look at ground source heat pumps 7 years ago, but didnt have the budget.

Sustainability_exp: We have been exploring different types of environmentally friendly heating systems and discovered it is a minefield and have no idea what would be the best for our property.
Future_exp: House was built in the 1700s and needs modernisation including a low carbon heating system, a great project to you as a show case, due to its age.
Upgrade_exp: We currently dont have any plumbed radiators, so we have looked at this as a solution, however  not sure how financially viable this is?
Building_exp: We have currently added a couple of small extensions and this is the perfect time to look at  the most suitable and environmentally friendly heating solution for the whole property.
Financial_exp: Obviously that would be of a huge benefit
Technology_exp: We have been trying to fact find on new technology, however have struggled to get any unbiased opinions.
Planned_exp: We really don;t know which solution is better suited to our property.  We have been looking at Heat pumps v solar, but are still undecided.  Some more information on this would be great.
Replacement_exp: currently we have no heating system, except for the open fire, so this is an ideal opportunity.

Future_exp: Low carbon technologies are extremely important as the global heating is getting more and more apparent. Every one of us has a duty to reduce their carbon footprint for the sake of our childrens future.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pumps seem to be the way forward to low carbon emissions when it comes to heating domestic housing. The technology is mature and has a high efficiency.
Building_exp: We will have our heating system upgrade by the next summer - the current system is very low efficiency, wasting energy is creting a huge carbon footprint.
Financial_exp: We understand the conversion from old gas boiler to heat pump is expensive and would not be available to us without such opportunity. We are really thinking green - walking instead of driving, supporting local businesses, doing our part, only what really counts, a proper low carbon footprint heating system is unavailable due to cost outside of our reach.
Technology_exp: Indeed, I read a lot about emerging and existing green technologies and also working in the field. As soon as we can do it, we will get rid our ICE vehicles and adopt an all-electric.
Research_exp: When first we read about this project we knew we have to try and apply - it is an amazing opportunity to take part in such an important research project! During my university days I also have studied heat flow and took part in a research project that examined low-scale, off-the-shelf solutions.
Planned_exp: Indeed, we do plan to adopt a heat pump system and looking for ways to reach that dream.
Replacement_exp: That is true - as described above we are indeed looking to replace our ageing gas boiler and would prefer go full green instead of a more modern gas boiler (which would still be better than what we have) that is currently available to us financially.
Other_exp: I have several friends thinking going full green, but hesitant to do so considering it is an unkown technology. We would like to show them that it is both available and a good solution. We are also extremely interested ourselves to see how much of a difference it makes and how it works.

Sustainability_exp: Done everything I can to reduce carbon footprint but the 16,000 kwh per year of gas consumption remains an insurmountable hurdle with any technology that appears well tested and reliable
Upgrade_exp: Been looking at this on and off for a long time but never got a quote as always appeared uneconomic and too much hassle given our normal sized radiators
Planned_exp: Done the research, cant make it stack up, and worried by the multititude of bad installation horror stories

Sustainability_exp: We have recently bought a 50s style bungalow and are attempting to renovate it into our dream property. It is really important to both of us that we build every element as greenly as possible and given there was no central heating there and we needed to put a new system in, we are considering using renewable options. We would prefer not to use gas in the property.
Future_exp: Yes, we are building a home we intend to settle our family in and we hope to install a system that will serve us and the property well for a long time.
Upgrade_exp: We need to upgrade the heating system anyway so our architect advised us to look into Heat pumps. We also intend to install underfloor heating so we think this could work well with the Heat pump.
Building_exp: As mentioned above we are renovating a detached bungalow which was in very poor condition and had been empty for a while. We have submitted plans to the council to build up into the loft and hope to have approval within a few weeks and we are just at the point of looking for a heating solution.
Financial_exp: Definitely! Its by far the biggest project we have ever taken on and we are quickly discovering there are lots of different costs. We hope to finish the project but we are unsure so being able to take advantage of a scheme this like would be absolutely huge for us. Particularly because there is no credit option currently for any of the heat pumps so finding that money upfront would be tricky for us.
Technology_exp: Yes we are amazed such a technology exists which is so green and efficient, we didnt know much about it until recently and we are still finding out about it but it seems like such a great solution for most peoples heating needs. We are also keen to explore any other new technology that can work with or alongside the Heat pump.
Research_exp: Yes we would be delighted to take part in this project, we believe every house should be fitted with these!
Planned_exp: We currently have no heating system in our new property, was previously heated with a hot water boiler and some oil heaters. Given we have to put a new system in it makes total sense to put in a green future proof solution and we had been looking into the possibility of a Heat pump and had some very expensive quotes!
Replacement_exp: As explained new property has no heating system currently.
Other_exp: It is our dream to turn our new home into a passive building or as close as we can. Part of that dream is not only for it to look nice but also that is has minimal impact on the environment and a heat pump would be a major step towards achieving this.

Sustainability_exp: I have an old Victorian property and I do not believe that I would be able to heat it sufficiently using a Heat Pump System. only fossil fuel will provide enough heat.
Future_exp: My gas boiler is now very old, and the day will come when I need to replace it. I am interested in an alternative type of heating system
Upgrade_exp: I do not think it will provide enough heat
Financial_exp: But I do want a heating system that works! (Ground Source system maybe???)
Technology_exp: My daughter lives in a new house with air source heating system, but her house is well insulated. My house will never be that well insulated. My brother is a retired gas fitter, so between us we have a fair idea as to what to expect. In a previous house that I lived in, I had fitted, a gas central heating system that was connected by a 1 inch pipe gravity feed system, with additional hot water provided by a solid fuel Rayburn! (Dating back to the ark)
Research_exp: See above. (Not sure if my wife will be as keen, if we find ourselves with out a decent hot water and heating system!)
Planned_exp: Because I do not believe it would provide sufficient heat.

Sustainability_exp: Retrofitting existing housing stock with clean heating will be crucial to reducing the UKs carbon emissions and I believe that heat pumps are the most suitable answer for most properties. Therefore, I am keen to be part of trials that will help develop this technology and hopefully drive down costs to make it feasible for large scale roll out.
Future_exp: I try to reduce my environmental impact and am conscious of my gas consumption but my primary motivation for being part of this trial is the hope that this trial will lead to the much wider take up of heat pumps in society
Upgrade_exp: Im very happy for my heating system to be upgraded but in terms of comfort I am fairly happy with my gas system
Financial_exp: I had looked at getting a heat pump installed previously but could not afford the up front cost. For them to be widely used the up front cost will have to reduce, or special financing be developed. I am hoping that this trial will help on the cost front
Technology_exp: Taking heat energy from the air and using it to heat your house and water is a great idea. Who wouldnt want to primarily source their heat energy from the air rather than fossil fuels?
Research_exp: I truly believe that heat pumps are an essential part of reducing our carbon emissions and therefore stabilising the climate and as such am very keen to be a part of a project that is helping to research and develop the retrofitting of them in UK houses
Planned_exp: I had looked into it but could not afford it

Sustainability_exp: I already have solar panels and an electric car. I am interested in heat pumps and energy storage for my solar panels. I am also interested in being able to use heat pumps to potentially cool the house in summer and heat it in winter. The high efficiency of these systems is also attractive. Our house was constructed 5 years ago and is very well insulated so would be suitable for low temperature radiators.
Future_exp: I have repeatedly looked at alternative heating systems. In our previous house I researched the potential for ground or air source heat pumps.  I ha e looked at houses in Canada that have very high levels of airtightedness that can then be heated using ground or air heat pumps.
Upgrade_exp: From my understanding the heat pump could be used with radiators (although they may need to be larger and it would be possible to add heating/cooling units.
Financial_exp: I saw details of the scheme and would like to participate. I have recently been looking at the options for replacing the gas central heating including heat pumps. I am waiting for details of the Covid scheme to assist with the cost of upgrading to more environmentally friendly heating sources.
Technology_exp: I have had an electric car since 2017 and solar panels for the last 2 years. I am keen to adopt new technology when it is at a cost that is able to provide a benefit with a reasonable prospect of repaying the initial outlay. This is why I have not yet purchased a battery to compliment the solar as the cost exceeds the benefit at current prices.
Research_exp: I have taken part in several market research exercises relating to electric cars and solar panels. I am keen to help furth and promote new technologies. This scheme would allow me to provide feedback to help improve the scheme for others.
Planned_exp: I am looking at replacing my heating for a heat pump if it makes financial sense. This scheme would allow me to do this.
Other_exp: I would like to be able to provide cooling to our house if possible.

Sustainability_exp: We bought an electric car last year and we have orders second one in early 202.  We shall then have no internal combustion engines for personal transport.  I know from my energy technology background that zero fossil fuelled home heating is the next big challenge.  \n\nI have a strong personal and technical interest in renewable technology.  I see either heat pump or hydrogen boilers as the way to go for home heating.  But there is no realistic prospect of any hydrogen distribution fed by green hydrogen generated by renewables.  Heat pumps are available technology but need to demonstrate that they can work in all types of houses - old and new, and small and large.  They need to be able to provide comfort at a price which is comparable to gas.  I do not expect a cost saving but just to be comparable is a step forward.  As with EVs early adopters will drive improved technology and lower costs.
Future_exp: Be great to live the dream of a house fit for a low carbon future.
Financial_exp: Yes and No - I cannot afford myself to replace the whole system with heat pumps and energy storage but I would be willing to pay something.
Technology_exp: I know it is not as simple as just replacing the boiler.  It needs in-depth technical knowledge to ensure heat pumps are correctly rated, radiators big enough, high grade heat for hot water provided.  It needs an expert to do it and is beyond my skill set or any local plumber.
Research_exp: I have 37 years technology experience in teh energy sector.  On retiring I did an MSc in Science Communication.  It would make a great blog to live this project and describe its outcome.

Sustainability_exp: We are excited by the potential of renewable energy and we see this is an affordable way to begin that process
Building_exp: We are building a kitchen extension in spring 2021 and would be very interested to know what features we could include in this, such as underfloor heating
Financial_exp: These steps towards renewable energy are not possible for us any other way.
Technology_exp: Family and friends have solar panels and electric cars, which we would love to do but arent in a place to financially at present
Research_exp: Keen to help in what sounds like an exciting development

Future_exp: As above - fitting a new condensing boiler 10 years ago did not result in any reduction in gas usage, so Im looking at what options we have to move away from that
Upgrade_exp: More not sure - Ive started looking at heat pumps, but current conditions dont really support investigations or the financial outlay.
Technology_exp: I work in IT and am a keen DIYer, so I like technical solutions to problems.

Sustainability_exp: I am really keen to reduce my carbon footprint by not being reliant on heating oil. About ten years ago I installed a small grid tied wind turbine to supplement my homes energy use, unfortunately it requires a lot of maintenance and has cost quite a bit of money to keep it working so I am now researching into a PV solar system.\nRecently I purchased a hybrid car for my wife and am looking into buying an electric vehicle for myself.
Financial_exp: To be honest, getting a free system would be great.
Technology_exp: Heat pump systems interest me and would be keen to have one. \nI visited the fully charged show at Silverstone last year and was really impressed by the Sunamp Uniq heat batteries.
Research_exp: This is a great opportunity to own an advanced heating system by ditching my old one.
Replacement_exp: My heating system is reliable so it�s not imperative to replace it.

Building_exp: Planning a loft conversions so would be interested in doing this as part of these works

Sustainability_exp: We are building a new house as the old one had no insulation. We have lots of roof on an adjacent barn and are looking to install 14kw of solar to help run an ashp but have struggled slightly as the builder/plumber are very traditional and want to use older technologies. there is no mains gas in our village so its oil for heating otherwise
Future_exp: We are building a new house as the old one had no insulation. We have lots of roof on an adjacent barn and are looking to install 14kw of solar to help run an ashp but have struggled slightly as the builder/plumber are very traditional and want to use older technologies.
Upgrade_exp: We are building a new house as the old one had no insulation. We have lots of roof on an adjacent barn and are looking to install 14kw of solar to help run an ashp but have struggled slightly as the builder/plumber are very traditional and want to use older technologies.
Building_exp: We are building a new house as the old one had no insulation. We have lots of roof on an adjacent barn and are looking to install 14kw of solar to help run an ashp but have struggled slightly as the builder/plumber are very traditional and want to use older technologies.
Financial_exp: It doesnt have to be free of charge I am happy to pay for it/contribute to it but help designing a state of the art system which future proofs is most important. there is no mains gas in our village so its oil for heating otherwise
Technology_exp: Things are moving quickly and it appears to us that most of the renewables solutions we are being offered or pushed towards are 5 years out of date, limited integration with solar and battery storage etc... due to inertia in the building trade.
Research_exp: I think its vitally important that people are aware of what really is out there. It has been a massive struggle to try and get our builder and his preferred plumber to push the boundaries and we are not sufficiently well informed to design our own system or validate what is being proposed by other providers.
Planned_exp: We are building a new house so a heat pump is a given. We do however want to ensure that the one we install is cost effective and efficient and isnt simply going to chew loads of grid electric when it could be a completely self sufficient system / offgrid system run from a solar array. As mentioned, cost subsidy is less important to us than expert guidance and design of the system.
Replacement_exp: We are building a new house so a heat pump is a given. We do however want to ensure that the one we install is cost effective and efficient and isnt simply going to chew loads of grid electric when it could be a completely self sufficient system / offgrid system run from a solar array. As mentioned, cost subsidy is less important to us than expert guidance and design of the system.
Other_exp: The property is part of a farm which we are slowly rewilding , turning into a wildlife haven and being self sufficient, zero impact is m,assively important to us.

Sustainability_exp: I have modern boiler, but feel I should be doing more for the environment
Future_exp: I have a large south facing roof which is ideal for Solar panels
Upgrade_exp: I would like a heat pump as I am aware of the savings available when associated with solar panels
Financial_exp: this leading edge technology is currently expensive and would be out of my range without a scheme like this.
Technology_exp: I would like to live in a carbon free environment
Research_exp: Anything i can do to advance the move to a carbon neutral environment would be great
Replacement_exp: My boiler is just under two years old, however, with a heat pump installed, it would be either redundant or just a backup

Building_exp: Planning to add an ensuite to our master suite which is situated in our loft conversion.

Sustainability_exp: I have two young children, and increasingly want to take action to leave a better planet for them. My work does involve developing energy efficiency products and services for large companies, but I am not sure whats available for me to do at home.
Future_exp: We now live in a home that we are happy to live in for many years to come, so I am hoping to look longer term for energy savings.
Upgrade_exp: My heating system is over 20 years old, so will need a refresh soon. I see heat pumps as a great option to stop burning so much gas.
Financial_exp: If my current boiler broke down and needed replacing in the next couple of years, I would not be able to afford to go for a heat pump system, so would likely have to settle for another gas boiler.
Technology_exp: Im an engineer and also have an interest in helping the environment, so always keen to have tech that suits both.
Planned_exp: Im at least wanting to go for heat pumps in the future, but wouldnt be able to afford it in the next few years.
Replacement_exp: My heating system is over 20 years old, so is due a refresh.

Future_exp: Britains houses are iconic, future proofing my house would mean it is possible to keep the looks , while lowering drastically carbon footprint.
Upgrade_exp: I 2scalways interested in that aspect, but was under impression it only/really works for rural areas( space) and newbuilds.
Financial_exp: Isn�t everyone? Some solutions like solar panels aren�t very economical. By the time they pay for themselves, they need replacing. The only good thing is, that�s it�s production carbon footprint doesn�t completely outweighs the carbon emission reduction.
Technology_exp: As mentioned earlier, really looking forward to new technologies that work well and could potentially be adopted in lots of homes across uk. It�s a huge opportunity With Britain toddling in the subject.
Research_exp: Wouldn�t it be great if home owners and builders across uk got a better understanding  and view of the great possibilities that are already out there to reduce the carbon emission and keep their bills down at the same time?

Sustainability_exp: Weve been trying to reduce our carbon footprint for many years. Weve done solar PV, solar thermal for hot water but upgrading our main heating system to a ground source heat pump somwe are able to go zero carbon is an important step in achieving this.
Future_exp: See above - we want to decarbonise now as we understand the planet will simply get hotter if we do nothing. We try to be early adopters of tech that will reduce greenhouse gas emissions and slow global warming.
Upgrade_exp: Ive already started looking at how we could do this, but being part of a trial and able to promote this technology nationally is very appealing.
Financial_exp: Id be lying if I said the opportunity to have a fully or part funded system wasnt attractive. But weve invested a lot of our own time and energy in getting ready for this but cant afford it just yet. So this trial would allow us to realise our dream earlier, for which the planet will thank us!
Technology_exp: Im interested in ground source heat pumps anyway as a scientist (which is why the trial is so appealing...) but were not adopters of tech for the sake of novelty. This will help us decarbonise just as solar PV and solar thermal have. Its hence a no-brainer to adopt and will be interesting too!
Research_exp: Im a research scientist. The idea of joining in with this trial is extremely attractive, plus I know what difference having co-operative participants makes when it comes to running trials!
Planned_exp: Our heating system is reaching end of life so we had planned to replace it with a ground source heat pump anyway. This gives us the opportunity to do.so, working with the trial to get what we want and provide useful data at the same time. A win-win for everyone.
Replacement_exp: See above - our boiler needs replacing but we want to decarbonise now rather than buying something we will have to dispose of in a few years, with all the negatives that brings.

Sustainability_exp: We are trying to address all aspects of our life. We have gone vegetarian, we now own an electric car and have reduced flights, often going to Europe by train
Future_exp: Would love to lower or carbon footprint
Financial_exp: Any help bring greener is welcomed. Also helping others through a trial is an added bonus.
Technology_exp: There are now so many choices it is hard to know which technology. Having some help picking a solution is great
Research_exp: I subscribe to offset earth (ecologi) and an a subscribe to Greenpeace. I want to save the planet for all species. We should all take it part in helping provide solutions and care for our planet. There is no planet b.

Sustainability_exp: With a shift in changing to greener energies, it seems like a no brainer that we should be made more aware of how we can adapt our homes for the long term. Houses in the uK are often very bad at being energy efficient, and this is key to achieving a zero carbon goal
Future_exp: Technologies such as heat pumps are likely to be the future of heating. Being leaders in this shift would be great for us to see the proof of concept
Upgrade_exp: Heat pumps seem a fantastic low carbon and future-proofed way of heating
Building_exp: We have renovated most parts of this house including getting rid of loft water tanks. The idea of upgrading and future-proofing our home sounds fantastic
Financial_exp: I am aware that the cost of retrofitting these systems is very high. This has put us off the idea of converting our home this way.
Technology_exp: Heat pumps seem to be the future of heating systems. It is incredible how they can draw energy from thin air to heat a home.
Research_exp: Schemes like this will aid to give better understandings on how we can meet our energy requirements in a low carbon way
Replacement_exp: although we have recently updated our system, it is sadly still a gas-mains system which as we are now very aware is polluting.

Sustainability_exp: The night storage heaters are very old and need replacing but I would like to be green with my heating, hence a heat pump. I currently have solar hot water and solar PV and an electric car.\nI have records in a spreadsheet of our daily electricity use since Sept 2011.
Future_exp: I need to install a heating system and I as I am not on the gas network it is either a heat pump system, or burning fossil fuels and I hope that burning fossil fuels will be not necessary soon
Financial_exp: Having just been made redundant a free of charge system would be very welcome!
Technology_exp: I have been interested in heat pumps and the Sunamp heat store since going to Fully Charged Live last year. I have always been an early adopter of technology and love explaining things to people.
Research_exp: I was a process scientist and running experiments and optimising processes was my job.
Planned_exp: I am planning on installing a heating system and a heat pump would be my preferred system. I have just had some quotes from local central heating installers, one of which was for a heat pump, though it was the most expensive.
Replacement_exp: We have night storage heaters that are over 30 years old.

Technology_exp: Id like to know how this works and if it is indeed more efficient than the current system I have which gives me instant hot water. Id also like to know how it uses existing pipe work and radiators and if there is a reduction of heat / power as a result of it using electricity.\nIm currently on a Smart Prepayment meter because of a previous trial, not because of any financial reasons. So it can be swapped.

Other_exp: I have always wanted a electricty only house heating system

Sustainability_exp: I am passionate about looking after the planet. I already have solar voltaic panels and an electric vehicle and my use of gas for heating is the biggest contributor to my carbon footprint. I have been watching heat pumps for a few years, but they are not something I can afford.
Future_exp: This would make the house as low carbon as possible meaning it will be good for future generations.
Financial_exp: As mentioned above, I have already paid for solar panels and an EV, but simply cannot afford a heat pump. I work part-time because I also care for my disabled wife, therefore my income is not high.
Technology_exp: Ive always been geeky, so love monitoring the output of my solar panels and the fuel consumption of my EV. A heat pump would be fascinating! My background is a degree in electronic engineering, but I dont work in that field any more, so all gadgets are welcomed!
Research_exp: I think that heat pumps should be widely adopted, but acknowledge that there price is prohibitive at present. Anything that can help move more people towards heat pumps instead of burning fossil fuels for heating needs maximum support. If I succeed in this, I will be using it to contact my local council and apply pressure for them to use similar technologies - I love the idea of ground source heat pumps installed under public parks to provide power for neighbouring homes.
Replacement_exp: Yes and no. The boiler is 14 years old, so is nearing its life end, but is functioning completely fine. I dont normally like replacing things until they are unusable!

Future_exp: As above - in addition, our house is a 1950s mid-terraced and as such, strategies for reducing the need for consumption are limited in scope, so being able to make that necessary consumption more efficient and environmentally friendly would be something I am keen on
Upgrade_exp: While the individual boiler in our house is fairly new (2 years old), the rest of the heating system is functional but not particularly modern or efficient.
Building_exp: This is our first home; the electrics are 45 years old so needs redoing, there is some immediately necessary redecorating. This means that wider refurbishment or building work isnt something we can really afford and we will have to wait some years before we can undertake it.
Financial_exp: See above - we are first time buyers raising our first child. The combined effect of having mortgage commitments, childcare costs, and initial necessary outlays eg to modernise the electrics means we have to be financially very cautious; even more so as due to covid we had to postpone dental work to when measures had eased, which incurred an unwelcome huge bill. Investing in low carbon tech is sadly definitely not something we could contemplate affording ourselves any time in the short to medium term future.
Technology_exp: Our house very much has the initial feel of the 1950s ex-council terraced housing which it is, and now setting up in it we are interested in how to make it sync with 21st century living - technologically and aesthetically. As it backs onto a railway line it has a lengthy back garden space, there is an undeveloped grass front garden down to the kerbside, and the back roof edge is south-facing, all of which make me intrigued at the possibilities that may be presented for upgrading its energy systems.
Research_exp: Keen to be involved in part of moving the country forward in its adoption of green tech and reduced reliance on fossil fuels / carbon emissions; would be a great opportunity for my family and I to benefit from modernised energy sourcing and efficiency measures - when I first saw this advertised I thought it must be a misleading advert/headline which you often get on social media as it sounded too good to be true! But I then briefly researched and thought I may as well apply as it could be a great opportunity.
Planned_exp: No realistic prospect of being able to afford a heat pump in the short to medium term future. Aware in very general terms of heat pumps but have not to the extent of any active planning.

Sustainability_exp: We have been slowly moving towards a low carbon impact for some years now by fitting solar PV and employing the most efficient systems we can afford.

Future_exp: We are interested in adapting our home to not use fossil fuels and retain more of the heat produced.  Our property is old but we believe modern technology will aid in making it fit for the future.
Upgrade_exp: As a non-fossil fuel approach, we are interested in a heat pump system.

Research_exp: We are keen to be involved in this as its a very interesting project and more energy suppliers should be taken similar innovative ideas to test the technology and move it forward.
Planned_exp: We are, but currently cannot afford to adopt all the technology required to reduce our carbon footprint substantially.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler still has a lot of life left in it, but it is a gas boiler and we want to move away from using fossil fuels.

Sustainability_exp: Our boiler is very close to the end of its life, it needs regular repairs coverd by a policy with Worcester Bosch for servicing and repairs. The last engineer told us we may not have a service contract much longer as parts for the boiler are running out due to its age. We would love to have a more sustainable solution and this would be a great time to install one, however we could not afford it as we are self employed gardeners living on a relatively small income.
Future_exp: We are a family that cares deeply about the environment and will embrace any opportunity to do things in the least damagin way we can. We are stuck with old cars and an old boiler due to financial constraints, so an opportunity like this would be very, very gratefully received. We would glady contribute to any ongoing research as required to help with the move away from fossil fuels for all in the future.
Upgrade_exp: We have looked into this as a better solution than a new gas boiler, but sadly it is financially out of reac to us.
Financial_exp: We had a terrible winter gardening and have had to share the childcare through this pandemic, so having our boiler on its last legs is a disater for us financially. We would be so greateful for help, and even more grateful to be able to reduce our carbon footprint as a family. Thank you for running this scheme!
Technology_exp: Anything that means we do less harm to the planet is very much a good thing.
Research_exp: It would be the leastwe could do in return for a chance to have a more sustainable home. We would also be glad to contribute in terms of it being good for the everyone if we can make these solutions more viable for all, and that they are the best they can be.
Planned_exp: I wish we could afford to tick yes!
Replacement_exp: As mentioned before, our gas combi boler is at least 21 years old and is on its last legs. Our service and repair contract is likely to be withdrawn very soon as they will no longer have parts for it.

Future_exp: but I am more interested n reducing my emissions rather than the future of my house.

Upgrade_exp: Boiler is at capacity heating house and likely needs upgrading

Sustainability_exp: Working within the electricity industry Im well aware how the world is impacted by the use of fossil fuels. Having an older house with old style heating arrangements is a massive carbon emitter so Ive always been keen to reduce emissions.
Future_exp: Low carbon is the future and needs to be rolled out in more homes quicker to try and combat the already rising rate of climate change.

Sustainability_exp: I totally endorse the need to lower our greenhouse gas emmissions and am intrigued to see how this new technology will aid that aim.
Future_exp: I hope to see this technology as a solution to the uk s future solution and would like to help in this trial

Replacement_exp: Within the next 2 to 3 years would have to replace the boiler anyway so a great opportunity.

Sustainability_exp: Interested in installing low carbon heating and Passivhaus design to reduce carbon footprint. Currently refurbishing the property to a high standard and would like to use a low carbon heating source if possible.

Since home heating generates a significant part of our national carbon footprint, I am very keen to reduce my contribution.  I am looking for an integrated solution that covers space heating and electrical power. I plan to invest in an electric car sometime in the next 5 years or so.
Future_exp: My current oil boiler is inefficient and needs replacing. I am keen to adopt one or more sustainable (i.e. low carbon) technologies to meet the needs described above.
Upgrade_exp: Of the likely future technologies (solar, wind, hydrogen (replacing natural gas) and heat pumps), I am looking at a combination of solar and heat pump to provide both space heating and power.
Building_exp: The original bungalow was extended horizontally about 20 years ago. In 2009, we  extended the main dwellling into the roof and highly insulated the whole building.  I have fairly large radiators for all the rooms but do not have sufficient space under the floor to install underfloor heating.
Financial_exp: Of course a free offer would be attractive.  However, I would be prepared to contribute, say, 2/3rds of the cost if I received an integrated design for both space heating and power and you undertook the whole installation.
Technology_exp: As a semi-retired engineering manager, I am intrigued by a number of these technologies at both micro- (household) and macro- (national) scales. I would happily be an early adopter in order to help this journey progress a bit more smoothly.
Research_exp: I would be happy to participate in data-gathering trials and identifying lessons.  I have just spent 20 years consulting on a wide variety of topics, identifying existing shortfalls and designing innovative solutions, most of which have successfully been adopted by the client. I would willingly give up to 1-2 days/week to support the work.
Planned_exp: I havent decided yet to change to a heat pump since my investigations are still underway.  However, I do see it as a choice between types of heat pump in a mix with solar PV, rather than no heat pump at all.  Although I have found several companies who will design either space heating or power generation systems, I have yet to find one which will provide an integrated solution.
Replacement_exp: Replacement is important but only within a wider integrated system design, as described above.
Other_exp: Do you have any idea of likely timescales for (a) a decision on whether I can participate, and (b) when the work might commence? [I need to manage down my oil stock, boiler maintenance etc].  Many thanks

Sustainability_exp: We are aiming to reduce our carbon footprint as far as possible in light of the Paris Agreement and the UK Net Zero 2050 policy
Future_exp: We have recently upgraded our kitchen electrical appliances (all electric) and as part of this the gas supply to our hob was capped-off.  We believe that heat-pumps are the way forward for well-insulated homes and we are keen to make this change as soon as possible.
Upgrade_exp: A heat-pump is the only low-carbon energy technology that is truly suitable for our house.  As we are in a conservation area we are unlikely to get planning permission for roof-mounted technologies.  The roof is also partially shaded.  Therefore, a heat-pump is the only viable low-carbon technology that we could use.
Financial_exp: Yes, but we are also keen to become as low-carbon as possible.
Technology_exp: I have been interested in heat-pumps for a while.  Unfortunately our previous home was not suitable for one.  Our current home appears to be much more suitable.
Research_exp: Yes - very happy to participate, provided data and demonstrate to interested neighbours.
Planned_exp: Our current boiler works well but is around 10-years old.  We would seriously consider a heat pump if we had to replace the gas boiler, but the relatively high cost is a key barrier for us.
Replacement_exp: Not at the moment but perhaps in less than 3-5 years time.

As stated all external walls  have cavity Wall Insulation( Rockwool), Triple glazing to the front and Double to the Rear.  Even though we are in a conservation area- we are exempt from this because of the late build of our property. Our Property is on a Hill, with the front facing south and the rear facing north.
Upgrade_exp: a work colleague that lives in Sweden has an air pump and ground pump for heating his house.  and find it costly to maintain, I have no issue with this as long as the savings outstrip these extra costs.  I am willing to share the details of the project  to show what can be done.
Building_exp: old houses always need work. We are looking to upgrade the boiler and hot water tank in the next year. We are happy to move related technology to other parts of the house to make things more efficient.

Replacement_exp: My Boiler is more than 20 years old, even though it is serviced  yearly- its not very efficient

We believe replacing the (very old) oil boiler for a heat pump is the right thing for us and the planet (Carbon/CO2) but need to either work out the details ourselves or find somebody we trust to advise us. Im also concerned about the other parts of the heating system that should or would need to be replaced if we had a boiler that operated at lower temperatures (ie do we need to replace all the radiators)

Sustainability_exp: Have been looking at a number of options to be greener E.g solar panels and storage batteries etc but the slow return on investment vs.upfront cost is still preventing us from really improving our credentials in this space.  I liked the sound of this opportunity as it would give us the chance to play our part without the significant upfront investment.
Future_exp: Our need to cut carbon emissions is clear, global warming is real.  We already take our gas and electricity from a green supplier but burning gas will never be carbon neutral.  Keen to heat our house another way that further reduces our carbon footprint.
Upgrade_exp: Our heating system is less than 10 years old so not ineffient or in need or replacement as such.

However, we do want to play our part in carbon reduction and so the free nature of this does appeal of course.
Technology_exp: Technology generally fascinates me and I certainly like to utilise it where there is value.  Heat pumps are interesting as on the face of it the science is fairly basic but the impact it could have for a low carbon future, if it works efficiently/effectively is huge.
Research_exp: Sounds like a great opportunity to help get meaningful data on the viability of these solutions for use in the future.

Ive recently completed the Cambridge short course on Business Sustainability Management and always looking for ways to reduce our environmental impact and help with the transition to a low carbon economy.
