Sustainability_exp: Due to the size and construction of this house and our desire to reduce our carbon impact, I am really keen to understand if we can do more to reduce our carbon impact. We have already migrated to a relatively modern boiler, have been slowly working to insulate underfloor and have brought a PHEV car.
Future_exp: We really like the idea of using air sourced or ground sourced heat to reduce our carbon impact.
Building_exp: We have stalled work on our house including installing underfloor heating with a secondary heat source to drive a reduction in carbon efficiencies.
Financial_exp: While for everyone money is a limiting factor, we would not be able to make significant carbon impacts on this house without support.
Technology_exp: Working in technology and been an advocate of carbon reduction I am extremely keen to understand more how this and I could help the carbon migration. We are more than happy to share consumption data to support this project.
Research_exp: As a wider family of tech and research centred people, we are extremely interested to understand if we can support the research project.
Planned_exp: I would love to have a heat pump but I simply can not afford the installation costs, give our large floor area it would be ideal for our house which is unfortunate.
Replacement_exp: Replacing the hot water tank with a secondary coil system with an additional heating source would likely significantly reduce our heating requirements but the system is functional.

Sustainability_exp: I have solar panels and am very interested in ways of reducing my environmental impact.
Technology_exp: I believe that new green technology is the way of the future. I think micro electricity grids are the way forward to get our whole country on sustainable green energy.
Replacement_exp: Its very old and I have been wanting to replace it for ages but didnt want another gas appliance.

Sustainability_exp: I am very concerned that we are not making fast enough progress in reaching net zero carbon by 2050, let alone by 2030 which is a tougher target but should be aimed for if the planet is going to remain habitable for humankind
Future_exp: I installed a wood burning stove a few years ago and am alarmed at the pollution it gives out which even in this suburban location can damage health. The main source of heat is by burning gas and thus raising carbon emissions.\nThe only future is to use electricity for all our domestic needs
Upgrade_exp: Purchasing electricity from the grid for heating and hot water could be a substitute for gas but is very inefficient and expensive. A heat pump is a way of keeping electricity use to a minimum whilst retaining comfort.
Financial_exp: I want to continue improving the thermal performance of the house but have limited resources. This would therefore release some of my resources to do other improvements to get nearer to net zero carbon.
Technology_exp: I had thought that underfloor heating would be required throughout the house. But you are suggesting that the change over would be less intrusive that I thought. This sounds like the technology that could be used to replace gas boilers across the UK
Research_exp: I am a retired architect, and have become increasingly interested in reducing everyones carbon footprint. This is a great challenge and your installation could demonstrate how this can be done in our housing stock. I would be happy to help publicise it.
Planned_exp: I have looked into making the change but it always seems too expensive and beyond my financial resources.
Replacement_exp: The gas boiler was replaced in 2016 and has a number of years life in it: I would not want it to be gas fired again but to date I have not found an affordable alternative.
Other_exp: I am ashamed that I have contributed to the climate change crisis, at home and at work, and wish to make some amends, so I can look my new grand-daughter in the face and say: I did something to resolve the crisis.

Sustainability_exp: I just upgraded my heating system.
Future_exp: Would like to reduce energy bills and be more independent.
Technology_exp: I like having technology in my house.

Sustainability_exp: This is the way of the future. The reduction of the use of Carbon and moving towards renewable energies
Future_exp: This is the way we have to move - towards renewable energy. It is going to reduce costs and guilt.
Upgrade_exp: The heat pump is a very efficient way to get heat from the environment. From what I understand, it develops 4 times the energy from the original energy that is put in.
Building_exp: We are refurbishing the property to the current standards.
Financial_exp: Of course. IT is a win win situation. I benefit from the new technology and you benefit from the data, user experience and testimonial/review that I can give.
Technology_exp: I have always willing to try new things. However, there is so much "fake news" around that I do not know who to believe. If it is free, there must be some credibility behind it. IF it is "fake news", they cannot get the credible equipment and data to support it.
Research_exp: I have been a research scientist (forensic science with Scotland Yard) and this is part of my up-bringing or career - try things and see whether it works. It is only with credible data /results that one can show that the method works and move forward from there.
Planned_exp: I have been looking around for a heat pump but it is too pricey for my budget.
Replacement_exp: My Potterton boiler is about 30 years old. It needs replacing.

Sustainability_exp: Always been interested in heat pumps but been put off by the cost.
Future_exp: Have put in many elements, external insulation, double glazing, solar panels. Am interested in going the whole hog.
Technology_exp: As mentioned have a number of elements eg solar panels and want to go further. I visited a couple of houses with heat pumps as part of Action Surrey and opened my house for others to see.
Research_exp: I have been part of Action Surreys open days and have shown people the benefits of the EWI.

Sustainability_exp: I think we should try to help and as I am unemployed I had the time and energy to pursue it.
Upgrade_exp: know very little but have googled a little and it seems interesting
Technology_exp: You cant get nothing from nothing, but it seems there are ways to get something from less which is fantastic
Research_exp: Sounds like a really interesting project
Replacement_exp: Everything is at least 26 years old and the boiler older so it is about time

Sustainability_exp: Having had solar hot water for a number of years, I am interested in the opportunity of making my heating greener too.
Upgrade_exp: My heating boiler will need replacing soon so I am interested in going with a greener solution. Heat pumps were not around when I looked into this before and I do not know anything about the technology
Building_exp: I am starting to look at replacing my boiler so a green technology would be a good solution.
Technology_exp: I had not heard of heat pumps so I think they are quite new. However, (having read a little about them) they could be a good alternative to solar panels for the UKs temperamental weather.
Research_exp: Having had solar water for over 10 years, I am rather dismayed that there are not more houses that have embraced green technology. Taking part in the trial would be a good way of helping broadcast the benefits of green technology for home owners. My case could be a good example as I would be replacing a boiler that is reaching the end of its life.
Other_exp: My 15 year old has been inspired by Greta Thunberg and David Attenborough and is keen that we as a family take action to help stop climate change

Sustainability_exp: Whilst we subscribe to green energy from our supplier we know we can and want to do more. Having launched new products and ideas for almost 20 years, I know the value of quality feedback during the pilot phase. Bringing a commercial and customer view will hopefully provide constructive feedback to Government on this initiative.
Future_exp: When we first moved in we investigated a domestic wind turbine. The writing is on the wall for gas, oil and other legacy heating solutions. Early adoption typically demands a price premium so an incentive to get there is a bonus!
Upgrade_exp: Deep bore ground source heat pumps seem the more pragmatic way to get this solution to a critical mass, quickly (given the average size of a new build garden).
Building_exp: We are looking to reengineer the rear of our house that would allow us to make space for required equipment in a utility room with a suitable outdoor wall close to likely bore holes, with easy access for external armoured cabling and water flow pipes (away from utilities serving the house with off-road space and access)
Financial_exp: Doing the right thing for limited cost! As mentioned, I see the trade being our family commitment to quality and timely feedback to the programme.
Technology_exp: I work in a job that pays me to review and introduce emerging technology. A bright idea or perfect product is only one part - matching it up to a use case and driving consumption is what makes it a success.
Research_exp: I spent time in a strategy role for a FTSE 100 company so understand that passion can get you to the table to pitch but the pitch needs to be data driven to get buy-in from key stakeholders. I want to help get the data and prove the case.
Planned_exp: More investigating than planning. But keen to affect a change sooner rather than later.

Sustainability_exp: As a family we are very interested in green energy and have strong desires to reduce our carbon footprint as much as possible. My wife actually works in the green energy sector, responsible for investment in solar and wind energy across the globe. We would be delighted to take part in this initiative and would be willing to provide as much feedback, questionnaires or interviews, to help you obtain the best possible result for your trial. Thanks!
Future_exp: Everybody has a responsibility to reduce their carbon emissions and we would be very honoured to take part in this trial, with the hope that it will drive a migration away from traditional heating systems, to low carbon solutions, in the coming years.
Upgrade_exp: Our system is dated with the boiler now over 10 years over. It is also painful seeing the amount of Gas kWh being burnt, when we could be using an environmentally friendly alternative! Installing a heat pump will be an excellent, carbon efficient solution to replace our old and polluting gas based system.
Building_exp: We aren�t currently planning to undertake any building works, other than plans to upgrade our insulation and windows.
Financial_exp: We moved into our property (first time buyers) in November 2019 and we have always been interested in making our home as energy efficient as possible (having been unable to do so in our rented properties). Cost is of course a factor, as our insulation  will also need improving as part of a heat pump installation, and we aren�t currently in a position to spend >�10k at the moment. Being accepted into this trial would allow us to move to a low carbon solution much faster than we dreamed, whilst also helping to provide valuable feedback to exploring mass implementation of green heating.
Technology_exp: We love new technology, having installed whole house LED lighting with motion sensors and WiFi heating controls immediately after moving into our property.\n\nWe have also recently installed x2 Daikin A+++ R32 Air Conditioning units in the most frequently used rooms - the living room and master bedroom. This is because we couldn�t afford to replace our entire heating system / upgrade insulation so choose to make sure we could operate two rooms efficiently during summer and winter, without using the main gas heating system. We will of course commit to not using this for the duration of the trial, as I presume this will impact the results.
Research_exp: We will provide as much time, feedback, data and help as you require. We promise to help as much as we can!
Planned_exp: As mentioned above, we have always had an interest in low carbon heating systems and the new technology implemented into modern heat pumps makes them an excellent alternative to gas boilers.
Replacement_exp: Our system is dated and is need of replacement. Being able to move to a low carbon solution now will be fantastic.
Other_exp: We would love to take part in this trial and will do everything we can to ensure you receive as much feedback and information you require. It would be a real honour to be involved in this amazing project, hopefully helping to steer the UK in the right direction- towards a carbon zero future! Thanks
Measures_Recommend: Loft Insulation; Wall insulation; Draft Proofing

Sustainability_exp: This is to me the main driver behind my application to this trial. I would really like to reduce my carbon footprint and therefore would like to move away from a gas boiler and also reduce if possible the energy losses of the house.
Always keen to reduce carbon emissions in any way possible

Future_exp: The governments plans to become carbon neutral means that people are (hopefully) going to becoming increasing aware of the disadvantages of gas heating systems. Our family has had the benefit of living and growing up in a wonderful environment and we want the house to continue to do this for families in the  future.  A low carbon heating system will help to make it an attractive home for future families and to continue the enjoyment that we have had.
Upgrade_exp: However, our boiler may be nearing the end of its life in which event we would want to consider upgrading the heating system in which event a Heat pump could be a way of doing this.
Financial_exp: Although we are wanting to reduce our carbon footprint the cost of installing the technology is probably too high for us unless it became absolutely necessary
Research_exp: As mentioned earlier I want  to encourage others to use non carbon technology wherever possible.  This form of heating is an excellent example.

Sustainability_exp: I have already tried with some success to future-proof and minimise the running costs of my house with Nordan windows and doors, cavity and roof insulation (reduced gas bills), and solar panels (hot water during the summer months, greatly reduced electricity bills).
Future_exp: The forthcoming legislation means Ill have to change the gas boiler, so Im very keen to explore ways in which I can upgrade my heating system and minimise my environmental impact, especially by using newer low carbon technology.
Upgrade_exp: A few years ago I looked at ground- and air-to-air source heating but I was advised it was uneconomic for my property. Newer technological developments may mean a heat pump is now a viable option for upgrading the heating system in my home.
Financial_exp: From November Ill be a pensioner, so Im very keen to future-proof my homes heating and hot water with the most effective technology and reduce the running costs as much as possible. The advice I received and the potential cost put me off a heat pump, so one thats free of charge will be very attractive and let me achieve my ambition to really future-proof my home for the foreseeable future.
Technology_exp: I like the idea of turning a house built in 1924 into one thats using the latest technology for its heating and hot water. I upgraded the solar panel system using micro-inverters and an iBoost system in order to get free hot water for the summer months. I have also installed a Nest system for greater security.
Research_exp: Im a keen supporter of new technology being used in the UKs housing stock to reduce the running costs and to minimise its environmental impact. So to do the most I can for my own home to help set an example of whats possible and what can be achieved makes huge sense to me.
Planned_exp: I have looked at this technology a few years ago and was very keen until consultants advised it was uneconomic in my case. I also realised that I needed to try to maximise the insulation of my home, so I invested in Norwegian double glazing (the best I could afford) and retro-fitted cavity and loft insulation. Having been attracted to heat pump technology initially, and seen what it could do in a modern home, Im still very keen to see what the latest heat pump technology can do for me and my home.
Replacement_exp: Gas boilers will be banned in new build property by 2025, and their replacement in older properties will be similarly encouraged, so this initiative from Ovo Energy represents the ideal opportunity to do that for my home.
Other_exp: Reliance on fossil fuels has to be reduced as soon as possible in all sorts of ways. Heat pumps for homes is a far more environmentally sustainable way to heat a property.

Replacement_exp: Storage heaters even though they are up to date are costly to run and dont provide much heat

Future_exp: I believe we will need widespread adoption of heat pumps to meet our national carbon reduction targets. Installing a heat pump would make an old house more fit for the future.
Upgrade_exp: My current gas boiler is very old (1980s) and inefficient. While it is still working, I am increasingly concerned by the carbon impact of having such an inefficient boiler
Financial_exp: I have recently reduced my working hours to part-time, as a step towards retirement, so have a lower income, which would make the capital costs of a heat pump more difficult to afford.
Technology_exp: As outlined above, I believe we will need widespread adoption of heat pumps in the UK to hit our national carbon reduction targets. I hope that by getting a heat pump, I can encourage others to do so too.
Research_exp: I am interested in exploring what can be done to make an old house more environmentally sustainable, with measures that have a reasonable payback period
Planned_exp: I am looking at heat pumps, to see if I will be able to afford one
Replacement_exp: My current gas boiler is very old (1980s) and inefficient. While it is still working, I am increasingly concerned by the carbon impact of having such an inefficient boiler

Future_exp: i am absolutely committed to achieving this and also being an evangelist to encourage others.
Upgrade_exp: As a keen adopter of new technology and understanding it isnt just plug and go, providing feedback will help everyone.
Financial_exp: who isnt attracted by the offer of free, but this isnt the primary driver. The new tech and reduced carbon and being a family that can cope and embrace new tech and evangelise it is most important.
Technology_exp: please see my previous answer. As an active member on the v2g trial i know what is needed here
Research_exp: research and data is my life (professionally and hobbywise) and aligning these with low carbon initiatives is a perfect fit
Planned_exp: technically i am indecided but there wasnt a button on this. I am keen on some low carbon initiative so this seems suitable.
Replacement_exp: it wasnt when i applied ! But i am never one to look a possible gift horse in the mouth as this meets the low carbon aims and new technologies goals too. Reducing fossil fuel usage.
Other_exp: as an active ovo forum member i feel i can really help advise others too in this area and encourage plan zero.
Measures_Recommend: Loft Insulation; Wall insulation; Draft Proofing

Future_exp: Two small kids, big changes needed globally, so if we can educate them, whilst supporting the low carbon transition, brilliant.
Upgrade_exp: Our heating is nearing its age and weve explored solar pv (+battery) etc, EV charging, Agile tariffs and so on, so were keen to support such a trial
Building_exp: Were permanently refurbing, its an ex 50s council house so a perfect use case for us to trial smart homes
Technology_exp: Renewable energy guru so I have to live and breathe it. Im also the Co-founder of an energy development and investment company that would gladly share the benefits on our public platform.
Research_exp: As above, happy to share data in the public domain, as is dictated.
Planned_exp: I dont know enough about them - electricity, yes, heat, less so, apart from building CHPs years ago.
Other_exp: Were keen to shift a 50s former council house into the next generation to show LAs how easy it actually is, particularly given the recent announcements on refurb and EE grants. Just filling cavity walls with insulation will kill houses, they need PV (not all pumping onto the network as we cant handle it) and off peak heat stores, even just simple hot water tanks heating up during wind and PV peaks. Filling cavity walls is akin to drowning - the building needs to breathe, unless it was built that way.

Future_exp: my home is currently heated by Oil, I see this has out of date and bad for the environment, adopting low carbon technology is something everyone should be working towards
Technology_exp: Im a technologist, having a Bachelors degree in physics and have worked in IT my entire career, Im keen to be actively involved in new technologies and benift from them. the Idea to heating my home with the ambient heat energy of the outside is quite exciting (in a nerdy way)
Research_exp: I would like to do my part in proving the viabiliity of these technologies so they can be adopted quicker by the wider public and thus reduce carbon emissions.

Future_exp: Technology is the way of the future and seeing these great ideas is something we are interested in
Upgrade_exp: We live in a 1950s build that would be perfect for a technology upgrade
Building_exp: We are fairly new home owners and have upgrades that we want doing and this would be a great extra

Technology_exp: 100% technology is the future and if we can be part of helping bringing in this sort of technology we�d be happy to help

Planned_exp: This isn�t something we thought about due to costs but this is a great way of doing it
Replacement_exp: We�ve got a 1950s build house with and old boiler so it would be great to upgrade it

Building_exp: We are due to get a small extension early next year.
Planned_exp: Wasnt aware it was an option previously!

Future_exp: We have taken action on the simple things like changing to LED lighting, other more expensive items are on the agenda however the expense has been the barrier.
Upgrade_exp: I am very interested in the heat pump technology however in the past it has been outside of my price range. Neither myself or my wife are getting any younger so its time we thought about our future.
Financial_exp: As i said previously, a heat pump has been on our agenda fro a while but the cost has been prohibitive.
Technology_exp: We have recently (the last couple of years) installed a google system and find it very easy and accessible, i believe a heat pump can work alongside this technology.
Research_exp: I am happy to have your product installed and am willing to incorporate any measuring equipment you may want to include.
Planned_exp: As i said previously, we have been looking at this type of technology for a while but the cost has been the barrier
Replacement_exp: Most definitely, Our system is very old and very expensive.

Upgrade_exp: My home is currently heated by a gas boiler older than 10 years and I would like to replace this using a renewable heat method.
Financial_exp: As I will have insulation issues to address also, this would help in a big way.
Technology_exp: I am keen to adopt the use all new technology enabling a greener environment.

Upgrade_exp: The boiler is over 30 years old and I want to replace it with a green alternative
Planned_exp: I think a heat pump is the most likely alternative I will use when I replace my boiler
Replacement_exp: Boiler over 30 years old. Reliable but nearing the end of its life and probably nowhere near as efficient as could be achieved.

Future_exp: My solar panels are 18 months old. I use them to heat my water, it seems to me there are many ways to improve the way we live
Upgrade_exp: Grudges are efficient as the heat they produce, costs less that the electricity used. In winter, it seems this would be a great way to heat the house
Financial_exp: Every thing is expensive, free helps.
Technology_exp: I work for a tech company.  I enjoy integrating tech into the home, to make life easier/better. The nest thermostat means heating/ water is off unless we are home. I can set that from the other side of the planet.
Research_exp: If this turns out to be the way forward, then it can benefit everybody to have examples where this has improved our carbon footprint.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is less that 1 year okd

Future_exp: Boiler is approaching 15 years old, so we will have to replace, preferably in a sustainable manner
Financial_exp: Not going to lie, this would be great!
Technology_exp: I have tried to add energy saving functions to central heating before and would be keen  to continue.
Research_exp: Happy to building and plumbing work to complete this project
Replacement_exp: Not immediately, but certainly within 5 years

Future_exp: I have concerns about fad products but see that low carbon technologies are the way forward given finite resources
Upgrade_exp: I would be very interested in this. our builder was not keen but I think this is lack of awareness and prefers to do things �as usual�
Building_exp: The house is currently being built-  having demolished our 1960s house that was very inefficient energy wise and poorly built in January. The new house is half built brick wise now - delays due to COVID pandemic
Financial_exp: Yes as heat pumps seem expensive compared to gas boilers
Technology_exp: Definitely intrigues us and we are confident in using new technologies
Research_exp: Due to the impact on the environment of all the new housing the government is keen to build, we feel our house would be perfect to be a test case. We have thickly insulated the walls and have a solid block floor (Rather than wood) between the 2 stories to help insulate the house as much as we can.
Planned_exp: Undecided due to costs/our builder putting us off
Replacement_exp: Unclear question/; we need a heating system and have agreed to gas boiler and underfloor heating but are not sure this is the best solution ecologically/financially

Future_exp: You�ll never future-proof. Renewable technologies will continue to improve, so it will always be catch-up.
Upgrade_exp: My heating works well, but is dependent on fossil fuels.
Financial_exp: With most technologies early adopters pay a premium. As the technology becomes more widely used, it gets cheaper. This would let us be early adopters without the price premium.
Technology_exp: I am interested in the technology, but that�s not why I�m keen to take part.
Research_exp: Low-carbon Housing could make a major contribution to reducing our footprint. Trying it out is the only way to find out what works in the practical sense.
Planned_exp: I would, but the up-front cost is too much at the moment.

Future_exp: The burning of gas for heating is not sustainable.  I would not want to support the gas industry by spending my money on a replacement gas boiler when mine fails.  I have already started the journey by adding insulation and underfloor heating on the ground floor.  Where radiators have been used upstairs, I have oversized them to allow lower flow temperatures.
Upgrade_exp: Smarter and greener has to be the way to go and will work beautifully with my underfloor heating and oversize radiators.
Financial_exp: Heat pumps are expensive (currently) and having a free trial makes this technology accessible and reduces the risk to me.  The return for the trial provider is that I am very keen to help out and accommodate the trial.
Technology_exp: I am a degree qualified engineer and something of a green tech nerd; electric car, UFH, advanced energy monitoring, solar PV, V2G from OVO.
Planned_exp: I have always planned to switch to a heat pump and have installed UFH and oversized radiators in preparation.  However, the final and expensive step of installing the heat pump has always been on hold waiting for the cost to become more competitive.
Replacement_exp: My boiler was installed in 2008, but is great condition.
Other_exp: It was always my plan to fit a ground or air source heat pump and so I have fitted UFH, with oversize radiators, as well as external wall insulation.

Building_exp: We are not currently undertaking works but are seriously considering this and are currently having plans drawn up by surveyors/architect.
Research_exp: I believe there is significant consumer trepidation around transitioning to low carbon heating systems and I am keen to be part of the group that can say "look, this is possible, and this is what Ive learnt from it".
Planned_exp: Id love to transition to a heat pump, but do not currently have any plans to do so.
Replacement_exp: Whilst I dont think our system is on the verge of collapse, the boiler is getting older all the time and it doesnt work effectively. This means we need to get an engineer out to take a look really and that may well result in advice about it needing to be replaced.

Future_exp: I believe heat pumps can be a part of balancing grid electricity flow through favourable off-peak tariffs and that there will be increasing opportunities to further improve affordability of running heat pumps in the coming years
Upgrade_exp: I find the gas boiler inefficient mostly due to the rather simplistic control system and would much prefer to have a smarter control system
Building_exp: We carried out extensive work in 2019 and although we considered a heat pump at the time we could not afford the initial cost, or complexity of installing it around building work. I believe our home is well suited to a heat pump with EWI added as part of the 2019 work and UFH already installed on the ground floor.
Financial_exp: The capital outlay for a heat pump, even with RHI payments is currently prohibitive.
Technology_exp: I love the efficiency of a heat pump, turning 1 kW of electricity into 3 kW of heat, so much better than turning 90% of the energy from gas into heat!
Planned_exp: As noted above we would love to install a heat pump, but cannot afford to do so at the moment.
Replacement_exp: My heating system does not need replacement, although I do not like the control system, I am reluctant to improve this as it seems a waste of time as I would much rather install a heat pump than improve a gas system which will never have very low CO2 emissions.

Future_exp: Our boiler is heading towards the end of its life. The easy and cheap option would be to just replace it with a new gas boiler, but for the reasons stated above want to take the opportunity to future proof it
Upgrade_exp: See comment above regarding boiler coming to end of reliable life span but wanting to future proof things and experience low carbon tech rather than taking the easy, simple and generally cheaper looking route of a simple replacement boiler.
Building_exp: Having recovered from the last bout of home improvement we did (internal solid wall insulation 2 years ago) we are now feeling prepared to take on some further work.
Financial_exp: Having spent 25 years as an energy and environment researcher, I recently had to leave my well paid academic job (at least temporarily) largely for health reasons.  At the moment I am doing much lower paid manual work till I fully recover and I can go back into my research/policy career.  The free trial would allow me to continue with our plans for decarbonising our heating system without having to compromise due to my reduced income.  (Although I am not in my main career, I do still have an advocacy role as I run our local sustainability group and community energy project)
Technology_exp: I want to know whether it really i as functional as a gas boiler...and am intrigued as to how complicated it is.  When I worked in DECC in 2010 the results were all coming in from the EST heatpump trials and this put me off somewhat.
Research_exp: As an energy and environment researcher with a strong emphasis I on policy interaction, I fully understand how important real life trials are and I am very keen to support them for the greater cause and participate for my own interest and benefit (also recognising that I am likely to be an,e to get a much better discussion of the finer points of the technology and issues arising with you as part of the trial, than I am with a basic installer)
Planned_exp: As described above somewhere, we had been thinking of trying to get away with just sun amps as a store driven off PV and topped up with cheap night time electricity as heatpump installation wasn�t looking like it was going to be particularly  cost effective due to having. Small house (and no hot water tank)
Replacement_exp: Our boiler is apparently reach8ng the end of its reliable lifespan
Other_exp: Having temporarily stepped back fro. My research career on health grounds, I am very keen to continue supporting the sort of research I was previously involved in (in my current job as a delivery driver, this has involved working with a university to monitor my exposure as a driver to air pollution throughout lockdown and the slow route back to normal).  I am also aware that as an established professional working/who has worked in this field I can potentially add value to the trial. Also as a leader of our local sustainability and community energy groups I have access to a large number of people who would be interested in finding out more about heatpumps and how well they work

Future_exp: The current boiler is coming to the end of its life and I do not want to invest in a gas boiler if there is lower carbon alternative.
Financial_exp: I am currently 62 years old, and have only minimal income from occasional part-time work. My age means that its almost impossible to get another job. I am not entitled to any benefits, have 3 more years to wait for a state pension and live on a very small amount of savings. Therefore it would be helpful to have access to this free trial.
Technology_exp: I have been working in technology since the late 70s and am always interested in technology which serves a purpose; in this case, as a means towards a low-carbon home.
Planned_exp: I dont want to replace an old gas boiler with yet another one, especially as I believe this will shortly be phased out. However, I am not sure I shall be able to afford a heat pump (or a new gas boiler!) so Im in a difficult position at the moment.

Future_exp: I want a heating system which doesnt rely on fossil fuels.
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump (possibly with solar water heating) seems to be the only obvious solution for decarbonising our heating.
Financial_exp: Installing a zero-carbon heating system is not a financially viable option for us at present, but I am very keen to do it for the reasons mentioned above.
Research_exp: I am keen to help out with any studies looking at making renewable domestic heating systems more widely viable and decarbonising residential heating at a larger scale.
Planned_exp: Yes, but its not financially viable for us at present.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler was replaced nearly two years ago, but I am keen to stop using fossil fuels to heat our home!

Future_exp: We will need to replace our heating at some point and this would be the best option I believe. We have been waiting for the boiler to break but it keeps going. I have a green tariff for gas and electricity but gas is the problem I think its still only offset rather than carbon neutral. I would prefer to come off gas altogether eventually.
Upgrade_exp: see above regards age of my heating system. I have been torn between investing in air or ground source solution but I think it air source is most practical. First though I am also looking how to insulate my wooden floors replace boards or I found a company locally with a robot to spray insulation only had initial contact so far...
Building_exp: No works ongoing but I recognise that works will be required to do this. We are willing to accept some disruption.
Financial_exp: I want to do it anyway but cost for me is a significant barrier and could only be done in incremental steps over many years otherwise. I was thinking, insulate, reduce, upgrade heating?, consider switch from radiators to under floor? then heat pump... I havnt had time to crystallize any plans as we both work full time. More of an aspiration without a project such as this. I would relish the chance to support this project and offer my property. Cost is a bonus rather than a driver.
Technology_exp: I have looked at it many times. In particular my work in battery research and development  has exposed me to several off grid and renewable innovation projects. My employer is investigating the electric car salary sacrifice scheme and we have an old car to replace also, if the scheme is introduced then we are considering an EV as a second car. I am sold on the idea but have so far not made the leap.
Research_exp: Renewable energy is the future and I am keen to support projects to promote uptake. In particular how to make it work for old housing stock which seems to have its own challenges. I am supporting the town council in promoting the uptake of green energy at the local level and it would be great to lead by example and promote the project in the town and beyond. In a previous employment I worked in quite a few collaborative projects with innovate UK etc, I miss that now that I am in a larger organisation.
Planned_exp: As I discussed above planning is probably to strong a word, I am but its currently aspirational without a project like this.
Replacement_exp: Technically its working fine and we have been waiting for it to break which sadly hasnt happened. It is old (robust) and no doubt inefficient but we have resisted partly due to cost but also due to the complexity of what to change it to as we dont just want a drop in gas boiler.
Other_exp: I want to do it and help others to do the same by disseminating the experience and outcome of the project in the community and through contacts in the town and district councils.

Upgrade_exp: We have no pressing need to update but this could be an opportunity
I looked at a heat pump to replace my central heating boiler and provide air conditioning.  The expense was too much.
Technology_exp: Ive thought about solar panels but not happy with the way they look.
Replacement_exp: Our boiler is approximately 15 years old and I also would like to relocate it from the kitchen to the toilet or garage.  Thats the reason I was considering an air pump to replace it.

Future_exp: I am looking at ways to maximise my use of renewable energy and reduce use of gas.
Financial_exp: As gas boiler us new I have been waiting for cost if heat pumps to come down before replacing entire heating system.
Research_exp: Having used a heat pump to keep the swimming pool heated, I often wondered how good it would be for heating a house.

Future_exp: My house is old, yes its listed but i believe we need to show change is possible, change can be sympathetic, and probably more so that a hudge oil tank and an outside boiler,
Upgrade_exp: I burn 1000s of galons of oil - this cant be right, there has to be a better way. Im tech savy, risk taking and happy to shout about the success of this project
Building_exp: i a competent diy expert, im happy to take apart bits of the house and sympathetically restore then to make this project happen, Besides i have a 5 and 2 year old so everything is trashed and needs renewing !
Financial_exp: i simply couldnt afford this without this scheme. Im a stay at home dad as i want the best future posible for my kids, i want the environment they live in to be part of this future. The downside of being a stay at home dad is that i dont have money for invest to save schemes. I do have the skills and ethusiams to celbrate success and help others lean from this project
Technology_exp: ive tried lots of new tech to make our home as green as posible - smart radiators, smart meeters etc but i think a step change is needed to make progress - one that i can afford on my own
Research_exp: I have a Phd in research, im used to being part of research projects and believe in trying new things to make the world better, Im willing to be open, honest and transparant in this process.
Replacement_exp: My oil boiler is near the end of its life, its fine but i dont want to be rushed into a like for like replacement if it died, this scheme would give me the confidence to keep it going until a greener alternative is available

Future_exp: We want to reduce our reliance on fossil fuels  and make a contribution towards reduction in climate change
Upgrade_exp: Current heating system is efficient but carbon-reliant
Building_exp: Ours is a new-built home completed in  2015
Financial_exp: We exceeded our building budget through provision of enhanced insulation and other measures so replacement of heating system  is not a financial option; we are approaching retirement and we need to be mindful of outgoings now.
Technology_exp: A sustainable energy source for main heating is the missing piece of the jigsaw in the construction of our home and we are keen to incorporate this if possible.
Research_exp: We want to prove that  low-carbon heating is cleaner and more cost-effective.  Participating in this project could mean that we pay a part in influencing future decision making of many other households.  We further feel that with Ovos  project we would be working in partnership and feel supported through it. Since building our home we have been strong ambassadors for self-build and environmentally efficient processes and we feel this well-planned Ovo project is potentially a very influential one.
Planned_exp: This is not a financially viable option for us.

Future_exp: Our current boiler keeps going wrong and I would like to move to something that I know is more environmentally friendly at the same time as reliable.
Upgrade_exp: See above - current system keeps going wrong.
Financial_exp: Our old boiler is only about 6 years old but is likely to need replacing soon.

Future_exp: We live in a conventional house and if the country is going to successful transition to a net carbon zero future then retrofitting a heat pump in a house like ours will be essential
Upgrade_exp: My existing boiler although relatively new is not performing well and needs to be replaced.
Financial_exp: Of course, cost is an issue and heat pump systems are not cheap at the present time and are not cost competitive but may represent the future.
Technology_exp: We are early adopters of the electric car and have looked at solar panels (but the roof is not ideal).  A heat pump system would be our next step to creating a more sustainable home.
Research_exp: We are keen to support the sustainable future as parents to two children we are keen to ensure that the world is a more sustainable place for everyone.
Planned_exp: At the moment the cost is too high and it does not make economic sense to install a ground source heat pump. This is the challenge....
Replacement_exp: As mentioned before our existing heating system is unreliable and we are considering replacement.

Future_exp: I want a sustainable home where I�m not burning fuel and rely on home generated electricity as much as possible
I would love to update the house so it is efficiently heating the house and able to benefit from the new technology available to do so.
Upgrade_exp: My existing boiler is old and likely to need replacing soon. It seems inconsistent with our net zero commitments to replace it with a new gas system.
Building_exp: We are likely to carry out works over the coming year that could see the heating system and radiators needing to be replaced so it would be ideal to have the opportunity for this to be a modern low carbon option.
Financial_exp: The cost of installing a heat pump and updating the rest of the system is prohibitive, even with the RHI income over years to come, there is a significant upfront cost.
Technology_exp: I would like to see what the best system would be for a home like mine and am aware that the technology has improved a lot over recent years.
Research_exp: It seems that Ovo have been putting a lot of work into moving forward the debate about climate change and aiming to bring about change to their customers energy use.
Planned_exp: I have done some initial research into heat pumps and it seems to be a really good low carbon option but the upfront cost is prohibitive.
Replacement_exp: I am loath to install a new gas central heating system when we know that the country needs to reduce its use of gas.
Measures_Recommend: Loft Insulation; Wall insulation; Draft Proofing

Future_exp: We can see (and are pleased by) how public opinion and regulation is moving towards low carbon technologies. We�ve heard that gas boilers will no longer be allowed to be installed in new builds in a few years and are keen to make our next heating system compliant with future regulations. It is clear to us that we cant hit net-zero and still have gas heating
Upgrade_exp: The gas boiler we inherited from the previous house owners is near the end of its life and the house was draughty and cool in winters. We�ve undertaken work on extra internal insulation and installed larger radiators but a new heating system is big part of our energy efficiency plan and we�re keen to see if a heat pump could be a part of the solution.
Building_exp: Weve done the low hanging fruit already, such as extra roof insulation. We are now considering building work to retrofit our home to make it more energy efficient, we are considering: external insulation, underfloor insulation, draught-proofing and better insulated windows. And a new heating system is one of the biggest parts of the retrofit.
Financial_exp: We are considering a range of measures to retrofit our home to be more energy efficient: external insulation, underfloor insulation, draught-proofing, better insulated windows, and a new heating system and it is frightfully expensive, so the idea that the heating system could be free would mean we would be able to achieve more of our energy efficiency retrofit plans
Technology_exp: As early adopters of an EV, we are excited by the prospect of being early movers for low-carbon heat and to be an example to those we know and that live close by.\nWe are already on a half-hourly electricity tariff and are keen to explore new ideas such as becoming prosumers and residential flexibility and how agile heat might change behaviour. We�ve also heard about thermal storage and are keen to explore if that could be part of our solution. In short we are fascinated by these new technologies
Research_exp: With much improvement in new-build construction techniques, we also feel that retrofit is hugely important for the UK to be able to achieve a net zero carbon economy. We�d be delighted to participate in a project that researches and explores how techniques can be perfected and then rolled out at scale. And wed be keen to learn from the insights generated from this trial and your technical expertise on how these technologies work and how best to deploy them. We are keen to be advocates for successful, green technologies.
Planned_exp: We are planning to change our boiler and are exploring to see if a heat pump could be part of the solution but have not come to any conclusion yet.
Replacement_exp: The boiler is at least 16 years old and is leaking a huge amount of heat where it is stored. We are keen to replace the old system as it is inefficient and expensive to run and want to explore if a heat pump could be part of the solution

Future_exp: I think this is probably the way things are going (hopefully) so taking part in this trial is a great way for me to be able to adopt this technology when I might otherwise not be able to.
Upgrade_exp: I dont know much about heat pumps apart from what I have read in your literature. Our boiler isnt that old so this isnt a necessity but looks to be a good way to go for the future.
Building_exp: Were not currently doing any building works but are renovating the house so any disruption caused wouldnt be annoying.
Financial_exp: Well of course I am. I dont think I would be able to afford for a long time otherwise so this is definitely attractive.
Technology_exp: Im a new homeowner and we are trying to upgrade our house to make it meet modern standards and become more energy efficient and this new tech seems to be able to achieve that effectively.
Research_exp: It sounds like its a good way forward for older heating systems and helping the UK reach its carbon goals so if we are good candidates and can help out with that then I want to.

Future_exp: Already have 12 PV panels on roof - space for 4 more + 12 vacuum tube solar collector. Looking to buy an Electric Vehicle I the next 2 years.
Planned_exp: I�m looking at alternatives to fossil fuel boiler

Future_exp: we need to cut our carbon footprint,its expensive and thats the only reason we havent done the improvements needed on our property.I have a 7 year old and Id like him to grow up in a world that we havent completely destroyed
Upgrade_exp: I actually dont know much about heat pumps but am interested to know all about it and its benefits
Building_exp: currently cant afford to undertake any major projects but wish I could!
Financial_exp: Id love to be able to help the environment and my family have comfortable home to live in.The opportunity to trial products free of charge is a big incentive to look into something we couldnt afford no matter how hard we work
Technology_exp: Im interested in how my neighbours eco house works and would like to try it for myself! Its fascinating and is the way we qill all be moving forward
Research_exp: Id enjoy trying anything that gives my family a better way of life
Planned_exp: I wasnt planning on changing as in the current climate we cant afford to look into things like this.
Replacement_exp: I have old radiators so the chance to change that would be fab
Other_exp: Id just like to give my family a nicer way of living and it will teach my child to help protect the environment

Future_exp: We would like to have a properly sustainable heating system that will ensure the property is both fit for purpose and environmentally friendly for the next many years. We intend to remain in the house for the duration and setting the house up to support us for this time has a strong appeal.
Upgrade_exp: We would very much like to be able to use the gas heating less - only as a backup to top up a more sustainable heating system in extreme cold conditions. An air source heat pump seems like the ideal solution for this.
Financial_exp: free is always a price we can work with!
Technology_exp: We currently have a pop-up swimming pool that is heated using an air-sourced heat pump and are very please with the efficiency and efficacy. (Plus we divert the cooled air into the lounge as cooling!) We are keen to use this fantastic technology more.
Research_exp: Why are new build houses not required to use sustainable heating and solar panels - it would be better for the environment, cheaper for the householders and easier on the national infrastructure? We would love to support any research that makes the more widespread adoption of these technologies more likely.
Planned_exp: My wife suffers from MS and finds excessive heat during the summer months to be very debilitating. This is why we currently divert the cooled air from the pool heater into the lounge. A heat-pump that is set up to act as both heating and air-conditioning seems like a perfect solution - more efficient heating in the winter and cooling - powered by our solar panels - in the summer.
Other_exp: As noted above, because of my wifes heat sensitivity due to her MS, we really would benefit very greatly from air-conditioning. It would be odd to install that without heating.

Future_exp: As the boiler is coming to the end of its life, it seems sensible to move to electric now rather than get another gas boiler
Upgrade_exp: As the boiler is coming to the end of its life, it seems sensible to move to electric now rather than get another gas boiler
Building_exp: We are currently installing solar PV, and had been thinking of sotentially getting a sunamp system but werent sure it was suitable without a heatpump, which we were doubtful that we could sensibly afford
Financial_exp: I recently lost my job working as a professional in the environment and energy sector and so our ability to upgrade our house has been significantly compromised.
Technology_exp: As someone who has worked in the environment and energy field for almost 25 years and had to advocate this stuff professionally - I feel it is time that I actually committed to this and did it myself
Research_exp: Having lost my job in energy research at the start of the year, the bit of me that is intellectually stimulated by all this stuff would love to be able to continue to participate in research and this seems an ideal way to do it.
Planned_exp: We were considering moving to sunamps, but potentially not via a heatpump (at least in the first instance)
Replacement_exp: We have been told that our boiler is likely to fail at some point soon

Future_exp: Yes, but main concern is environmental.
Upgrade_exp: Boiler was fitted in 2013 so its not urgent, but would like to change energy vectors so that local carbon emissions can be reduced - and I dont think Green Gas is likely to become widely available.
Financial_exp: Of course - but particularly that design and specification will be undertaken by a professional company that wants to succeed, not by someone I dont know and cant trust.
Research_exp: As above, main concern is environmental.
Planned_exp: I have been thinking about it but have not started to investigate in detail.
Replacement_exp: Boiler was fitted in 2013 so its not urgent, but would like to change energy vectors so that local carbon emissions can be reduced - and I dont think Green Gas is likely to become widely available.

Measures_Recommend: Loft Insulation; Wall insulation; Window replacement; Draft Proofing

Future_exp: Not sure what "future proof" really means. If it means protecting the future of the planet for future generations then my answer is yes, if it means protecting my house from changes to heating regulations  in the future then no.
Upgrade_exp: Current system works fine, it just isnt environmentally friendly.
Financial_exp: Obviously but it isnt the main reason
Technology_exp: The need to do something is clear, progress can only be made by beta testing new technologies to see what works and what doesnt
Research_exp: I believe we need to do more to combat global warming and trials like this can help new technologies develop.
Planned_exp: It is beyond my budget at the moment

Future_exp: I am particularly interested in optimising the insulation in my house, in installing triple glazing, and getting an air source heat pump fitted (if this could be run on solar energy too, that would be even better).
Upgrade_exp: As stated previously, I am very keen to get an air source heat pump installed, for cleaner, greener heating in winter, and sustainable aircon during the summer months.
Building_exp: Ive not started any building or refurb as yet but if I could get any help with any of it, I would be keen to look into it further.
Financial_exp: Some of the costs of systems available are a bit daunting, especially as I dont earn a huge salary.  But I am really keen on getting a sustainable system installed.
Technology_exp: Air source heat pumps sound like a fantastic way of heating a property in winter, and cooling it in winter.  I would love to combine it with solar panels to run it without grid electricity (or to feed into the grid).
Research_exp: It is important that this kind of technology becomes increasingly high-profile as we need to reduce our carbon emissions as a matter of urgency (I am active in XR by the way).  So if I can support this project I would be very happy to.
Planned_exp: I was considering applying to get an air source heat pump grant via the Green Homes scheme that the government are about to launch, although I realise it will be very competitive so want to avoid the disappointment of missing out.
Replacement_exp: My heating system is functioning as it should, I guess, but I dont really use the gas system as its so expensive.  Another reason is that it doesnt provide air conditioning as an air source heat pump would, and this is going to become increasingly necessary in years to come, but needs to be sustainable.
Other_exp: Health reasons:  I have respiratory allergies and need to be able to heat my house sustainably and affordably so that mould doesnt accumulate during the winter months.

Upgrade_exp: I had been trying to look at the new green deal and had seen about the heat pumps and have been trying to find out how they work.
Financial_exp: I came across this trial while I was finding out about heat pumps. I am with SSE though. I hope this is still ok.
Technology_exp: Yes. I don�t know anyone who has one and would like to see how it works.
Research_exp: I would like a greener and more efficient way to heat our home and it would be great to help this country�s future heating requirements.
Planned_exp: As above I will be looking into the new green deal although I don�t have any idea how much it would cost.
Replacement_exp: As above. We are using so much electricity with our storage heaters and Immersion  heater compared to our neighbours.

Future_exp: The government is pushing towards electrification of domestic heating and transport, if I adopt a low carbon heating system I will be well placed to build onto the system with other technologies such as solar PV and battery storage further reducing carbon emissions and saving me money
Upgrade_exp: using a heat pump will allow me to replace my gas boiler with a more efficient system
Financial_exp: I have been considering installing a heat pump but have been put off up until now by the upfront cost
Technology_exp: As this is the way the domestic heating market is moving, I would like to change to gain the most benefit
Research_exp: I understand that this project is to pave the way for the wider spread of low carbon heating systems which will ultimately help reduce our greenhouse emissions and help fight global warming
Planned_exp: I have been considering changing to a heat pump but have been put off by the upfront cost
Replacement_exp: I still have the original heating system from when the house was built in 1994 and so the opportunity to replace this for a greener and more efficient system would be great

Future_exp: Technology is moving so fast i want to benefit from this
Upgrade_exp: I have heard that they are 300% efficient, if I can reduce my impact this is great for me and the kids
Research_exp: I am happy to share this, it�s such a hot topic at the moment we all need to find ways to reduce what we can

Future_exp: Low carbon technology is something we should be moving to as fast as possible to reduce our impact on the planet. Technology can offer significant gains whilst also improving our lives
Upgrade_exp: A heat pump using low carbon sources is one of the tools we can use to achieve a low carbon future. We already have an electric car and solar panels, this scheme looks like the next obvious set for us.
Building_exp: I am not currently undertaking any building work on the property.
Financial_exp: Being an early adopter for new technology comes at a cost, if this can be provided free and I can contribute to the develop of the technology or system I am more than happy to support it.
Technology_exp: I am interested in the new technologies and how they can help us and the planet.
Research_exp: Supporting the research and taking the science and carbon reduction economy forward is a positive thing for society and I�m happy to do my part in supporting it where I can.
Planned_exp: I was researching the idea of getting a heat pump and came across an article which linked me to your scheme. I will still investigate the option but probably more slowly if I�m not successful due to the current prohibitive costs.
Replacement_exp: My system is 10 years old, it�s performing adequately but runs on gas so I would like to move to a greener source of energy when practicable to do so.

Future_exp: Society is coming around to carbon neutral and willing to facilitate this trial.
Building_exp: If we are successful, we�d look to undertake kitchen works incl. remove gas hob to be 100% electric on a green tariff so can be carbon free.
Financial_exp: The initial outlay is high, and payback is long, the warranty periods are short so there is a risk to being 100% self funded for a retrofit.
Technology_exp: We had an MVHR system installed due to house being very airtight after final double glazing installed. Additional loft insulation & an Air source heat pump would complement.
Research_exp: We have a moral duty for future generations to cut use of fossil fuels ASAP.

Future_exp: We are  looking at ways to future proof our home and make a commitment to net zero to support climate change for our generation and our daughters generation and future. \nWe do not want to replace our old boiler with another gas boiler and would prefer to look at ASHP and other options but price is a prohibiting factor at the moment.
Upgrade_exp: We do not want to replace our old boiler that is very inefficient with another gas boiler and would prefer to look at ASHP and other options but price is a prohibiting factor at the moment.
Building_exp: We are replacing our open fireplace with a DEFRA approved log burner and have insulated our conservatory roof recently with a product called easy ceiling with a layer of kingspan on top to support heat loss/solar gain. \nSolar PV isnt an option at this time so would like to consider ASHP to come away from fossil fuels.
Financial_exp: ASHP is a big investment for us at this time and not sure we could afford this now but our boiler does need replacing and would prefer not to replace with a gas one and prefer renewable option.
Technology_exp: I would like to be a local advocate for the technology too
Research_exp: As mentioned in my role as Commercialisation Manager at Clean Growth UK I support the development of clean tech R&D so would be good to walk the talk and use the clean technology of ASHP in my home to promote the benefit to others and reduce our environmental impact.
Planned_exp: We would like to have a heat pump but cost is a prohibitive factor at this time.
Replacement_exp: As mentioned we would like to move to a renewable heat source and away from gas. \nOur gas boiler is old and inefficient and often loses pressure.
Other_exp: Did we mention we would like a truly green net zero home?

Future_exp: We need to make better choices when it comes to low carbon. Gas is not the answer so I want to know how we can move to a lower carbon and less environmentally damaging form of home heating.
Upgrade_exp: Our boiler is old, likely or possibly the original one (not sure but it�s old) and will need replacing and a heat pump is a modern  and better solution
Research_exp: Projects such as this help consumers make the best choices and as we all need to be making more environmentally conscious covers I hope a successful project as this one will new will presume those doubted or nervous customers Male the right choices rather than sticking with what they know.
Planned_exp: A heat pump is an option I am very interested in. Our boiler is old and I want to make the best environmental option when it comes to replacing it. I think a heat pump is a great option for this.
Replacement_exp: It will needs upgrading soon as the boiler is very old.

Future_exp: I would love to have a system that is resilient should the external grid fail
Upgrade_exp: Given heat pumps are practically magic (1KWh in =~ 3KWh of heat), Im excited to see what can be done to move away from reliance on gas
Financial_exp: Very much so. Its a great opportunity to do something that I would otherwise not be doing
Technology_exp: As mentioned before, heat pumps are astonisihing.
Research_exp: Having worked with the BBC R&D department, I appreciate the attention to detail and understand the amount of effort that goes into research projects on all sides.

Future_exp: To reduce rising costs of other bills, and to future proof property against impact of climate change and to make the property comfortable to live in for future generations
Upgrade_exp: Subject to available space, we would be interested in a heat pump. Otherwise happy to explore all options to upgrade heating wherever possible
Financial_exp: As first time buyers we are keen to improve the property whilst keeping costs low
Technology_exp: Willing to adopt new technology for the benefit of the planet and future owners of the property
Research_exp: Sounds very interesting and forward thinking. A progressive, innovative move from the government.
Planned_exp: Dont know - we were exploring all options when we heard of this trial. Would still be interested in taking part
Replacement_exp: We have no central heating, and are reliant on inefficient stand-alone electric oil-filled radiators  to heat a poorly insulated property. A new heating system for the house is a must.

Upgrade_exp: we are very attracted to the idea of accessing good advice on the selection of appropriate technology. The market is moving fast, and when we built the house in 2014 we had confusing and conflicting advice from companies trying to sell us ground source or air source heat pumps; in the end we setlled for an efficient gas boiler as an interim step while green generation technology improved in cost and efficiency
Financial_exp: It would of course be great to have free installation; battery technology is especially expensive, and help with the cost will make abig difference
Technology_exp: as stated above, we see this house as a progression. we built it to the highest levels of efficiency in terms of energy conservation - but did not take the next step to renewable generation. We really hope this project will enable us to do this confidently and effectively
Research_exp: I appeared in the OVO ad campaign last year, representing an older generation that needs to do everything it can to help redress the damage done to the environment during our lifetimes, for the benefit of our children and grandchildren. Helping a reseach project that aims to work out how best to accelerate the installation of renewable generating is an exciting opportunity.
Replacement_exp: it is five years old - so halfway through its maximally efficient life span. if we are selected to proceed with this programme, we would aim to give it to someone to replace a less efficient one

Future_exp: I use technology as an enabler at home. Almost all outdoor lighting is solar, smart controls for heating (TADO) in smart TRVs at each radiator (nine in total). This reduces my energy consumption and bills overall from the last five years. Beyond that, I use a variety of smart controls at home to manage security (e.g. Ring, WiFi Plugs) and yet make an energy-efficient home. I believe in using technology to make homes smart and (cost and energy) efficient at the same time.\n\nI am competent and comfortable with technology with a background of 10+ years in the telecom industry.
Upgrade_exp: The combi gas boiler has been advised to be replaced at the last service in February 2020. It is at the end of life and needs to be replaced. This trial would be an ideal opportunity to replace a fossil fuel boiler and reduce energy bill at the same time. The boiler is now small (by capacity) since the loft extension was done (in 2018) therefore a storage heat pump will be an ideal energy-efficient replacement. For now, we can only use one shower or hot water tap at one time so combi boiler is not really ideal solution as well.
Building_exp: The original property was a three-bedroom bungalow for which loft conversion was done in 2018 to add two bedrooms upstairs. No further expansion/extension planned.
Financial_exp: I have invested in energy-efficient loft extension in 2018, Smart Heating Control (TADO), Solar Panels (4KW), Hybrid (10+ years) and EV Nissan Leaf (since 2015) to reduce my energy impact. With increased financial liabilities, I have now exhausted my ability to further invest however very keen to benefit from this energy trial to be considered as an incentive for a progressive, smart and future proof home heating solution.
Technology_exp: Further to my comments above, I am excited by the technology in making homes smart yet cost and energy-efficient. I have benefitted from smart heating controls (TADO and Smart TRVs) in reducing my energy bills. My fuel cost has massively reduced since the purchase of EV in 2015 and Hybrid car. I am excited about the technologies offered in this energy trial and keen to integrate the same making our home future proof but more importantly zero carbon.
Research_exp: I am one of the top (five) contributors on the OVO forum since I joined the trial in June 2020. I am naturally drawn towards the use of technology to enable better living. Both of my recent posts have been converted to blogs with hundreds if not thousands of views. I have background and experience in R&D, design and development so fully understand the challenges and the value of feedback especially when youre deploying a pilot to scale.
Planned_exp: I am the sole bread earner for the family. My wife is a house-wife and therefore money is always stretched when it comes to making home improvements. With other financial commitments, it would not be feasible to pursue install even if this very much so desired.
Replacement_exp: As mentioned above, our Greenstart 35Cdi combi gas boiler has been advised for a replacement however we will not be able to afford it with a single income and uncertainty caused by the pandemic. This required improvement would continue to be on hold. Unless selected for this trial we will have to proceed with repairs as and when required. This trial would be very timely as it would remove a faulty boiler and provide an energy-efficient heating system.

Building_exp: We are looking to refurbish the bathroom and upgrade our heating/hot water system.\nwe are also looking to replace our double glazing and all external doors.

Future_exp: I think it would be great if this property, which is a typical example of the poorly insulated building practice of its period (1969/70 - an era where residents were expected to consume huge amounts of cheap fossil fuel) could be made into an example of modern best renewable practice. Of course it would make the property more future proof, and that would be great - but I also see it as payback. I can remember as a boy that my mother would run 5 electric radiators 24/7 as well a coal fire to heat this house in winter back in the 1970s when fuel was cheap. And that was all playing its part in todays climate problems. 40 years on I run just the 1 radiator at the minimum level I can put up with and wear sometimes 5 layers of clothing to try and keep warm. It would actually be rather nice instead to be comfortable, but helping save the planet as well.
Upgrade_exp: As already outlined, there is *no* central heating system in the property, and this is a situation that badly needs to be addressed, but in a sustainable way (please NOTE that in one of the earlier questions you asked what the system was, but there was no option to say there was none, so I was forced to tick boiler even though there is *no* boiler).\nI had not properly realised, until researching it during the lockdown period, how far heat pumps have now advanced compared to solar electricity generation, and how they can provide a total solution for space and water heating, and even cooling in summer. Now that I realise how their use has progressed around the world (e.g. Canada) I am convinced they are a good solution for my property, and something that should be encouraged nationally.
Building_exp: Like many people during the Coronavirus situation, I have been using this enforced isolation to try to improve the property, but lacking any resources to pay contractors, have been limited to tasks such as decorating that I can undertake myself. But the heating of the property is a very urgent situation, as it is effectively unliveable in winter. Since the primary heating has always had to be by plug-in radiators, to heat the property to any degree of comfort would be unaffordably expensive and also environmentally damaging. But without such heating there are frequent occurrances of condensation, mould and mildew as well as the adverse effect on my comfort and wellbeing of being deprived of the use of the unheated rooms. These issues have become increasingly severe in the 9 years I have lived in the property, but on the positive side there are now renewable technologies available that were not a decade ago, and it would be ideal to go down that route if at all possible.
Financial_exp: Given that I am currently in receipt of Universal Credit and have no savings, it is simply impossible to install a renewable heating system any other way, placing me in effective fuel poverty and with the most expensive heating system possible (plug-in electric). Each year I have hated the arrival of cold winter months, knowing there is no sensible way to heat the house - and of course I have noticed, since moving to Rye from London 9 years ago, that the temperatures in the countryside are distinctly lower in winter than they are in cities.\nSo in short, it is both the fact that the property has no central heating (which I lack the means to install) AND the fact that a renewable system would reduce the running costs to close to zero, that makes a free heat pump system something that be quite transformative for me and an immense help .
Technology_exp: I think one of the most intruiging features of heat pumps - which adds to my interest in installing one, but I think its overlooked and important anyway -  is the ability to cool in summer as well as heat in winter, and to do both of these things renewably (ideally with solar PV to run the compressor). And that is not just a question of comfort - if we fail to address emissions properly, then we will need more cooling during hotter summers, which in turn could be a source of further emissions. As an example of this, a dear friend in London told me this week that during the recent heatwave her partner had brought some plug-in air coolers to her flat - she is currently replacing a boiler, so I recommended she at least consider a heat pump. I couldnt persuade her - largely because she thinks it would probably be forbidden in a leashold flat -  but that conversation focussed my attention even more on how good a solution a heat pump would be for myself, compared to say a biomass boiler. I remember the heatwave of 1976, and the heatwave last week was only a small taste of that, but also a sign of things to come in the future.
Research_exp: I think this is an excellent initiative, and I am impressed that OVO is taking a lead with it. I think a project like this, especially if the favourable effects are well-publicised, can do a lot to shape public perceptions, so that we stop thinking of a gas boiler as the normal and something renewable as somehow weird. I am keen to support and take part in it, not only because it would help meet an urgent need for my own house and welfare, but also because aligns with the views I hold on responsibly using resources and protecting the environment for the future.
Planned_exp: Well its both yes and no! I would very much like to install a heat pump, but see no way to afford it in the forseeable future given my circumstances. I am of course looking very carefully at the Green Homes Grant scheme, but the details of this are very sketchy for now, and I doubt that the support available would cover the cost of the installation, given that there is no existing central heating system to connect to. That is to say, assuming that I would qualify for vouchers to the level of �10k, the costs of additional insulation measures needed before a heat pump could be installed (cavity insulation, possibly underfloor insulation, double glazing) would themselves be subtracted from the 10k total, leaving insufficient funds for the heat pump itself, which would be more than usually expensive because of the need to retrofit radiators and pipework. So I can foresee that whole route falling through. And of course we do not yet know whether the scheme will be able to be rolled out effectively for all interested applicants and in what timeframe. So I think it highly unlikely that the Green Homes scheme will be of help in this instance - at best it might be a route to a solar water heating installation (helpful of course, but what is desperately needed is renewable space heating as well as water).
Replacement_exp: As already set out, there is no heating system - only plug-in radiators and a fireplace in the living room. These properties (there are 70 identical in the area) were built in a very different era, in 1969, just before the oil price shock, with the expectation that fossil fuels would always be cheap sources of heating, and were fitted with minimal insulation. Central heating was a luxury add-on when they were constructed, but was never installed in the property (it was my mothers house until she died in 2008). The lack of a heating system has become increasingly problematic since I have lived here - in the colder months I have to effectively live in my bedroom on the upper floor as this can be kept warmer by the roof insulation - but the discomfort this has created for me will have been more tolerable if it is now possible to install a system that will not be environmentally harmful.
Other_exp: I have touched on this reason above, but it is worth expanding on. It is quite likely that we may face a winter of semi-lockdown with the virus situation, and already we have all probably taken a long hard look at our living conditions in the period we have been confined to our homes. Being of a somewhat  vulnerable age group (there have been many hospitalisations of males in the 55-60 age group) I have been confining myself largely to the house. That is one thing in summer, when the temperature indoors is comfortable. But I dread the prospect of months of semi-isolation in a property with no central heating, no affordable means of heating, and where I am obliged in winter to live largely in one room to keep at all warm. It would make such a difference to enjoy the amenity of a sustainably and comfortably heated house. It would make a very great difference to my life and state of mind.
