Future_exp: If we are to have any chance of avoiding the worst impacts of climate change, we know the world needs to shift urgently away from fossil fuels. If this (hopefully!) happens at the rate required, then fossil gas powered heating systems will rapidly become obsolete. So this would also be a way for us personally to get ahead of the curve (although this is a much less important reason for us than wanting to reduce our emissions and support the spread of low carbon heating technologies).
Financial_exp: This makes a big difference to us, as we have unreliable self-employed incomes that make it very unlikely we would be able to afford this scale of investment any time soon.
Technology_exp: This is also a factor, as were both very interested in clean energy technology, and having more direct experience of its workings would help us to be champions for this kind of technology in the rest of our lives!
Research_exp: As stated above, were keen to do what we can to help support the growth and spread of low-carbon technologies, to help accelerate the shift away from fossil fuels and give us a chance at a safer climate. This project looks like a great opportunity for us to help do that.

I have outdoor space near to the existing boiler location, which would be south-east facing so good for capturing the hottest air of the day. I will be redecorating soon so its a great opportunity to change things without actually disrupting the home, but the works arent extensive enough to disrupt the heat pump installation. Future_exp: The UK government has committed to neutral carbon emissions by 2030, therefore gas prices will have to increase. Cars and other technology will have to be powered by electricity with increasing demand on the grid. The only way for our family to meet this challenge is by changing our heating technology to allow for this increased demand and ideally become as independent as possible of the electricity grid.
Upgrade_exp: We want a low carbon heating system that has a long life span of ideally 20+ years with minimal maintenance costs, minimal moving parts and much better efficiency than condensing gas boilers.
Building_exp: Within the next few months we are going to refurbish the kitchen and bathrooms, and want to install more carbon-efficient underfloor heating throughout the ground floor. In addition, we would want to install insulation in the roof, loft and walls. This is therefore the ideal time to upgrade our heating and hot water system.
Financial_exp: It is difficult to ignore the fact that low carbon technology heating systems are expensive. Installing both air and ground source heat pumps are significantly more expensive than quotes we have had to upgrade to a condensing boiler and new hot water storage unit. Our priority is to insulate the house as we dont have enough money to also change the heating to heat pump technology.
Technology_exp: Having seen heat pump and battery technology evolve over the last few years to the point that they are no longer niche products has pushed us towards realising that now is the time to act.
Research_exp: The idea of being part of a large trial of proof of concept that low carbon heating works, is accessible to the general public and is the means of actually achieving our international commitment to carbon neutrality really is exciting.
Planned_exp: But the expense of changing to a heat pump could prevent us from doing so.
Other_exp: As well as our key worker jobs for the NHS, we are both carers for our 3 children who unfortunately have learning disabilities. One of those children also has a medical condition (Raynauds) that results in very poor peripheral circulation. A cold environment such as our house worsens the Raynauds causing significant pain in her hands and feet.Unfortunately, it is proving impossible to even find a specialist insulation installer willing to take on any work for the next 1 year because the green homes grant has overwhelmed the renewables and insulation sector.

Research_exp: see the answer above, I am very keen to help to do what I can to provide valuable feedback on the system so that it can be refined and improved. I am very interested to see how this works and how effective it can be.

Future_exp: As a computer engineer, I am always looking to the future, and see a number of exciting technologies that I would love to adopt given sufficient money.
Upgrade_exp: I considered a dalkin HT heat pump in the past, but sadly it was out of my price range, but based on the consultants who initially visited, I know I have ample room, and there shouldnt be any major issues installing one.\nThe only point worth mentioning is that my heating currently runs on microbore 10mm copper pipping, hence the need for a high temp heat pump.
Building_exp: Other than making our home less carbon intensive, I have no plans for any other work.
Financial_exp: This free trial could give me a chance to fulfil my plans to live a lower carbon lifestyle and leave my environment in a better way than when I moved here.
Technology_exp: I love new technologies and love to learn and see how tech can help improve the quality of my life and reduce my environment impact.
Research_exp: Obviously there would be a benefit to my household in hopefully reduced energy bills and reducing my carbon footprint, but I view this as a small way to validate the technologies and ideas and hopefully help others role them out. Together, we can all make a positive impact and help save the planet.
Planned_exp: I looked into purchasing a heat pump, but it was sadly out of my price range.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is coming up to 6 years old, so probably wont last many more years, and is undoubtedly less efficient than more modern ones.

Future_exp: with small children we cannot afford surprise bills in the future

The future is not burning gas and coal and the sooner we move away from this the better. We need to update the heating system on our house and doing so with 20th century technology seems reductive and not something future generations will thank us for.
Upgrade_exp: Ever since moving into our house 18 months ago my partner, who works in environmental science, and I have been looking at heat pumps as the ideal way for us to heat our house from an environmental point of view. The large upfront costs and also not knowing what would be required on a house of our age is what has held us back so far. The expertise that Ovo are offering is just what we have been looking for hence our interest in this trial.
Building_exp: We are looking to replace a poorly insulated 1980s kitchen extension with a more modern replacement that will not be a heat sink in winter. As part of this we wish to move the boiler from its current location in a bedroom to the extension and have been actively looking at an airsource heat pump or hybrid system to heat the house.
Financial_exp: Of course, being offered the system free of charge is a major draw to this trial. However, almost equally of interest to us is the expertise that Ovo are offering. If we wanted a gas boiler heating system we can go to British Gas and they can help out. We have not managed to find anything similar for more environmentally friendly options and it is the access to this knowledge that particularly attracted us.
Technology_exp: The science of heat pumps is in itself interesting before the technology associated with making the house more efficent in general is included.
Research_exp: We live in a typical 1930s semi of which there are hundreds in Eastleigh alone. By showing that it is possible to heat homes such as this using renewable sources and what is required it lowers the bar for others to follow a similar path. The results in older, less well insulated properties will be fascinating, we have frequently been told and read that houses like ours are incompatible with heat pumps and renewable, modern heating and would love to prove this wrong. In addition we are both research scientist and such things just interest us.
Planned_exp: We would love to change to a heat pump but have been told in the past it will not be possible and that the best we could hope for is a hybrid heat pump and boiler as we dont have a passive house or similar. The mantra "youre on mains gas, stay on mains gas" is what we have faced.
Replacement_exp: We have an old combi boiler that doesnt heat the entire house and is located in a bedroom. We wish to replace this and want to do so in the most environmentally friendly way possible.

Future_exp: We must reduce our dependence on carbon fuels and I have gone some way down that road. This would be the next step. I would be very happy to show off such a system.
Upgrade_exp: Boiler is between 15-20 years old and will need replacing soon.
Technology_exp: Always keen to embrace new technology and move with the times .....and if that is also eco friendly that is a considerable bonus.
Research_exp: Would be happy to collect data/share information to promote eco friendly initiative.
Planned_exp: I have enquired before but cost was beyond me.
Replacement_exp: My gas engineer has been nursing our boiler for some years now. The end is surely nigh!

Future_exp: In order to achieve the personal and national goal of Net Zero by 2030, it is imperative we switch to heating technologies which dont rely on fossil fuels. I see the switch to an electric-powered heat system to make complete sense in this context, especially as I can harness the solar power from my PV roof panels and the Grid is decarbonising year by year. Hence, I do believe this is a very sound investment for the future.
Upgrade_exp: I have been exploring the different technologies available recently. Owing to the type and size of the property, the amount of insulation and the outdoor space available, an air source heat pump seems to be the ideal solution.
Building_exp: I am not planning to undertake any building works separate to this. However, I understand that the installation of an air source heat pump will require works on the house to be carried out.
Financial_exp: This certainly removes one of the barriers to transition from my gas central heating to this greener form of heating system.
Technology_exp: I am naturally someone who likes to investigate and use new technology. I am interested in learning all about the new heating system, how it works, and how I could optimise it for my needs.
Research_exp: I am fully supportive of this research and will gladly contribute data in support of it.
Planned_exp: I feel a heat pump is a logical, greener alternative to my current system so yes, I do plan to change to this when an opportunity to do so arises.
Other_exp: I wish to be an advocate to others to show how it is possible to reduce ones personal carbon emissions through lifestyle changes and also with the use of new technology such as the heat pump.

Future_exp: We believe that houses need to become more environmentally sustainable to help protect the planet. We have started to do this with our retrofit.
Upgrade_exp: By using a heat pump system we could reduce or eliminate our green house gases emissions from heating.
Building_exp: We are part way through a complete retrofit of the downstairs of our house including an extension. The majority of this retrofit was to make the property more energy efficient. We are starting to do the same with the upstairs now.
Financial_exp: We have already spent a lot of money on bringing the property up to modern building standards. We had looked into various options to upgrade our boiler, however we do not have the money to undertake this at present.
Technology_exp: We like the ideas of new technologies to benefit ourselves and demonstrate to others how this would benefit them.
Research_exp: We think that it is very important for research to take place, to be able to develop technology.
Planned_exp: We have not got the funds to undertake this.
Replacement_exp: Whilst the boiler is reasonably efficient it is 13 years old and the service engineers have warned that it may need to be replaced soon. Also with the increased insulation it might not be the most efficient for our heating and hot water needs.
Other_exp: It would expand our knowledge of an environmentally sustainable heating method for our home.

Future_exp: Ours is a loveable property, an end of what was once a large country house. Its time to adopt the future and ensure a greener profile for ourselves and future owners too.
Upgrade_exp: Why not, it sounds a super efficient alternative way to provide heating in the 21st century and beyond.
Building_exp: We are currently undertaking investing in our annex to make it an accessible living space for an 85 year old relative. Giving them an independent dwelling, but close enough to be part of our main household too.
Financial_exp: We want to be considered as leading-edge adopters of heating technology, utilising our land, to bring the "green" inside our home.
Technology_exp: There�s a bunch of emerging technologies, that we are keen to adopt to show we�re taking an innovative approach to modern technology and the benefits. Too many times resistance to technological change, or technological inertia, is often considered a negative force in the digital environment.
Research_exp: Excited to work collaboratively with the researchers providing relevant feedback.
Planned_exp: At the moment whilst an attractive proposition the initial outlay makes it challenging to achieve right now.
Replacement_exp: The current heating works ok, but this presents a opportunity to change to a greener future.

Upgrade_exp: Hot water heating is not very effective at present - takes a long time to heat water during colder months
Planned_exp: I had not looked into heat pumps previously
Replacement_exp: Our hot water heating, as mentioned above, is not very efficient. However, otherwise we were going to remain with our current system unless we could upgrade to a more environmentally friendly option.

Future_exp: I am fully aware of the ambitions to move to 100% electric heating by 2025 and would love to pilot technology that can assist in this transition. I installed underfloor heating and have 5 zones already in my home, with the view that it would be perfect to retrofit a heat pump in future, but have not been able to save up the money to do this.
Upgrade_exp: During our 2018 retrofit I installed underfloor heating and have 5 zones already in my home. This was with the view that it would be perfect to retrofit a heat pump in future, but have not been able to save up the money to do this.
Building_exp: I have already future proofed my home with the view to save up and install a Heat Pump.. including Underfloor Heating, separate zones, a new immersion tank, Solar PV, improved insulation and triple glazing.
Financial_exp: The investment to improve the efficiency of my home has meant that I have not been able to save up to go to the final step and install a Heat Pump in my home.
Technology_exp: Im an early adopter and have trialled countless efficiency equipment in the past (Smart Meters, Electric Vehicles, LED lighting..etc). I do this mainly so that I can learn about living with the technology which allows me to promote the technology to residents and other people in the sector.
Research_exp: I am a passionate supporter of research projects. I have taken part in Pilot projects in the past, including Smart meter trials, so am keen to be part of this research to help others.
Planned_exp: Whilst retrofitting the home a few years ago I installed Underfloor heating in the home with a view to install a heat pump at some point in the future.I am really keen to move towards having a heat pump, but this was something that I was planning to save up for and install in a few years.
Replacement_exp: Its unlikely that I will have the finances to replace the equipment in the next few years, so this is an opportunity to bring the retrofit forwards.

Financial_exp: Exploring heat pump and battery options but so far not found options that will pay back the up front investment. It may be that we havent had the right advice yet.
Technology_exp: Keen to be part of helping these new technologies become more mainstream.
Research_exp: Keen to provide lots of feedback to inform how to encourage wider take-up of these technologies.
Planned_exp: Yes but as above, not found a satisfactory solution yet.
Replacement_exp: Boiler and wider system were installed about 6 years ago - not yet in need of replacement.

Future_exp: Our current boiler is, as far as we know, the original bolier so its at least 30 years old.
Upgrade_exp: Having done some quick research, Im keen to try out this unique heating system and hopefully make it become the new normal
Financial_exp: We dont have any savings and were currently in a debt management plan. So this would be a great help
Technology_exp: I have a passion for new technology and being involved in its development
Research_exp: Ive been involved in projects before involving the use of new technology at work and would like to extend that to home life
Replacement_exp: We currently have a very old boiler and our water is heated via an immersion separately.\nThis just seems like a very inefficient way for a system to work but we cant afford to replace it ourselves

Future_exp: The UK is going to have to move away from gas central heating if we are going to stand a chance at hitting our carbon reduction targets. Switching from gas central heating now, will mean we are ahead of the curve.
Upgrade_exp: Our gas combi boiler is very old and nearing the end of its life. We urgently need to think about a replacement option, and would love to move over to a low carbon system, but heat pumps are still prohibitively expensive.
Technology_exp: We work in biological science and engineering sectors, so we are always interested in new emerging technologies. Especially ones that have an environmental benefit.
Research_exp: I work in research, so I know how important it is to do your homework and do a proof of concept study before launching into a big project. This project looks like a great initiative that will test whether heat pump technology is a viable alternative to the gas heating systems that most homes have today.

Future_exp: We know that gas boilers will eventually be banned.
Financial_exp: We wouldnt be able to afford a heat pump system at the moment.

Future_exp: We are making adjustments like running a hybrid car and investing in LED lighting at my husbands workplace.
Upgrade_exp: We looked at pellet boilers but they take up a lot of space.
Technology_exp: My husband has an excellent understanding of how things work and is interested in this.
Research_exp: Sounds like an exciting project we would be proud to take part in.
Planned_exp: This would be ideal if it wasnt so expensive.
Replacement_exp: Our back boiler is original to the house and although it works perfectly it is hideously inefficient from an energy point of view.
Other_exp: We have a 10 year old son and want to make him aware of Greener options and the importance of investing in renewable resources.  Also to protect his future.

Future_exp: Gas will run out eventually and if Im here to see the day, Id like to think that I have a system in place which will be able to continue with just power from electricity.
Upgrade_exp: Ive looked at the possibility of Solar power before, and decided (at the time) against it. Thats not to say in the future when prices come down a bit I wont decide to take it on, but at the moment its just too much for me to afford. :-(
Building_exp: No big work planned, just decorating and a few external adjustments like renewing the gutters and drain pipes - planned for spring sometime.
Financial_exp: Although Im an Osteopath and theoretically I should be earning a decent enough wage, the fact is that my wife isnt working (due to long COVID symptoms affecting her heart) since April and the prospect of her working in the near future is slim. This means that the financial burden of running a house and paying all bills has fallen squarely on me - not complaining, but just giving a reason for being attracted to a newer central heating system free of charge. Id very much appreciate any help you are willing to offer.
Technology_exp: Ive always been interested in newer tech, but as always, it does tend to cost a pretty penny when it first comes out doesnt it, hence I dont have anything like this already. I love to be able to do my bit for the environment as and when possible. I drive a Skoda Fabia 1.0, 3 cylinder car for this very reason.
Research_exp: Id like to know more about what exactly is expected of us in the research, but Ive previously heard good things about this kind of heat pump so am very interested in finding out more about taking part.
Planned_exp: Ive looked at the idea, but have previously been a little put off by the pricing of just changing for the sake of it. We had a new boiler 7 years ago and its been working fine, bar the odd issue and so have been reluctant to change it as it hasnt given up the ghost just yet. If we had more money then Id definitely be looking to change it anyway for a mixture of heat source pumps/energy supplying tech, (solar/ground & air heat sourcing etc).
Replacement_exp: It could always do with an update, but its working fine at the moment, bar the odd issue here and there. It does need the water pressure topping up about once a week during the winter, but the plumber says the boiler is working fine, so unless I need to replace it, then best to just keep an eye on it - thats what we do. Would be nice to replace it though.

Future_exp: Also....I am getting older so need to think carefully about doing changes before physically I can not.
Upgrade_exp: My house being south facing has opportunities for a heat pump.
Building_exp: Over seven years I have been slowly refurbishing the house. Sadly it has proved to be a money pit and retirement looms.
Financial_exp: Retirement in two years and the effect of Covid on my career/work has made me concerned about bills. I live on my own.
Technology_exp: This technology is moving fast. So fast that honestly I have not a clue what can be achieved today.
Research_exp: I am passionate about doing my part to cut my carbon footprint. Just do not know where to start and concerned about financial outlay at this time of my life...
Planned_exp: Had thought about the technology as I thought my house would be ideal but cost made me put on the back burner (excuse the metaphor!!!)

Future_exp: carbon emitters are most damaging to our environement. really need to take steps to adopt low carbon models and may be even eliminate.
Upgrade_exp: i have heard about the heat pumps, and am really interested in incorporating this into our house.

Future_exp: We understand the urgency of the climate emergency and want to do whatever we can to be part of making the UKs housing fit for the future. Also if it helps reduce our costs and makes the house more attractive to buyers in future that would of course be great.
Upgrade_exp: We are very interested in heat pumps but would otherwise not be looking to upgrade our heating system while its still functioning.
Planned_exp: Its something were interested in for the future, but dont have the cash for any time soon.

Future_exp: I had looked at air source heat pumps for when our boiler is no longer viable
Upgrade_exp: the boiler is 19 years old and i have been looking at whether a heat pump would be a viable alternative when it needs replacing.
Financial_exp: but also to see how cost effective it would be so I can share that with others who may be interested. I am the trustee of a climate change charity in London and do comment on carbon reduction initiatives
Other_exp: I think its important to trial these initiaives in a number of different house types to get real evidence on their effectiveness and cost/benefit to be able to persuade others to move to the technology.

Future_exp: We are interested in heat pumps and solar. We also have a separate pool house and swimming pool. The pool is currently heated from an air source heat pump, we are wondering if this could be powered by solar.\n\nWe have a field behind the pool house that has plenty of room for solar panels, this could support the heating of the pool and also the electric use by the main house.
Financial_exp:
We have a very interesting and nice looking house, this would make a very good case study for you and prove these systems can work in old as well as new houses.

We are also willing to work with you and accept that if it free their maybe some compromises from our side.

We also understand that we might need to do further enhancements on Insualtion and draft proofing, we started this last year.
Technology_exp: Burning circa 5k litres of oil does not feel very environmentally friendly. A heat pump powered by solar would significantly reduce our Carbon footprint.
Research_exp: As stated above, we are keen to work with you and our house would make a good case study. Google Westfield House, Tufton, you will quickly find the particulars, it is a nice looking house for a case study :-)
Planned_exp: We havent formally done anything about this as have had other financial priorities, but every time the boiler is serviced, we are reminded it is near the end of its serviceable life, so need to think about the transition before being forced to install another oil boiler.

Future_exp: Having both Solar types in the past where one worked really well and the other not so, I have see how these new technologies can help. Also have a heat exchanger Air Con unit for my office for the real hot days.
Upgrade_exp: Our boiler is very old and have been told that when it fails it will need replacing, also it uses a lot of gas so costing us a lot.
Building_exp: The last owners of our home have lived here since 1950s and did very little to the house for the past 30 years, I have had to spend a lot on the house which is hidden like new wall ties but this does not help in the efficiency of the house just keeps it up.
Financial_exp: Being a technical person I understand the importance of giving real life examples of systems being used in different situations, most people have given up on the car industry with the fuel figures they quote.
Technology_exp: I have a heat pump air con unit for my home office, as this is the cheapest way to cool my computers in the hot weather, and I have installed both solar types in the past and wish I have the capital to do some of it again.
Research_exp: Throughout my working life I have used cutting edge technology in the Broadcast Television world, and have feed back useful information to suppliers on using their equipment in the real world.
Planned_exp: At the moment I can not afford to change our heating system.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is old and burns a lot of gas and this would be a great solution, to remove gas completely from our house as we use induction for cooking, but the house has gas points for lighting.
Other_exp: We are planning on living in this home for the rest of our lives while bringing up our two children, so Im looking for quality long term products to install into our home that will save us money and help the planet.

Future_exp: We would very much like to update our Heating system to a far more efficient, modern, economical and environmentally friendly system
Upgrade_exp: We have done a fair amount of research into heat pumps & like the concept of being part of the renewable energy revolution which definitely seems to be the way forward. We feel we owe this commitment to our children & generations thereafter.
Financial_exp: We wouldnt be being honest if we denied this fact !
Technology_exp: We are very interested in fully understanding how the technology works & how it impacts the environment.
Research_exp: Were keen to take part as it would mean an opportunity to do our bit as soon as possible. If not selected to take part it is definitely something we would wish to invest in in the future (renewable energy) when the time is right (probably upon retirement). Our current Oil system feels outdated & will certainly need changing/renewing within the next 5 years. Our boiler is nearly 20 years old so will very likely need replacement sooner rather than later.

Future_exp: Gas Boilers are due to be phased out and we would like to support the roll out of new green technologies.
Upgrade_exp: I like the idea of the steady ambient temperature.
Financial_exp: We wouldnt be able to afford the new technologies at this stage otherwise.

Future_exp: Would like to become carbon neutral
Upgrade_exp: If this is the most efficient method
Technology_exp: We use technology in many aspects of our lives and are keen early adopters
Research_exp: We would like to part of a pioneering project as our new build house was not built with modern or Smart technology controls and an efficient heating system.
Other_exp: We believe builders should be shown or made to build more efficient heating systems into new houses. Our house could be a model to show this.

Upgrade_exp: dont have much idea about the heat pump, however keen to explore how it helps reduce the carbon impact.
Financial_exp: Also the fact that it will be a completely different/unique experience to other households comparatively.
Technology_exp: Could share the first hand experience with family and friends.

Future_exp: Green tech is getting more accessible for home owners but until recently we can only �green� out electricity and not our heating.
Upgrade_exp: Friend has just installed heat pump and convinced me to look into it
Financial_exp: Of course! However we are looking to upgrade other aspects of our house to use HIVE or similar to better control how energy is used not just where how it is generated.
Technology_exp: As an engineer I am advising industrial clients on Energy Transition - keen to understand the economics of similar tech for consumers
Research_exp: As above - we need to demonstrate that new tech can affordably reduce carbon footprint. Without good evidence and case studies it is difficult to make the case for better government policies and subsidies - trials like this are hugely important

Future_exp: We both feel like weve been handed a wonderful opportunity to future proof our home from the word go! \nYoull note that the property is not currently insulated. However, were already commissioning a builder to begin the process of fully insulating the entire house in order to complement a renewable heating system and to make certain that it is as effective as possible. Were very keen to bring our home into a green future, whilst still retaining all of its charm and character.
Upgrade_exp: Again, echoing the answers given above - wed very much like to steer away from traditional methods of heating our home in favour of more eco-friendly alternatives. Similarly, we think this is supported by other eco ventures - such as the fact that we have recently leased an electric car in an attempt to reduce our carbon emissions.
Building_exp: Whilst we are undertaking building work in order to insulate our property - the driving force behind this is to ensure that any heating system that is installed is as effective as possible.
Financial_exp: We have to be honest and say that this is a definite yes! As weve recently moved home  - our budget is finding itself typically stretched and were exploring ways in which we can be as eco-friendly as possible, but also stay within our means. This would present a fantastic opportunity for us to be involved in a ground-breaking study whilst also achieving our own eco goals.
Technology_exp: Weve always been keen adopters of new smart-home technologies and will continue to be intrigued by what the market has to offer.
Research_exp: Again, as mentioned above - we both think that this type of research is vital for the future protection of our planet - and ensuring that any eco-friendly alternatives prove as efficient and effective as possible for every home in the UK. It would be a wonderful opportunity for us to be part of this change.

Future_exp: As I am 73 I want to get a really green heating system installed while I am still in good health and enthusiastic. It concerns me that I am burning a fossil fuel and want to have peace of mind for the rest of my life.
Upgrade_exp: I have been researching the options for years and decided some time ago that the Heat Pump was the way to go (although I do love the idea of hydrogen power).
Financial_exp: This will make my wife very happy (and take the pressure off me).
Technology_exp: I was excited and intrigued by the idea of heat pumps many years ago when the only devices were, I think, attached to windows for heating individual rooms.
Research_exp: Just ask my wife how keen I am!
Planned_exp: I had been looking into the costs and thinking seriously about heat pump installation, but the Zero Carbon Trial has made me think that perhaps I can get a system installed sooner (without having to save up first).
Replacement_exp: My boiler is 10 years old so Im not expecting it to last for many more years.

Future_exp: We are keen to be a great example of a low carbon lifestyle and show others how to reduce their carbon footprint for the future. To show that making the switch, means little to no disruption to regular life, but more importantly, can help to reduce our burden on the planet.
Upgrade_exp: We have been in this house for just over a year, as well as it being a relatively old house, we have been keen to find the best possible low-impact upgrade to our E-rated boiler system.
Technology_exp: For several years we have been fascinated with technology that can make life easier, but also less damaging to the environment. Over the last 12 months, we have successfully reduced our electricity bill by incorporating smart technology, including LED lights and other smart appliances as well as an electric car. Which is another reason why we have been fascinated with heat pump technology.
Research_exp: We have scientific/analytical jobs, so we have past experience working on research projects and very keen to get back into any research that can help reduce our energy requirements. Especially if we can help others on their path to a low impact lifestyle.
Planned_exp: We have been looking for a while, however, the high price and unfamiliar technology has meant we have been reluctant to make the jump.
Replacement_exp: As we have an E-rated boiler, getting it replaced with a state-of-the-art new system, has been our top priority since moving in.

Upgrade_exp: Its the future, this house needs a few upgrades and having this would be a massive start.
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt be, but its about getting back to the correct way of approaching the future post COVID.
Technology_exp: It would be amazing to see how easily things could be set to take care of themselves, without the need of fire.
Research_exp: I understand that this will be a part of the set up.
Replacement_exp: We have a recent installation of instant water heater put in, but realise that theres more to do.

Future_exp: Definitely. My boiler is now 11 years old, and while it is very efficient I would like to know how I can future proof  my house.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pumps seem like a viable way to enhance my system without investing in something new
Financial_exp: A free installation is attractive, but Im more interested in learning about how new technology can be used to reduce my families impact on the environment. Should my property not be viable for this tech, I hope that Ill have use of an expert that can tell me how I can improve my homes heating performance to further lower my environmental impact.
Technology_exp: I have started on the journey of new tech, and keen to keep going
Research_exp: If data and knowledge can be used to improve products and services offered to OVO customers, that would be great.
Planned_exp: Im trying to understand if a heat pump viable for my property, Im not quite sold yet. Id like to know more about noise and running costs
Replacement_exp: Im looking to enhance my heating system rather than replace it

Future_exp: I am actively exploring a range of ways in which my house can be future proofed through investment in new low carbon technologies.
Upgrade_exp: While upgrading our heating has not been my most immediate priority, it is something that Id like to do in the short to medium term. This seems like a great opportunity.
Building_exp: The house is something of a project and we have been working on it gradually over the last five years, e.g. by adding insulation and investing in double-glazing as we decorate each room. I am also considering installing some solar panels and an electric car charging point next year, when I am made redundant.
Financial_exp: Obviously this is an attraction, but Im also attracted by the possibility of moving to a technology that will reduce running costs in the longer term.
Technology_exp: My brother recently installed an air source heat pump and I have been fascinated to learn more about it. Im really keen to explore ways in which new technology can actively help to reduce environmental impacts, while still allowing us to live reasonably comfortable lives.
Research_exp: This is a relatively new technology for most people, so Id be excited to be part of a project that helped to make it more familiar, offering a real alternative to more people in the future.
Planned_exp: I dont have a specific plan to change to a heat pump at the moment. As explained above, changing my heating system is something I had thought of as a slightly longer-term objective.
Replacement_exp: My current system works perfectly adequately, so replacement isnt an immediate need.
Other_exp: I am looking at a variety of ways in which I can reduce day to day running costs in the future, at the same time as reducing my environmental impact. So I am looking at solar panels and battery storage for my electricity needs, and have also started investigating grey water recycling systems. This would be a fantastic opportunity to extend that aim to my heating costs.

Future_exp: Yes, always have been always will be :) Really interested to see how we can use technology that alreay exists to reduce our carbon footprint, time shifting, storing and making use of offpeak surplus as well as local microgeneration has to be better than new large new power plants, transmission losses etc.
Upgrade_exp: Our electrisity is now very green, but our gas usage to heat the hosue is not.... very interested in how we could cut this use and dependance!
Building_exp: Getting to the end of that ... but when we did I installed a thermal store to help reduce cycling the boiler and allow it to operated at maximum condencing efficency. This has a solar coil (never used as have Immersun / immersion heater connected to the PV).
Financial_exp: Im only human, who would not be! But I see it as more than that; its being part of something new and on the cutting edge of helping everyone move to a more sustainable future! We need too!!
Technology_exp: I work in IT and have grown up with the rapidly changing technology and how the interent has shrunk the world. Having been an early adpoter of solar, and local microgeneration, Im now looking into how we could use more technology to reduce our carbon impact.
Research_exp: Yes, I love playing with data and have been keenly tracking our solar output over the years. It would be great to be able to be an ambasador and say that we were part of something new and prooving that this is the correct way to go. Ive already got one of our friends to install rain water harvesting after they saw our system.
Planned_exp: Our boiler ahs needed a new contorl board, but otherwise is now 10+ years old ... it will need changing but its a big leap to jump onto new tech thats just starting to proove its self.... what f it was not right its a very big outlay to get wrong on your own!!

Future_exp: I have been sort of looking into this anyway and was arranging a quote for improved loft insulation to start the whole process. My wife and I are both concerned about our impact on the planet, we have moved to an electric vehicle, we have greatly reduced our waste output. we only use renewable electricity and carbon offset our gas. being able to make these sort of changes to our house seemed out of our budget except for the simplest things (e.g. a smart thermostat). this would be really great to have help with. Gas is going to become the next coal and it would be really good to be at the front of that change.
Financial_exp: Of course! who wouldnt. we are relatively new homeowners and the cost is prohibitive to us.
Technology_exp: I have read/watched articles about new heating technologies. I have seen Fully Charged (Youtube channel) videos about some of the tech you are offering. very intrigued.
Research_exp: MY wife and I are both scientists so we understand the benefit of research projects.
Replacement_exp: Gas boiler is only 5 years old. another reason prohibiting us as it isnt at the end of its life, so seems frivolous to replace it.

Sustainability_exp: Reducing our familys carbon footprint is important to us. We have a young toddler and it is imperative that we try and do our best to reduce our impact on the environment by teaching him about all the ways we can achieve this.
Upgrade_exp: Whilst i have no immediate plans to replace my existing heating system it is relatively old (installed with when the house was built in 2005) but is in very good condition. It is however not the most energy efficient heating system nor is it the cleanest. Consequently, i need to consider how much longevity is left with our existing boiler and start to consider alternatives.
Financial_exp: Of course the technology trialled being free is a major draw, anyone that says otherwise isnt telling the truth. Its a massive incentive and one that we are keen to take advantage of if possible.
Technology_exp: I have seen heat pumps on the news recently and along with friends that shared the details of this trial, i certainly see a future in this technology and wish to adopt it if i am able.
Research_exp: I am in favour of any trials that push out wider adoption of low carbon systems, whether that be heating or transport etc
Replacement_exp: Our heating system is relatively old (installed with when the house was built in 2005) but is in very good condition. It is however not the most energy efficient heating system nor is it the cleanest. This is something we are keen to address.

Future_exp: As above really. This is so important for everyones benefit worldwide. In the UK we rely quite heavily on the need for home heating during early spring, late autumn and winter months. Hence a cost effective, non-fossil fuel alternative is extremely important.
Upgrade_exp: I find it fascinating that we are now finding through new technologies, ways of harnessing existing natural, sustainable, energy resources that have always been available to us, but only now are we able to tap their potential.
Financial_exp: Obviously, however I am more motivated by the adoption of a cost effective Green solution for my heating needs, instead of simply, due to age and in due course, simply replacing my existing Gas boiler. Thats not a step forward.
Research_exp: It would be very good to feel I am helping to contribute to research/trials of a new technology in the hope that this could be rolled out over time to become a major contributing factor to mankind being able to reduce his carbon footprint.
Replacement_exp: Due to age of the existing system, this will be required over the coming 2-5yrs.

Future_exp: Anything that will lower my carbon footprint will be an advantage
Financial_exp: The present heating and hot water system in the home is out of date and extremely expensive, particularly for people living on pensions. Anything that can help to reduce the cost will be welcome.
Technology_exp: I welcome any opportunity to adopt the latest technology as this will pass on to other occupiers in the future
Research_exp: I welcome any project that will help improve the carbon footprint of the property and eventually pay a small part in reaching a greener way of living
Replacement_exp: As already mentioned, the existing storage radiators and immersion heater are over 20 years old and no longer efficient. they are in urgent need of updating.

Building_exp: Looking to undertake single storey side extension over next year.

Future_exp: We intend to live in our house for at least the next 20 years and want to ensure we utilize the current technology in the most sensible way so that we do not have to change the technology in 5-7 years time due to it being obsolete. It is very confusing to sift through all the options that are available and understand what the best solution might be.
Upgrade_exp: Our current boiler is very old and we are looking at the option of replacing with an air pump heat system but as our house was built in the late 1960s/early 1970s we are not sure whether the financials stack up. Having done some research we believe in order for the air source heat pump to be effective we would have to invest a huge amount in cavity wall insulation, replace our very old double glazing, replace the radiators with larger units (or install underfloor heating) and ideally fit some solar panels to reduce reliance on electricity supply. As electricity is much more expensive than gas it may end up being more expensive to run an air source heat pump. Also we believe we may need a secondary heater for hot water. We are a family of four with two very sporty children, lots of showers and lots of washing machine cycles and tumble drying. Despite the current government grants it looks like it may be too expensive for us despite our enthusiasm to move to a more sustainable heat source.
Building_exp: We are intending to rewire the house as it is a very old system and add an ensuite bathrooom as well as generally redecorate.
Financial_exp: As mentioned previously we believe that the current grants etc and costs of the system and ongoing electricity price will mean that if we installed an air source heat pump over time we would be financially worse off than replacing with a more modern gas boiler.
Technology_exp: As we intend to stay in the house for the long term we would like to adopt new technology to make it more efficient but struggle to sift through all the various systems and options.
Research_exp: We would like to be involved as we would like to believe that more environmentally friendly options are viable for retrofit.
Planned_exp: As above we have looked at replacing our gas boiler with a heat pump but believe in the long term would still be more expensive.
Replacement_exp: As mentioned above, we need to replace our ageing boiler but are currently looking at the options and were disappointed to learn that a pump system could be more expensive.

Future_exp:
We are purchasing the above property shorlty (sale agreed, completion of sale expected within the next two months) and an old gas fired back-boiler is fitted to the property.

We chose a house with a substantial solar PV installation to reduce our reliance upon the less green aspects of the electricity grid, particularly as electric vehicle owners, but the house continues to be heated with gas, which wed like to avoid. We are keen to explore concepts which either reduce our gas requirement or allow us to stop the gas supply to the house altogether.

The property has sufficient garden space for a GSHP and wed be willing to have one fitted, there are also suitable locations for an ASHP too, as well as space on the roof of the main property for solar water.

We are also keen users of various smart home technologies and would be interested in room by room smart thermostat installations where possible.
Upgrade_exp:
We are purchasing the above property shorlty (sale agreed, completion of sale expected within the next two months) and an old gas fired back-boiler is fitted to the property.

We chose a house with a substantial solar PV installation to reduce our reliance upon the less green aspects of the electricity grid, particularly as electric vehicle owners, but the house continues to be heated with gas, which wed like to avoid. We are keen to explore concepts which either reduce our gas requirement or allow us to stop the gas supply to the house altogether.

The property has sufficient garden space for a GSHP and wed be willing to have one fitted, there are also suitable locations for an ASHP too, as well as space on the roof of the main property for solar water.

We are also keen users of various smart home technologies and would be interested in room by room smart thermostat installations where possible.
Building_exp: We will be carrying out substantial decorating of the property upon completion of sale and moving in, and we see this as an opportunity to have any new pipework fitted such that decoration can be carried out after.
Financial_exp: Without additional financial incentive, with electricity prices and gas prices where they are, the most financial sensible investment is to continue using mains gas to heat the home, possibly with a more efficient boiler. We we hate to burn fossil fuels where we dont have to, but as we are upsizing to this property with a growing family, the financial bottom line (even taking into account RHI) means that we may lose the opportunity to transition to carbon-free heating.
Technology_exp: We are all keen users of a wide variety of technologies and are always willing to experiment with innovations. The home will be smart in most other aspects (lighting, robotic cleaners, smart locks, smart speakers etc) but would like our heating system to match this.
Research_exp: Both my wife and I are from scientific / engineering backgrounds and would be keen to support this project. We would also like to involve our young children in the process so they can learn about the future of carbon-free home heating.
Planned_exp: Only if made cost-efficient with GHG and / or RHI payments and with the right installation.
Replacement_exp: The property currently has an aging back-boiler which we would soon be replacing.

Future_exp: As part of our move to a low carbon house, we have already switched to an electric car with V2G charging and lighting out lighting is now LED lighting.
Upgrade_exp: Our heating system is very old and inefficient.  Our house is also drafty and the house is often cold, even with the heating on.  Our heating bills are more than double that of our previous, modern house.
Building_exp: The original garage was converted into a utility room by previous owners however it is not insulated and so we are planning to bring it up to modern heating and insulation standards.
Financial_exp: I am a keen supporter of government backed trials to improve environmental performance illustrated by the fact that we are on the OVO V2G trial.
Technology_exp: We see the new, greener technology that is being retrofitted to existing housing stock as a real game changer in the UK�s transition to a low carbon economy.
Research_exp: We want to help inform the future roll out of greener heating technologies in the UK by giving useful feedback based on our experiences of systems installed as part of the trial.
Planned_exp: This year we are planning to renovate our utility room, which currently lacks insulation and is where our old gas boiler is located, and so  a change to a heat pump would be ideal.
Replacement_exp: Our gas boiler is old and inefficient (Band D) and our heating controls are very basic - a single analogue thermostat and a basic programmer.

Planned_exp: I need to replace the boiler but hadnt concluded on what way to go.

Future_exp: To reach our targets on climate change everyone of us has to do our bit. If i can help with your help then it goes another little way to achieving these goals.

Future_exp: To add to my above comments, my boiler is 20 years plus old it was in the house when we moved in 20 years ago, it has been very reliable but had a couple of glitches. This trial not only combines having someone find the best heating system for the house but it also taps into the other grants that would make the house more insulated. We already have cavity wall insulation they injected it in the walls years ago, we didnt find this made much difference. Our loft is very insulated apart from the loft hatch, but we are really keen to make any recommended improvements to help us and the environment.
Upgrade_exp: As per above our heating system is 20 years + and the new system should be a air or ground pump. Ive been looking into these systems for years, but again it is the upfront cost and also picking the best supplier.
Financial_exp: I dont have a lump sum to buy a air or ground source air pump even though ive looked into the RHI repayments over 7 years. But apart from the money it was the fact that this is a complete package. So your team will come up with the best heating solution for the house and you have access to the �5000 of improvements grants as well if needed. And the fact that you are monitoring the performance of the system. Im not sure there wont be any cost savings for us based on our gas bills, but it will future proof the house, and hopefully our bills overall wont increase.
Technology_exp: I have been looking at ground and air source heat pumps for a number of years. I know that a air source produces 3x energy and ground 4x energy but at a lower temperature so bigger radiators are required. Im not sure if the garden is big enough to take a ground source pump but ill leave that to the assessors.
Research_exp: I think we need to have more information about heat pumps, ive read lots of reviews but to have a central source of information would be good. Im guessing that i wont be saving on my energy bills from gas to heat pump but it would be good for other people to be able to access that information from these trials.
Planned_exp: I wouldnt have enough money to change to a heat pump so this trial gives me that opportunity.
Replacement_exp: My heating system is 20 years + old. It is working but it had a little glitch 2 days ago, didnt work for a day and then started working again. We already know that it is very difficult to get parts for it now. When it had a glitch a couple of years ago, we were lucky to find parts on e-bay.

Sustainability_exp: We are very keen on investigating the best clean alternatives to oil for out property. We already run 2 electric vehicles and had solar at our last property.

Upgrade_exp: We are not yet sure if ground or air source would be most suitable and would appreciate advice on most sustainable option.

Future_exp: we are really keen to bring our house unto date with the heating and hot water system as it is a mixture of electric heaters and radiators in lots of rooms, and some only have electric heaters so need updating and have a radiator installed back in. All in all replacing it with an air source heat pump will improve the efficiency and heat we can get into the house.
Upgrade_exp: We are really keen to get an air source heat pump fitted, as we find it hard work with the back boiler on the wood burner, so quite often resort to electric heaters in the rooms also, which is difficult and expensive
Building_exp: We are not having any building works done, we just would like an air source heat pump fitted to improve our heating system and bring us upto date.
Financial_exp: It is a very big expense to put the complete heating system in so having some help with the cost would be great
Technology_exp: We love the idea of an air source heat pump, and being able to improve our effect on the environment.
Research_exp: If we can help improve things in the future for us and others with the efficiency of there homes, that would be great
Planned_exp: we have contacted a supplier and made the initial enquiries as we very much think this is the best and most efficient heating system for our house as we are not on mains gas

I would benefit from heating in the bathrooms and the small room since these are currently unheated.

Sustainability_exp: Im always looking for ways to make our carbon footprint smaller, but cost is generally an issue.

Technology_exp: Intrigued, yes, and if it is practical to install in our home and cost effective to run as well as an environmentally friendly way of providing our heating and hot water it is a win/win situation.
Research_exp: Looking at the question below, no I am not already planning the switch, but I am keen to be involved in the research if there is a practical opportunity to do so.
Replacement_exp: I am currently trying to sort out whether to repair our existing system (which is working, but leaking), or replace it. If this can be at least approved and expected to happen reasonably quickly then it would be perfectly timed.

Sustainability_exp: We strongly believe that it is everyones responsibility to actively take opportunities to move to green energy sources. We believe it is our duty to have a renewable energy source to power our home. \nBurning solid and fossil fuels at home bothers us deeply.

Sustainability_exp: Currently have a bulk storage tank, very old back boiler and system

As a household we are committed to reducing our carbon footprint as much as we possibly can. We are constantly looking at ways to do this and feel that a combination of low tech and hi tech solutions is the way forward. The more renewable the solutions, the better.
Future_exp: The upgrading of the UKs housing stock towards being as carbon neutral as is possible. We already source our electrical supply from a 100% renewable supplier but still have to rely on GCH to heat our home. This is not sustainable and we urgently wish to decarbonise our heating system.
Upgrade_exp: We have done some considerable research into different brands of ASHPs (we dont have the room in our garden for Ground Source) and have plenty of space to fit a suitably sized ASHP without impacting any of our neighbours. As it stands, a Daikin pump looks pretty good to us.
Building_exp: ... apart from planning to install more environmentally friendly insulation in our roof space to increase its efficiency. We are currently looking at Steico products as a solution.
Financial_exp: Yes, who wouldnt be, and we do wish to be able to lease closely with the system designers & installers. More importantly we want to be able to feedback information about the efficacy of the system to inform other households as to the very real benefits of this technology.
Technology_exp: I have a degree in Interactive Media and used to teach on a Masters degree course at the London College of Communication. I have an interest in usability issues around software design and the integration of complex physical systems.
Research_exp: As Ive said earlier I am well versed in interactive system design and would welcome this opportunity to contribute to a wider understanding of how the intelligent implementation of technology can impact on all our futures.
Planned_exp: Weve been thinking about this for quite some time and can only see the benefits of installing an ASHP. This initiative is a fantastic opportunity to take the bull by the horns and implement our plans.
Replacement_exp: Our Gas Combi boiler has a 10 year guarantee and would need replacing in 3 years time anyway. We believe that this scheme means we can bring forward our aims to convert to a greener way of living at the earliest opportunity.
Other_exp: There is a sense of urgency in the Climate debate right now. By taking practical action to implement a sustainable heating system we can be part of the change towards a better future.

Sustainability_exp: We are on a green tariff which fits well with our night storage heaters but they are old and insufficient to keep our house warm. We rely on our multi fuel stove which feels regressive. Our entire family understands and takes seriously our environmental responsibilities, particularly the children.
Future_exp: When moving to the house (with no gas central heating) I had always assumed we would install gas central heating at some point. That doesn�t seem the best thing to do now with emerging greener, more future-proof alternatives. I am particularly interested in heat pumps and solar-electrics and integrating that with domestic batteries and my electric car (Nissan Leaf).
Upgrade_exp: I am looking at various options and heat pumps seem the best system for our house. I understand the benefits both environmental and financial (in time) but the high initial capital outlay is difficult.
Building_exp: We will soon be starting a building project to extend our small house to better fit our growing family. It is the obvious time to upgrade our heating system but alongside the costs of a building project, the high initial costs of a heat pump system are a real barrier.
Financial_exp: As previously mentioned, we will soon be starting a building project to extend our small house to better fit our growing family. It is the obvious time to upgrade our heating system but alongside the costs of a building project, the high initial costs of a heat pump system are a real barrier. We would be delighted to receive what is a relatively novel technology (I�ve never lived in a house with it so it does represent a small risk) free of charge.
Technology_exp: I have an engineering background and work in a technical area so new technology always interests me. I have loved changing my motoring habits by switching to an electric car and have installed smart lighting and power controls in my house. I would love to extend this to the heating and electrical supply of my house.
Research_exp: I believe it is vital that we shift our thinking of how we heat and power our homes to tackle the environmental challenges we face. As with electric cars, the large scale uptake of these cars rely on motivated �early adopters�. I would consider us in this category; I�d love to be part of showing people that the technology works and is better than what came before.
Planned_exp: It has been an ambition to change to a heat pump for some time but the high installation cost has so far been a barrier to taking the plunge.
Replacement_exp: You will see from my responses that my current heating system is pretty old and currently not up to the job requiring dirty supplementary heating.

Sustainability_exp: I am very keen to reduce my carbon footprint and am very passionate about climate issues in my job (advertising and marketing)
