Hopefully it will result in technologies and govt policy that will help to reduce the costs for the average income. Otherwise the aspiration of a low carbon domestic housing objective will fail.
Technology_exp: Well yes, in the sense that I understand it is the way forward. A system that  can reduce or obviate carbon emissions is exciting.  But not because Is is new technology , more because it has a direct benefit for the future of our society.
Research_exp: My house is representative of much of the housing stock in this country.  I would be very happy for it to play a part in informing engineers and the public that this technology is viable for old housing stock. Also, I personally would be representative of a demographic that is not always shown as an early adopter of new technology.
Replacement_exp: I would expect that considering the age of my boiler I might be faced with making a decision about its replacement in the next 5 years.

Sustainability_exp: I would really like to reduce our carbon footprint whilst also minimising our use of fossil fuel produced electricity.\n\nI have been looking at renewable sources for a few months and very keen on the technologies you offer.
Future_exp: Our home does not have mains gas, so finding an alternative would fantastic. I am also aware that the national electricity grid is struggling to create sufficient power during peak times.
Upgrade_exp: Ive been investigating heat pumps and really do feel that they are a solution to many heating challenges. We have plenty of land around our home, so we know that installing a heat pump will not disturb any neighbours.\n\nMy daughters are very eco conscience and they would find the heat pump technology fascinating.
Building_exp: I am investigating some modifications to our home, including potentially installing underfloor heating on the ground floor. We will also be replacing our kitchen and redecorating the whole house.
Financial_exp: Government and business support for renewable technology will really help early adopters like me try the new technology. Im happy for my home to be used as a showcase.
Technology_exp: Im always looking for methods improve and optimise our home. Anything that can help the environment and showcase how technology can help everyone in their day to day lives.
Research_exp: Both my wife and myself love to research. If there is anything we can do to assist, you only have to ask.
Planned_exp: We have a water bore hole and Ive been in touch with a company about Ground Heat Pumps. Both Air and Ground heat pumps are technologies I would consider to help with heating our home.
Replacement_exp: I am looking to potentially replace my oil boiler and our home has very large radiators, so a low heat system should work well.
Other_exp: We are planning to start our building work this summer, so a perfect time to install a heat pump.

Upgrade_exp: potentially - it depends on the noise level
Building_exp: hope to put new flooring down and re-do the conservatory soonish and so a new low carbon heating system could work well

Planned_exp: We werent planning on changing but have always liked the idea of being able to change to a more energy efficient system if we had the money to do so.
Replacement_exp: The heating system is old so is in need to replacing anyway. Being more efficient with our replacement would be amazing!

Sustainability_exp: I�ve been considering a more carbon neutral energy sources and have been with sustainable energy companies for sometime.  We are already vegan to reduce our environmental impact and are looking for additional ways to help the planet
Future_exp: Now is the time to make these decisions not just for use, but also for future generations
Upgrade_exp: Our boiler is about 15 years old and is in need of changing
Building_exp: We are due to renew the kitchen which is where the current boiler is situated
Financial_exp: This is an incentive, but we will still be moving forward with some changes.  It just depends whether we can maximise those changes for the better
Technology_exp: I�m technology focused so this is all good
Research_exp: Anything that can benefit learning and improve the option for others to take the decision to move to more green products is a win

Sustainability_exp: I have invested in solar PV and battery storage to reduce my grid electricity consumption and I�d like to address the gas heating system next.
Upgrade_exp: I have been researching air and ground heat pump systems as an alternative source of heating.  Sadly I don�t think my rear garden is big enough to support a ground heat pump as 600 sq m are required as a minimum.
Building_exp: I am currently considering extending my house but have no firm plans in place to do so just now.
Technology_exp: I�m very interested in technology and spend much of my working week on science based projects.

Building_exp: we are planning a new kitchen and at the same likely to fit new boiler (existing one is >20 years old), so would consider this as an alternative
Financial_exp: likely to fit new gas boiler. Would be interested in heat pump as an alternative, but unsure of the tech, and the price looks rather high - if it were free then Id go for it.
Technology_exp: Im always interested to try new tech. that this would also reduce my carbon footprint is appealing.
Planned_exp: actually not a definite No - we do need to replace the old boiler. Without this trial wed likely just fit a new efficient boiler. But could be persuaded to a heat pump with more info - and an attractive price.

Sustainability_exp: my son is always badgering me to be more eco!
Planned_exp: be nice but outlay cost is too high compared to a standard gas boiler.
Replacement_exp: boiler is over 15 years old. be nice to lose the water tank in loft.

Financial_exp: And will work well with the pv system
Replacement_exp: My system doesn�t need to be replaced but the boiler is nearly 10yrs old

Sustainability_exp: I think its important to stop harming the environment and wold like a greener solution to heating my home and sourcing my electricity. I am put off by the significant upfront costs that seem to take man years to recover.
Future_exp: No new gas boilers are to be installed in new builds. Our current boiler is approx 30 years old. Rather than replace with a new gas boiler I would prefer a greener/lower carbon solution.
Financial_exp: The significant upfront cost of installing a heat pump stops this being an option for me, along with the high electricity cost of running the system. If the system was free of charge then it makes sense to do it. I would love to have this in my home and help the environment at the same time.
Replacement_exp: the answer to this question is yes and no. Our system is all fully working but is old. our boiler is around 30 years old therefore probably using more gas than a newer condensing boiler would, therefore i need to be considering options.

Upgrade_exp: older boiler in need of replacement

Sustainability_exp: Looking to get my home carbon neutral through various methods however they are all too expensive for the short term. This house will be our forever home with room to have children
We have 4kW PV , so interested in getting that working with heat pump.
Building_exp: currently have planning application in for a heat pump
Planned_exp: Have planning application submitted for a heat pump

Sustainability_exp: Now we have 3 children, we want to reduce our carbon footprint and teach them about energy saving
Future_exp: We would like to use renewables to heat our home, and remove the gas boiler, and stop using the coal fire
Financial_exp: Yes of couse if it saves us some money

Sustainability_exp: Would like to take green house gasses to 0
Future_exp: There is no gas in my area so would like to have an efficient heating system
Upgrade_exp: I have only heard good things about heat pumps

Sustainability_exp: I installed solar panels 15 years ago and am keen to continue to reduce my environmental impact. I have been researching ASHP and home battery storage.\nMy oil boiler is now at end of life, so it would seem a perfect time to change to an more environmentally friendly solution.
Future_exp: I have been changing the way I use energy and fosil fuels and am keen to use technology to help drive these advancements. I already have a Solar iboost connected to maximise the solar power and reduce carbon on water heating, and see energy efficient heating intelligently controlled as the next big step
Upgrade_exp: ASHP seem to be the future for accessible environmentally friendly
Building_exp: I am due to replace my oil boiler in the next few months, so am planning for the disruption anyway, so it would seem a perfect opportunity
Technology_exp: I have been researching environmental technology and am also considering Solar battery storage along with extending my solar array. i work in the digital sector, so technology has always been of interest both for work and home. IFTTT and advancements in efficient and AI controlled
Replacement_exp: The current heating solution is 15 years old, so needs to be replaced

Sustainability_exp: We are starting from scratch having bought a house with no central heating or radiators, nothing apart from a log burner which is bad for our health and the environment.  It feels like an opportunity to do the right thing and make a greener, more renewable choice for this house and a healthier future for our 3 year old son.
Future_exp: It would be counterintuative to install gas central heating (no gas running to the house currently) when oil/gas are being phased out in the UK.  A heat pump seems like a good investment for safer, environmentally concious energy. I think it would be an enormous asset to the property
Upgrade_exp: We currently have a log burner and 2 small oil radiators that the previous owners left in the house for us.  A heat pump would be an incredible upgrade for us in a home without central heating!
Financial_exp: We had hoped to install a heat pump to solve our central heating issue (lack of) but it has been a difficult time for us after my partner lost all of his work last March due to the pandemic (he is a musician).  We are living on one income at the moment and this scheme would be life changing for us
Technology_exp: My sister lives in Norway and has an air pump system in their house.  Weve always been intrigued and impressed by the system and how well it functions in cold temperatures.  It seemed like the logical step for us when we started to research our options for installing heating.  We have experienced many an old unreliable gas boiler in previous homes and would relish the opportunity to use new technology and see how it performs
Research_exp: We would be very happy to take part in the research project.  Renewable energy is so important and it feels like the UK is very much behind in this field particularly compared to Scandinavia.  We would be happy to do whatever we can to test and promote the technology
Planned_exp: This would give us an opportunity to go ahead with our dream to get a heat pump that would be out of our reach financially right now without some support from a scheme like this.
Replacement_exp: We dont currently have central heating so not quite a replacement as such
Other_exp: Only to add that its really, really cold right now without central heating and we would hugely appreciate being considered for this trial so we can make a warm and comfortable home for our son.  Thank you for your time

Sustainability_exp: I have spent 40 years in H&V research and would like to walk the talk I�ve been making for all that time
Future_exp: Gas is clearly going to become less viable, hydrogen may come on stream but not likely in the next decade.
Upgrade_exp: There is little more I can do to reduce losses. A lower carbon supply is the only next logical option.
Financial_exp: Frankly I�m not convinced that the new system will be similar in cost to run. It makes little sense to inject personal capital on unproven heatpump options.
Technology_exp: I am familiar with the technologies suggested.
Research_exp: We need successful independent demonstrators to convince a sceptical public to adopt non-gas solutions.
Planned_exp: As explained I am not convinced of the economics and payback potential
Replacement_exp: Boiler is fairly new and most radiators have been replaced in the past 5 years.

Upgrade_exp: Were interested in a heat pump as we work from home, and understand that heat pumps are a way of providing heat throughout the day.
Building_exp: We have an older boiler in an awkward location so we would like to get rid of it and replace with an environmentally friendly alternative.
Financial_exp: The house needs a lot of work so anything that can save us some money would be much appreciated!
Technology_exp: The optimisation of electricity usage sounds interesting and might help to reduce future energy usage.
Research_exp: I work in a university so Im really aware of the importance of data and research, so Id be happy to participate in research that might contribute to a greener future.
Planned_exp: Weve had some quotes but are still considering options.

Sustainability_exp: I have recently bought this bungalow and (eventually) I would like to convert it to an eco house which is fully self-sustainable with groundsource heat pump powered by solar, also rainwater harvesting. I have the outside space to accommodate such items. As we are new to the property we are still investigatiing the cavity wall insulation but we are intending to make it fully insulated to help with a low temperature heating system.
Future_exp: Our boiler is quite old and we do not wish to replace it with another carbon fuel system especially as they will be obsolete in the coming years - not to mention the detrimental environmental impact of oil (we do not have mains gas)
Upgrade_exp: Ideally we would like to have underfloor heating and groundsource heat pump. We are prepared to make some internal alterations to accommodate a plant room for this equipment, and we have ample land to accommodate the coils.
Building_exp: We will be upgrading our bungalow to an eco-friendly house.
Financial_exp: We have looked into RHI scheme, but the initial outlay is still cost prohibitive
Technology_exp: I have done a lot a research and believe this to be the way forward for everyone. However, when I speak to my friends about this I am shocked at how many of them have never heard of it. I think having it installed myself is the only way for them to experience it in order for it to catch on more widely.
Research_exp: I would love to get involved and spread the work. Most people dont know this is a viable alternative.
Planned_exp: I am planning to in the future definitely. However, at the present time it is cost prohibitive for us.
Replacement_exp: The boiler is old, so we probably only have another couple of years out of it.

Sustainability_exp: Thermal insulation, ashp, PV and EV charging
Building_exp: Opportunity to upgrade thermal insulation and heating, PV and EV charging
Other_exp: We are about to refurb and extend our house

Sustainability_exp: Im very keen to see options for local generation, storage and more efficient heating systems.
Future_exp: I love the idea of local generation and storage, as well as reducing the total energy needs of my home. For this reason I installed a smart heating system so we only heat the rooms in use.
Upgrade_exp: It surprises me how little uptake there has been for heat pumps in the UK, particularly ground source ones. Id be happy to install one at home to reduce the energy needs.
Financial_exp: This sounds amazing!!! Im interested in this approach even at cost, but to be a part of the trial for free would be fantastic.
Technology_exp: Im an engineer and love tinkering with new technologies. we have a suite of smart controlled items at home including the heating control system, lighting and cameras, and would be happy to add to this!
Research_exp: Partaking in research to make this more available to others in the future sounds great to me.
Planned_exp: my heating system works at the moment so I would leave it running as-is to reduce the waste until it needs replacing, however I would be happy to switch it out to be involved in this scheme.

Sustainability_exp: I am keen to see what is possible in terms of retrofitting and heating a large old Victorian house, which is mainly stock and then heat it, ideally without a gas boiler. Im interested in how we best achieve net carbon zero through retrofit and what we can do to drive this change through the pre war housing stock.
Future_exp: Im keen to adopt low carbon technology. However, like all technologies, they will adapt and improve quickly. Were at the beginning of that curve, so it feels likely that mainly technologies (possibly heat-pumps) will improve their efficiency as volume increases
Upgrade_exp: I want to explore the extent to which it is possible to heat a large Victorian house either entirely or mostly via a heat pump and the changes e.g. insulation which might be needed in conjunction to see measurable and viable improvements in energy consumption
Building_exp: I have no major building work planned, but would be prepared to explore what might be needed to insulate the house to improve viability of using heat pumps.
Financial_exp: Of course, receiving a grant is beneficial, but I am committed to this stuff and would want to work with your partners to make it a success.
Technology_exp: I know a reasonable amount about the technologies, but not sure the extent to which things like ground source might be viable. We have a decent sized back garden (100ft plus), so that might be an option.
Research_exp: Id love to be involved and support the project. Im passionate about how we make the shift towards net zero and specifically how we crack the challenge of heating old housing stock in and efficient way.
Planned_exp: I have been looking at the green homes grant, but have no firm plans at the moment.
Replacement_exp: My existing BAXI boiler is about ten years old but has an annual service and maintenance package and, at present, there is no reason to dispense with it.

Sustainability_exp: We are wanting to reduce our carbon footprint by externally insulating our house, getting solar panels on the small bit of roof which is south facing, moving to an electric car. We are vegetarian, and do not eat any products which contain palm oil. We buy organic veg and fruit and recycle as much as we can. Having an air source heat pump would be our next step to reducing our impact on the world.

We are currently renovating our home and to make it as green as possible. We are planning to install an air source pump, solar panels and rainwater harvesting as this will be our long term home (we hope for the next 30 or 40 plus years!). We want to leave the planet in a better place than it is now!
Future_exp: We want to reduce our reliance on fossil fuels. We already use green electricity suppliers to provide our electricity but want to take this further.  We have friends who have used them in their house and have seen how successful they can be.
Upgrade_exp: The boiler is approx 13 years old. We do not want to replace this with a new gas boiler as this is outdated and want to be green. we have already investigated air source heat pump and have checked feasibility with a government accredited supplier and we know that it will work well in the house.
Building_exp: We have plans in place to renovate the house and remove the gas supply from the house and use the air source instead. We have planning permission for some works to be done including building a green home office/spare room at our house.   This would also include a shower ensuite.
Financial_exp: If we are able to obtain the system free of charge it would mean we would be able to bring forward some of our other green ideas such as water harvesting and solar panels to build on really greening our home. We would be happy to be a spokesperson /advocate for green technology to encourage others to go down this route as a way of reducing climate change.
Technology_exp: Our boiler is currently outdated and does not offer much flexibility with our heating system. It is inefficient.  With new technology we would be able to control the heat pump in a much more sophisticated way to maximise its use.
Research_exp: Heat pumps are not very well understood and needs significant promotion to improve uptake. If by being in this research project demonstrates how heat pumps are cost effective and green, it would assist with initiatives as greening new builds, social housing, public buildings retrofitting older properties to make real longer term changes in reducing fossil fuels.   We would be more than willing to  to do all the data recording required to ensure that the results can be demonstrated from the project.
Planned_exp: We have already received a quote for the heat pump and have applied for the Government green grant launched in the wake of covid 19.  We were told by the green grant helpline that the scheme doesnt really get heat pumps and no decisions are being made on them!.  We are not holding out much hope that we will receive a voucher for the heat pump. We would love to become greener and would really like to take advantage of your scheme to make our dream a reality.
Replacement_exp: as per above our boiler is 13 years old and whilst it is still working, it is not very efficient and needs replacing in due course.  we want to invest in our family future and ensure any replacements are good for us and the planet!

Sustainability_exp: We already have two electric cars, solar panels and domestic battery storage and we are keen to reduce our carbon footprint as far as possible. We are on the Tesla Energy Plan provided by Octopus. We would like to stop burning gas to heat our home.
Future_exp: Just about all of the money that we have spent on our home since moving here in 2004 has gone towards improving its heating efficiency and reducing carbon footprint. They have been long-term investments.
Upgrade_exp: Our existing boiler is 11 years old and working well but we still feel uncomfortable with burning stuff to keep warm.
Financial_exp: Mainly because our boiler is very reliable and it might seem wasteful to replace it with an air source heat pump before the end of its life.
Technology_exp: We bought our first fully electric car in January 2016 and between us, my wife and I have covered 72,000 miles in full battery electric cars. We do not have internal combustion engine devices in our household, nor do we have a wood burner.
Research_exp: So much of the UKs Co2 generation comes from home heating and changing this situation will be slow and difficult and the process will need a lot of support and good publicity.
Planned_exp: If our gas boiler was old, unreliable and at the end of its life then it would be an easy decision to fit an expensive heat pump conversion.

Sustainability_exp: I am very mindful of the damage each household causes on the environment and would like to mitigate this with advise and guidance on how I can make a difference for future generations.
Future_exp: We plan to stay in this property long term. Although the house is old, we want to protect the original elements while embracing new innovate technologies to help the house still be a successful and ideally low carbon home for many years to come.
Upgrade_exp: We are keen to test new innovations which benefits the environment, minimises future environmental damage, whilst creating a warm and cosy home. Sometimes it can be scary to try very new technologies independently, so the opportunity to test while fully supported by experts is an invaluable opportunity we would love to be a part of.
Building_exp: We have just purchased this property and are aware it is dated and needs love, time and effort to create a perfect home that is fit for purpose for the 21st century.
Financial_exp: This property was above our price range, but we fell in love with the house and want now to do justice to the property. Any money we do not spend by the provision of a heat source pump etc, will be used on other environmentally friendly options where possible. However, we would love to be able to give this lovely house a reason to shine and be involved in such a fantastic opportunity and hopefully be able to make a real difference to new and retro fit heating systems for the future.
Technology_exp: We have been keen to be involved and adopt new technologies to support a more environmentally friendly way of life for a few years and regularly visit the ideal home show and grand designs
Research_exp: We would love to be involved in a project such as this and believe it would be a fascinating and rewarding experience. To be a pioneer in new types of heating that would truly changes for reduce the way we take precious resources from our beautiful planet would be a privilege.
Planned_exp: This is not something we have considered in our property due to its age, however if this is possible and can be demonstrated successfully by this pilot, I am sure it would encourage many more households to seriously consider this option for the future.
Replacement_exp: Our current heating system is old though currently still in working order. The opportunity to upgrade this and be part of a pilot to demonstrate the heat source effectiveness and installation process to customers for future heating options, that can truly change the way we utilise our limited natural resources eg gas currently would be wonderful.
Other_exp: This is a truly amazing opportunity and thanks to OVO for the work they already do to protect the planet and offer renewable energy! We would love to be involved in this pilot. It would be a privilege to demonstrate we can all make a difference in how we live in our homes and bring them on a journey to the 21st century. We have 3 grandchildren who would find the whole experience fascinating. Also our son in law (to be) who has a degree as a civil engineer, specialising in renewable energies. Our village is historical and beautiful and residents try hard to maintain the character. It would be a privilege to demonstrate heat pumps can become a realistic, feasible and cost effective way to heat older properties, whilst retaining character and truly making a difference to our planet for future generations to come.

Upgrade_exp: A heat pump is a possible solution. Although we have outside space I�m not sure it is large enough for a heat pump

Replacement_exp: I�m not too keen on having oil due to the impact it has on the earth

Sustainability_exp: As conservationist I very aware of climate change and would like to do my bit to help the planet.
Future_exp: I used to have a back boiler and upgraded it to a combi one. I had my roof replaced and insulated. There are 4 sash windows that are single glazed and I am not able to double glaze them because I need to take out the windows to bring furniture in. But I have paid someone to insulate them as best as possible.
Upgrade_exp: I read that heat pumps are very efficient and are being installed in new homes.
Financial_exp: As a pensioner anything that can reduce my environmental impact free of charge is good news!
Technology_exp: I would like to know more about this technology
Research_exp: If my home is suitable I would like to take part in this research project.
Replacement_exp: My combi boiler is 10 years old but works well but a replacement would be welcome if it could save me money.

Sustainability_exp: We have recently purchased the property, and plan on renovating to add a Groundsource heat pump along with air source and solar PV. We are an eco-focussed family and own an EV car along with a PHEV car. We would like to revamp the property and make it as eco-friendly as possible as itll be our now forever family home.
Upgrade_exp: Yes- theres also space in the garden for ground source.
Building_exp: We will be planning major renovation works in 2022, as were expecting a baby this year.
Financial_exp: We plan on doing this anyway, however it would be great to be a shining case study for this project as we plan on also adding Solar PV, other heat pump, EV charging, etc.
Replacement_exp: We would like to reduce the gas consumption, as this is not renewable, and the heat-pump coupled with solar PV means we can run off-grid.

Sustainability_exp: We have been looking at reducing our carbon footprint and now cycle more and buy local food, without plastic packaging where possible. Wed like to improve our homes impact on the environment.
Future_exp: I think that this technology is likely to be necessary soon and as our boiler is old Id like to replace it with newer technology so that it doesnt need replacing again in a short time.
Financial_exp: At the moment the technology is very expensive and we would not save much if anything on heating bills so cost us a factor.
Research_exp: If we are going to get to net zero then household heating is a key part of this. Im therefore interested in taking part in a trial to consider how this can be introduced more widely.
Replacement_exp: Its working fine at the moment but is old and will likely need replacing soon.

Sustainability_exp: I want to explore how deep a retrofit is possible on a flat like mine. I know from work that 85% of the properties that need to be imrpvioed to meet net zero are already here, so this isnt a marginal wish. I have a platform to share the benefits and the process through my work social media and want to help galvanise more action so not (Only) selfish. I came across this through Kayla Ente who i interview for my podcast last year. The main other thing i want to do is reduce loss associated with the the original glazing. Ive begun improving the wall and under floor insulation on a room by room basis. Being more systematic about the retrofit coordination would be fantastic.
Building_exp: In the sense of ongoing improvements
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt be. Its about making the whole process affordable, thinking about the ways this enables other things to be pulled forward.

Sustainability_exp: We have recently moved into the house and are looking to extend and modify it, adding more insulation, updating the inefficient heating system and introducing some renewable power
Future_exp: The house is a 1960s dormer bungalow with narrow double glazing in some areas and little insulation in the eaves. We are looking to improve the insulation, replace the double glazing , introduce under floor heating and change the open fire to a modern wood burner.
Upgrade_exp: We would like to add an ASHP but believe we also need a gas boiler as back up particularly for radiators in the bedrooms and hot water.
Building_exp: The house is a 1960s dormer bungalow with narrow double glazing in some areas and little insulation in the eaves. We are looking to improve the insulation, replace the double glazing , introduce under floor heating and change the open fire to a modern wood burner.
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt say yes to this but actually we would be happy to take part if it gave us access to advice and part financial contribution.
Technology_exp: As above, we are very keen to do whatever we can afford. We are keen on new technology especially if it reduces our carbon footprint.
Research_exp: Working with a research project gives access to advice and the latest ideas.
Planned_exp: As above. Our heating system needs replacing so it seems silly to not look at low carbon sources.

Sustainability_exp: For future generations - I have children and grandchildren and I am concerned about global warming
Future_exp: I am aware the government want people to install renewable energy as a way of heating their homes and hot water and not be reliant on fossil fuels
Financial_exp: This is helpful as I have retired
Technology_exp: I understand new homes are being built with this type of system
Planned_exp: I saw the information on the OVO website and thought it was a good incentive to upgrade my outdated system to a renewable energy one
Replacement_exp: I have recently moved and the system requires upgrading

Sustainability_exp: I want to reduce my carbon footprint and reliance on gas. Ive switched one car to EV, and want to move the house to smart as much as possible and cut out fossil fuel use.
Future_exp: We have a typical average 3 bed semi and would be good to show whats possible for everyone.
Upgrade_exp: Heat pump is the most logical way forward for the average house. Ground source requires a big garden or a community solution which doesnt work for existing houses.
Building_exp: We have no structural changes planned to the house, only some internal refresh/decoration
Financial_exp: Taking part in the trial is a financial advantage, but not essential. Ive been looking into heat pumps as part of my overall ambition to change the way we heat our house.
Technology_exp: Changing the house to smart and only using heating when really needed is the biggest part of reducing carbon footprint. Stopping from heating rooms and the home when not in use.
Research_exp: Very happy to be part of this and helping out to find a way for all homes to switch to reduce carbon footprint, especially when ours is an average house and a good candidate to show what is possible for all.
Planned_exp: I have looked at heat pumps, and want to swap, but our boiler isnt on "its last legs". I saw this trial as a way to make the switch sooner and also be part of finding a solution for all homes.
Replacement_exp: As above, our current heating system works and is 13yrs old, but I want to cut our reliance on fossil fuels.

Upgrade_exp: We installed an efficient gas system when we last upgraded
Building_exp: Ground floor has already been upgraded, likely to convert the loft in the next couple of years, which will give an additional 3 bedrooms and 1 bathroom.\n\nCurrent system was specified with this in mind.

Sustainability_exp: I think of myself as a bit of a "tree hugger"! I am genuinely concerned about what we are doing to the planet and I am always looking for ways to reduce my impact on the planet.
Future_exp: This is not a priority for me.
Upgrade_exp: I am not currently looking to upgrade but I do want to reduce my carbon emissions.
Building_exp: No building works being undertaken but I do understand that any change to the heating system will result in some disruption.
Financial_exp: This is not a priority for me. I will be looking to change my current boiler to something more green when it needs replacing.
Technology_exp: Particularly if it reduces my carbon footprint and shows other people what can be done with an older style house.
Research_exp: Yes. As above. Reducing our carbon footprint is important to me and my family. Im also keen to show that the green technology can be brought into a house like mine.
Planned_exp: Yes but it wouldnt be until my current boiler needs replacing.
Replacement_exp: My boiler is still relatively new.
Other_exp: Im keen to support any business or operation showcasing green technology.

Sustainability_exp: Im very keen to do what I can to reduce our environmental impact and move to a green solution. Weve taken the first steps in handing in our petrol cars and buying an EV (VW e-golf), and I want to go further reduce the impact of our home living. A lot of my current work is about reducing carbon emissions on the national grid. I was the creator of www.carbonintensity.org.uk which is about showing when it is greenest to run your electrical appliances and know many systems like this use its data to plan usage. I would love the opportunity to take part in the trial and show that the green solution is the way forward. Our gas boiler is exceptionally old and ive been desperate to go down the route of a heat pump to remove gas from our house.
Future_exp: We see this house as our forever home and would love to future proof it with low carbon technology so we can reduce our impact on the environment.
Upgrade_exp: I want to make our house low carbon, and see removing gas as a way to do this. I dont want to upgrade to another gas boiler, as were keen to reduce our reliance on gas move to low carbon options. I was researching heat pumps, both ground and air, and feel more comfortable that this would be a far better solution that keeping on with gas boilers, considering our goals of lessening our impact on the environment.
Financial_exp: We feel that this house has a lot of potential in terms of energy efficiency savings, it could be improved dramatically. However doing all these works requires a lot of financial investment, this would be a route to fast track our goals of reducing our carbon impact.
Technology_exp: Weve always been keen to try new technologies which can have a positive impact on the environment. Weve taken the leap to EVs early, and would love the opportunity to take on other new technologies to reduce our emissions and impact.
Research_exp: Happy to support the project and take part in whatever is required.
Replacement_exp: Our heating systems works fine, though weve explored replacing the boiler. However this has only been new gas boilers and weve been keen to look at heat pumps, however this requires a higher financial investment and specific companies to fit them.

Future_exp: Keen to adopt low carbon technology
Financial_exp: interested to be involved in trials of new technology
Research_exp: Forward thinking like to be involved in research regarding new technology

Sustainability_exp: Im and energy assessor so keen to know the benefits and know ASHPs can work on some properties

We have just bought a project house, moved in yesterday, it�s a beautiful old lock cottage on the grand union canal and we will be installing wooden double glazing ans renovating the house to a high standard over the next few years. We are looking to be here for at least 10 years and what to make our long term home as energy efficient and environmentally neutral as an hold house can be.
Future_exp: We want to blend the charm of the house house with as many energy efficient technologies to create a home which holds uk history but functions as a modern family home. We want to become as self sustainable as possible by growing our own vegetables, keeping a few chickens reducing our environmental impact as much as possible.
Upgrade_exp: Currently we are on a LPG tank and pay extra for partially bio gas through calore. Whilst I have put that some of the property is subject to flooding. The majority of the house and garden are not subject to flooding and the ground floor cellars make a safe and dry location for any required plant.
Building_exp: Over the next 10s we hope to of completely rejuvenated this house from making the old cellars into the main house kitchen, dining and utility room to retailing the roof. Whole time we will be keeping to grade two listed regulations as keeping to the river and canal trusts visual restrictions.
Financial_exp: We are a young couple who have have strived for the most we can afford. My partner has year breast cancer last year at 30 and so we have decided to grab life by the horns, not worry about money but make every day as good as it can be. We want to embrace life and do things right by the property and ourselves. We want to go full green on our energy but it will have to be a many years before we can afford to make the upgrade. This scheme will allows us to reach a more sustainable life more quickly
Technology_exp: Ground source heat pump has is a very interesting system due to its low energy consumption. It�s clear that the world needs to invest in low energy systems if we are going to maintain a future inline with our current climate.
Research_exp: As a research project I would be very keen to participate. A civil engineer by education means I have a basic understanding of many engineering item and at the end of the phone would be able to take readings and systematically monitor the system. What�s more with no children, a failure of the system even in a cold winter would allow us to rap up warm and not put the warmth of young children on the line. We hope to install a log burner over the next year which will again mean that a failure of the system would be tolerable for us.
Planned_exp: I have not yet looked into the options available to us here but will be looking to upgrade our system as some point in the near future.
Replacement_exp: Yes and no. The system is fine and the boiler is fairly new but I will be looking to switch to a system that can be considered more sustainable in the near future.
Other_exp: I want this house to be as sustainable and as mordent as possible to mix the old with the new and this house has the space and charm to be a great model off house even old properties can achieve fantastic environmental sustainability.

Sustainability_exp: As an environmental consultant, its the right thing to do.
I am concerned about climate change and wish to reduce our carbon footprint.
Future_exp: I believe that the use of gas boilers will be phased out soon.
Financial_exp: The cost of a heat pump is an obstacle to fitting one.
Technology_exp: I am studying carbon management for a postgraduate degree.
Research_exp: I would be interested in engaging in a project towards the net zero target of the UK.

Sustainability_exp: Ive wanted to transition away from gas for years, but never been in a position to do so.
Future_exp: Definitely. Gas is on the way out and installing a new gas boiler now feels like a poor decision.
Upgrade_exp: I have an old gas boiler so replacement needs to happen sometime. I dont want to replace it with a gas boiler!
Building_exp: No major refurbishment, other than the replacement of radiators.
Financial_exp: Who wouldnt be! These systems are still out of my affordability and the significant upfront cost required.
Technology_exp: Very much so! Im a big fan of smart home technologies and feel there are fascinating opportunities to be had in the next decade.
Research_exp: Without a doubt. As someone with a research background I would be very keen to help as much as possible :)
Planned_exp: I really want to do it, but still see it as something I could afford to do in ~ 4 years.\n\nIve had quotes before and know my house is suitable for a system.
Replacement_exp: The boiler is 20+ years old, and the radiators are not in optimal locations, so both are in scope to be replaced.

Sustainability_exp: This is my main interest here. Updating our heating, water and insulation is probably our no. 1 way of reducing our family�s carbon footprint, followed by a move to an electric car.
Upgrade_exp: Our boiler is 15+ years old and our heating system will eventually need replacing. In recognising this I�d like to proactively consider any other low carbon ways of doing this.
Building_exp: We are planning to replace/ renew our kitchen/ utility rooms in the next 2 years, which is where our existing boiler is located, so making changes to our heating system at the same time makes good sense.
Financial_exp: Yes that appeals but it is not the sole driver here.
Planned_exp: I�d consider a heat pump but I really don�t know enough about the technology.

Sustainability_exp: I am Co-Chair of a local environment group, Greening Steyning, and were are actively campaigning to cut emissions locally.  I plan on using the heat pump installation as a case study to share with others locally.  see: www.greeningsteyning.org
Future_exp: We have already done a major retrofit job on the house to improve insulation levels.  Installing a heat pump is the next step.
Upgrade_exp: We already have a relatively new gas condensing boiler, so were starting from a reasonably efficient base.
Technology_exp: Though I wouldnt say we are very techy.  Its important that the new system is intuitive to use.
Research_exp: I come from a research background having worked at the Univ of Sussex so would be happy to engage.

Other_exp: Reduce the country/worlds carbon emissions. I already produce all our electricity needs from solar.

Replacement_exp: My property has never had central heating.

Technology_exp: We already have solar PV for 6 years
Replacement_exp: We want to go off the gas grid

Sustainability_exp: Clean energy improtant. Want to stop using gas for heating. We want to future proof the house for future generations and reduce our carbon footprint. Partly motivated by mitigating the inter generational divide- todays young people didnt cause the climate crisis but theyre the ones wholl have to live with consequences and pay for it.
Building_exp: We are getting cavity wall insulation and replacing old single pane windows with double glazed windows. We are building a kitchen extension and a loft conversion which will include high standards of insulation and ventilation.
Replacement_exp: WE have an old Potterton boiler. Its very inefficient. We feel like we are heating the street.
Other_exp: We found a heating engineer we had confidence in to fit an air source heat pump well in our home.

Sustainability_exp: I have been looking at renewal heating options for some but ground source heat pumps are quite expensive
Future_exp: I have been looking at renewal heating options for some but ground source heat pumps are quite expensive. The air source heat pump seems like a good option for me
Upgrade_exp: I have been looking at renewal heating options for some but ground source heat pumps are quite expensive. If the system could work with some of the existing radiators that would be great
Building_exp: I am making a change to my property including solar panels so this would be an ideal time to do the work
Financial_exp: I have been looking at renewal heating options for some but ground source heat pumps are quite expensive the fact that this is free would allow me to move towards zero-carbon living
Technology_exp: I have been looking at renewables for some time but the options have been expensive. I also like the fact there integration with the phones
Research_exp: Im quite excited about this technology because i am interested in renewable especially heat pumps and solar so would love to contribute
Planned_exp: I was planning to do this at some stage in the next couple of years so the timing is good
Replacement_exp: My boiler has had a few problems so was looking to replace it rather than keep repairing it

Sustainability_exp: We realise how the impact of climate change is already causing disasters across the world and feel that we need to drastically reduce our carbon footprint and encourage others to do the same.
Future_exp: We want to switch to low carbon technology as soon as possible so that we can demonstrate how successful it can be.
Upgrade_exp: We want to upgrade in the sense that we want a cleaner, greener energy source.
Financial_exp: We have recently retired so provision of the system free of charge is very attractive to us and will also allow us to invest in solar panels at the same time.
Technology_exp: We are part of Seaford Environmental Alliance which is a registered charity which promotes awareness of green alternative technologies and lifestyles to the local community.
Research_exp: We feel the relatively little is know about how heating and energy contribute to our carbon footprint, and how alternative forms of energy are now very viable.
Planned_exp: We have been thinking about changing to a heat pump for a couple of years following on from our own research about how we can mot effectively cut our carbon footprint.
Other_exp: We feel that we need to do everything we can to reduce our carbon footprint.  We have adopted mainly plant based diets, switched to ethical banking, adopted more active travel and this is the next big step we need to take.

Sustainability_exp: Our oil boiler is old, inefficient and above all omitting large volumes of CO2 it is a top priority for us to reduce our carbon implant of the world.
Future_exp: Like to be an early adopter
Upgrade_exp: I these are the only realistic heating options for us in this rural off Gas grid setting
Financial_exp: Yes it would be a lie to say otherwise but other than that I�m intrigued to see how OVO�s trial can support evidence to promote wider change.
Technology_exp: Yes would love to see how this new technology can help reduce our environmental impact.
Research_exp: Haha. Sorry pretty much as stated above!! Else really need to take individual responsibility for our own impacts. And support and promote development of wider systems that do so.
Planned_exp: Yes this is a timely opportunity as our oil boiler is very old and inefficient.

Upgrade_exp: I am looking to replace my current heating system with a low carbon alternative
Financial_exp: Of course, although we were planning to have an ASHP installed anyway and have an application pending with the Green Homes Grant Scheme

Sustainability_exp: Currently our system is very old and in-efficient so it has a larger environmental and economical impact.
Future_exp: If possible I would like to future proof as I intend to have a loft conversion so would need a system with capacity to do so.

Sustainability_exp: Ive worked in the renewables sector since 2006.  It has been my passion to further the impact of renewable energy - and energy saving as a source of tackling climate change. - I used to put together B2B conferences and I think I arranged for Stephen Fitzpatrick to  come and speak at one or two. I currently work for Ovesco - community energy in Lewes and Community Energy South an umbrella organisation that supports communities to set up their own community owned renewables project. Currently my electricity supplier is currently Octopus energy. I definitely want to get this house off the coal fired Rayburn, which I have rarely used since I moved in, in February.  My house is south facing and ideally I would like to get some pv panels on the roof too.  There is some solar thermal on the roof so not a huge amount of room.
Future_exp: I have always wanted to "green" my home, but previously was unable to do so as I lived in a conservation area, and now it is easier.  The house has double glazed windows and cavity wall insulation but needs insulation in the roof.  Before moving in I even went to look at Beattie passivsystems retrofit in Peterborough, but unfortunately the cost of that system for retrofitting a house is prohibitive for ordinary people.
Upgrade_exp: When I moved in I knew I had to do something about the coal fired Rayburn and I have been looking at installing either a wood heating system or an air source heat pump.  Many of my neighbours heat their homes with oil or wood as we are off the gas grid and I know that others would be interested to see how the air source heat pump works as I think I would be the first in the cup de sac to have one.  Two houses have pv on the roof, so there is clearly interest.
Building_exp: The house is a project.  The electrics look ancient as is the Rayburn.  I need to, re-wire, install a kitchen, replace carpets, quite probably replace some of the ceilings, paint - basically everything.
Financial_exp: Air Source Heat pumps are expensive to install and given the amount of work I need to get done on this house, getting a system provided free of charge would be an amazing help!
Technology_exp: Ive long worked in the industry and never been able to install eco technologies myself.  Part of the reason I took on this house was to make it as eco as I could afford to do.  If I can save money on the heating, I might be able to install some pv panels - or do something about recycling water.
Research_exp: I am on the outskirts of Barcombe village where Ovesco are doing a project to roadmap how to get that village off oil.  I know that there are people in this village who would be interested to replicate that project.  Part of my job is running webinars for the Community energy sector - and people often phone Ovesco to ask for advice, it would be great to be able to give my personal experience of the things people need to think about.  Also I just love innovation and looking at how we can improve things. So I would be very happy to liaise with Ovo and their partners to share data collection etc.,
Planned_exp: As I said above, the house is currently heated by a coal fired Rayburn which is very smokey and inefficient.  I dont like to use it as it makes me cough, so it has been pretty cold and uncomfortable here.   I was initially going to install a pellet boiler, but there are difficulties with the chimney and flue so I have been looking into an air source heat pump.  Even though the RHI offsets the price it does not do so up-front so the cost of installing one will impact on what else I can do to this house.
Replacement_exp: See above - the hot water cylinder would probably need to be moved Currently there are only 4 radiators in the house. On the side of the house farthest from the Rayburn.  None in the rooms above the Rayburn which suggests that the previous residents found the heat from the Rayburn made those upstairs rooms warm enough.  In my opinion those rooms have been pretty cold.

Sustainability_exp: We are installing solar to power the heat pump and underfloor heating to part of the house to increase efficiency.
Upgrade_exp: We previously received a quotation to install a heat pump but it was more than we can afford at present.
Building_exp: We are in the process of building a single storey extension to provide wet room facilities and a downstairs bedroom due to my mobility and upgrading all double glazing to triple glazing to reduce our emissions, however we had already started this work prior to signing up to the scheme.
Financial_exp: We had received a quote to install a heat pump in early 2020 but financially we were unable to proceed due to budgetary limitations.
Technology_exp: I am very excited about the technology and seeing how it works in the real world as opposed to reviews on YouTube etc.  We are keen viewers of the Fully Charged show on YouTube.
Research_exp: 100% I am a very keen environmentalist and have hated relying on natural gas to heat our home and water.
Planned_exp: We are unable to afford a heat pump.

Sustainability_exp: I am very concerned about the climate crisis and want to play my part in doing something about it by moving to sustainable heating.
Future_exp: We are all electric and I want to move to low carbon technology - I do not want to install gas or any other fossil fuel-dependent system.
Upgrade_exp: Our electricity bill is currently over �3000 a year and a heat pump will save us a significant amount of money.
Financial_exp: Our bills and outgoings are high and it will be very helpful to have the system free of charge. We will need to pay for radiators to be installed, so any savings we can make will be significant for us.
Technology_exp: The technology looks fascinating and I like the idea of installing a cutting-edge system into our 1930s bungalow.
Research_exp: I am happy to support anything that will encourage more people to take up low carbon technologies. As a scientist I am also keen to help with research projects.
Planned_exp: I have looked into this and a heat pump is my technology of choice. Solar panels will not provide enough energy for us.
Replacement_exp: We have got electric heaters but they are very expensive and the cost is proving unusustainable for us.
Other_exp: This questionnaire has covered all my reasons really well!

Sustainability_exp: We have solar panels and an electric car already, we want to take the next stp to reduce the environmental impact of our property.
Upgrade_exp: Our current combi boiler is working fine, we believe heat pump technology is a way to reduce the carbon footprint of our property
Financial_exp: So far as were aware, we will be making a financial contribution to this.

Sustainability_exp: Weve recently moved to this house which needs a new heating system and would much rather install a greener system than gas (which it currently has)
Upgrade_exp: We have a very ancient gas boiler which will need replacing shortly we are sure.
Building_exp: We are due to re-configure the kitchen where the current gas boiler is stored, so the heating system needs to be moved.
Technology_exp: Moving away from fossil fuel seems like an inevitable necessity and we are keen to do this sooner rather than later. As the whole property needs a cosmetic overhaul as well as some reconfiguration, now seems the right time to get a new heating system installed which is up-to-date technology that can hopefully last us many years.
Research_exp: Its so important how we can move forward with reducing the carbon footprint of the majority of the UKs houses and seeing the reality of retrofitting heat pumps is important step towards this
Planned_exp: We have been looking into these already
